{"pageid": 4, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation11_for_edx/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation11_for_edx-tab4", "text": "When designing a suspension system, engineers typically fix the value of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega \\,[/mathjaxinline] at a value that reflects the typical road conditions that the car will encounter. The engineers then choose the parameters [mathjaxinline]\\, k\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, b\\,[/mathjaxinline] to ensure that the vehicle will not be in resonance with bumps in the road under normal conditions. For example, if [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega \\,[/mathjaxinline] is fixed at 2, it is obvious that choosing [mathjaxinline]\\, k=4\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, b=1\\,[/mathjaxinline] would be a bad choice as the car would be in resonance under these conditions.    We have only touched upon a few of the interesting properties of the response of this driven oscillator. Continue playing with the mathlet so that you fully understand the behavior of the system.    For example, can you find the values of [mathjaxinline]b,\\, k,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega \\,[/mathjaxinline] that produce the largest possible gain in this mathlet? {"pageid": 5, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation7_for_edx/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation7_for_edx-tab6", "text": "![A cross section of the boat submerged in water and tilted by an angle theta. The force of gravity points vertically downward from the center of mass of the boat, which lies along the center axis. There is a force of buoyancy that is equal and opposite this force at the center of buoyancy, which lies in the center of mass of the displaced water, which lies at a point to the right of the central axis. Both of these forces are labeled as having length W. The distance between the center of gravity and center of buoyancy is r. The angle between r and the vertical position is phi.](/static/images/u1c3s2_r7_boattorque.svg)   An unaligned pair of equal and opposite forces creating a torque   [mathjaxinline]\\phi >0\\,[/mathjaxinline] if the center of buoyancy is to the **right** (in water's frame) of the center of gravity   [mathjaxinline]\\phi < 0\\,[/mathjaxinline] if the center of buoyancy is to the **left** (in water's frame) of the center of gravity        Having found the coordinates of the new center of buoyancy, we can now compute the torque [mathjaxinline]\\tau[/mathjaxinline] exerted on the boat:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tau[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle - W d_2 \\qquad \\text{where}\\, \\, d_2\\colon =r\\sin \\phi .[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.86)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Here, [mathjaxinline]\\, W\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the weight of the boat, and [mathjaxinline]\\, d_2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] as shown in the figure above, is the (signed) length of the **lever arm** . The negative sign is present because if [mathjaxinline]\\, d_2>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] meaning the center of buoyancy [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(B_x(\\theta )\\, B_y(\\theta )\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is to the right of the center of gravity, the torque will rotate the boat in the [mathjaxinline]-\\theta[/mathjaxinline]-direction (counterclockwise in our convention).    As seen in the figure above, the lever arm [mathjaxinline]\\, d_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] depends on the locations of both the center of gravity and the center of buoyancy. Hence, it depends on the various boat parameters and is also a function of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta .\\,[/mathjaxinline]    The sign of [mathjaxinline]\\, d_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] is very important. It corresponds to whether the center of buoyancy is to the right or left of the center of gravity (in the water's frame) when the boat is rotated away from the flat position. This determines the direction of the torque and in particular whether the boat will rotate further away or back to the flat position. The expression for [mathjaxinline]\\, d_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] in terms of the boat parameters will give us guidelines to design a boat that will not capsize immediately.    ###  Finding the lever arm and the formula for the torque  It remains to find[mathjaxinline]\\, d_2[/mathjaxinline] as a function of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta \\,[/mathjaxinline] and other parameters of the boat.    ![A cross section of the boat submerged in water and tilted by an angle theta. The force of gravity points vertically downward from the center of mass of the boat, which lies along the center axis. There is a force of buoyancy that is equal and opposite this force at the center of buoyancy, which lies in the center of mass of the displaced water, which lies at a point to the right of the central axis. Both of these forces are labeled as having length W. The distance between the center of gravity and center of buoyancy is r. The angle between r and the vertical position is phi.](/static/images/u1c3s2_r7_boattorquewithlabels.svg)    Projecting the vector connecting [mathjaxinline]\\vec{B}\\left(0\\right)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\vec{B}\\left(\\theta \\right)[/mathjaxinline] onto a unit vector parallel to the waterline gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle d_{1}+d_{2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(B_{x}\\left(\\theta \\right),B_{y}\\left(\\theta \\right)-B_{y}\\left(0\\right)\\right)\\cdot \\left(\\mbox{cos}\\left(\\theta \\right),\\mbox{sin}\\left(\\theta \\right)\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{b^{3}}{12A}\\mbox{sin}\\left(\\theta \\right)+\\frac{b^{3}}{24A}\\mbox{tan}^{2}\\left(\\theta \\right)\\mbox{sin}\\left(\\theta \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{b^{3}}{12A}\\left(1+\\frac{1}{2}\\mbox{tan}^{2}\\left(\\theta \\right)\\right)\\mbox{sin}\\left(\\theta \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      But  [mathjax]d_{1}=\\left(G_{y}-B_{y}\\left(0\\right)\\right)\\mbox{sin}\\left(\\theta \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore,  [mathjax]d_{2}=\\left(\\frac{b^{3}}{12A}\\left(1+\\frac{1}{2}\\mbox{tan}^{2}\\left(\\theta \\right)\\right)-\\left(G_{y}-B_{y}\\left(0\\right)\\right)\\right)\\mbox{sin}\\left(\\theta \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This gives the torque [mathjaxinline]\\, \\tau =-Wd_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] to be  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tau[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -W\\left(\\frac{b^{3}}{12A}\\left(1+\\frac{1}{2}\\mbox{tan}^{2}\\left(\\theta \\right)\\right)-\\left(G_{y}-B_{y}\\left(0\\right)\\right)\\right)\\mbox{sin}\\left(\\theta \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      For [mathjaxinline]\\theta <<1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] expanding [mathjaxinline]\\tan \\theta[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\theta[/mathjaxinline] about [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta =0\\,[/mathjaxinline] gives the linear approximation  [mathjax]\\tau \\sim -W\\left(\\frac{b^{3}}{12A}-\\left(G_{y}-B_{y}\\left(0\\right)\\right)\\right)\\theta \\qquad (\\theta <<1).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\tau \\sim -k\\theta \\,[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]k>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] i.e. the boat has a **stable equilibrium** at the flat position, if  [mathjax]\\, \\displaystyle \\frac{b^3}{12A}-\\left(G_{y}-B_{y}(0)\\right)>0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  The torque", "filename": "recitation7_for_edx-tab6-text1.html", "title": "The {"pageid": 7, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@04_complexexponential/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@04_complexexponential-tab9", "text": "The same method shows that the [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}}}[/mathjaxinline] **roots of unity** (the solutions to [mathjaxinline]z^n=1[/mathjaxinline]) are the numbers [mathjaxinline]e^{i \\left( \\frac{2\\pi k}{n} \\right)}[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]k=0,1,2,\\ldots ,n-1[/mathjaxinline]. Taking [mathjaxinline]k=1[/mathjaxinline] gives the number [mathjaxinline]\\zeta \\colon =e^{2 \\pi i/n}[/mathjaxinline]. In terms of [mathjaxinline]\\zeta[/mathjaxinline], the complete list of [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] roots of unity is  [mathjax]1, \\; \\zeta , \\; \\zeta ^2, \\; \\ldots , \\; \\zeta ^{n-1}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (after that they start to repeat: [mathjaxinline]\\zeta ^n=1[/mathjaxinline]).  This shows there are [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] complex [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]-th roots of unity. Geometrically, they all lie on the unit circle in the complex plane. Each root has the form [mathjaxinline]e^{i\\theta }[/mathjaxinline], which has absolute value 1. The roots are evenly spaced around the unit circle, starting with the root [mathjaxinline]z=1[/mathjaxinline], and the angle between two consecutive roots is [mathjaxinline]2\\pi /n[/mathjaxinline]. These facts are illustrated for the case [mathjaxinline]n=6[/mathjaxinline] in the figure below.  ![ ](/static/images/6th-roots.svg)   **Figure :** The six solutions to the equation [mathjaxinline]z^6 = 1[/mathjaxinline] lie on a unit circle in the complex plane.      Roots of unity", "filename": "04_complexexponential-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Roots of unity"}

{"pageid": 8, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab2", "text": "First order (nonlinear) equations can be written in the **standard form:**    [mathjax]y' = f(x,y)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]f\\, (x,y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a function of the two variables [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, y[/mathjaxinline].    Notice we now have two standard forms for first order differential equations. Recall first order **linear** equations can also be written in the standard form for linear equations:  [mathjax]y'+p(x)y=q(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---          This unit is concerned with first order **nonlinear** differential equations, such as the one boxed in blue in the video:  [mathjax]y'=x-y^2.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The sad fact is that we can hardly ever find formulas for the solutions to nonlinear DEs. Instead we try to understand the qualitative behavior of solutions using geometric methods or approximations.  Introduction", "filename": "28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Introduction"}

{"pageid": 9, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab9", "text": "Let us now use the characteristic polynomial to solve the DE that we started with in this lecture, the one that models a spring-mass system with no dashpot:  [mathjax]\\ddot{y} + y = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]r^2+1[/mathjaxinline], which factors as [mathjaxinline](r-i)(r+i)[/mathjaxinline]. Its roots are [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-i[/mathjaxinline]. Thus, the exponential solutions  [mathjax]{\\color{orange}{e^{it}, e^{-it}\\; \\text{form a basis for the collection of all solutions}}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Since the coefficients of the DE are real (the DE models a real life situation), the real and imaginary parts of [mathjaxinline]e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] (or equivalently of [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{-it}\\,[/mathjaxinline])  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathrm{Re\\, }(e^{it})[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos (t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.87)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Im\\, }(e^{it})[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sin (t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.88)      are two real solutions to the DE. These are linearly independent and so  [mathjax]{\\color{orange}{\\cos t, \\sin t\\; \\text{form {another} basis for the same collection of all solutions}}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The general **real** solution is all (real) linear combinations of these two real basis functions:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle y(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1 \\cos t + c_2 \\sin t, \\qquad \\text{where}\\, \\, c_1,c_2 \\in \\mathbb {R}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.89)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This is the same as we have guessed from experience in the beginning, without using the characteristic polynomial.     **Question 9.1**  The general solution given by the exponential solutions [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{it}\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{-it}\\,[/mathjaxinline] corresponding to the roots of the characteristic polynomial is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C_1 e^{it} + C_2 e^{-it}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.90)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      However, this is complex since [mathjaxinline]e^{\\pm it}[/mathjaxinline] are complex. Can the real solutions we found above, [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1 \\cos t + c_2 \\sin t,\\,[/mathjaxinline] be obtained from this general complex solution?   **Answer:**   Yes.   Since the roots [mathjaxinline]\\, i\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, -i\\,[/mathjaxinline] of the characteristic polynomial are complex conjugates of one another, the exponential solutions [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{it}\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{-it}\\,[/mathjaxinline] corresponding to these roots are also complex conjugate of one another. Now, recall that the real and imaginary parts of any complex function [mathjaxinline]\\, z\\,[/mathjaxinline] can be obtained by linear combinations, with complex coefficients, of [mathjaxinline]\\, z\\,[/mathjaxinline] and its conjugate [mathjaxinline]\\, \\bar{z}:[/mathjaxinline]  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Re\\, }(z) \\, =\\, \\frac{z+\\bar{z}}{2}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ;[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Im\\, }(z)\\, =\\, \\frac{z-\\bar{z}}{2i}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.91)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Applying these formulas to our example, we have:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\cos t \\, =\\, \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(e^{it}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{e^{it}+e^{-it}}{2}\\,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.92)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sin t \\, =\\, \\mathrm{Im\\, }\\left(e^{it}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{e^{it}-e^{-it}}{2i}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.93)      (This is Euler's formula backwards.) To get the general real solution, we take linear combinations of the expressions on the right above for [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos (t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\sin (t)[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore, the real solutions can be written as [mathjaxinline]\\, C_1 e^{it} + C_2 e^{-it},\\,[/mathjaxinline] provided that the coefficients [mathjaxinline]\\, C_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, C_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] can take complex values.  **Question 9.2** Which basis should be used?  ###  Answer  It depends:    * The basis [mathjaxinline]e^{-it}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] is easier to calculate with, but we need to be careful which linear combinations of these functions are real-valued.     * The basis [mathjaxinline]\\cos t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\sin t[/mathjaxinline] consisting of **real-valued** functions is useful for interpreting solutions in a physical system.   So convert back and forth as necessary.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Undamped system revisited", "filename": "06_higherorderlinearodes-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Undamped system revisited"}

{"pageid": 13, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation7_for_edx/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation7_for_edx-tab3", "text": "![A sketch of the cross-section of a boat is represented as approximately a rounded rectangle. The boat is tilting in the clockwise direction and forms an angle theta with the horizontal axis.](/static/images/u1c3s2_boatintro.svg)   Cross section of a boat and the rotation angle [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta[/mathjaxinline]      As explained in the video, the rotational motion of a boat rocking sideways close to its flat equilibrium position is described by the linear approximation of the rotational version of Newton's second law:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle I \\ddot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tau (\\theta ) \\qquad \\text{where} \\, \\tau (\\theta )\\, \\text{is the torque}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.74)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sim[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -k \\theta \\qquad \\text{where }\\, k>0, \\, \\theta <<1,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.75)      where [mathjaxinline]\\, I\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the **moment of inertia** of the boat, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\tau \\,[/mathjaxinline] is the **torque** exerted on the boat, and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta \\,[/mathjaxinline] is the rotation angle as show in the figure above.    The moment of inertia and how the torque depends on [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] are determined by the geometry and distribution of mass of the boat.    (Here, we are referring to (the component of) the moment of inertia and (the component of ) torque relevant to the sideways rocking of the boat\u2013rotation along an axis parallel the long side of the boat.) {"pageid": 14, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab4", "text": "In this course we'll focus on polynomial differential operators with constant coefficients, that is operators of the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P\\left(D\\right)=a_nD^n+a_{n-1}D^{n-1}+\\dots a_1D+a_0,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      where all of the coefficients [mathjaxinline]a_k[/mathjaxinline] are numbers (as opposed to functions of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]). All operators of this form are linear. In addition to being linear operators, they are also **time-invariant** operators, which means:  If [mathjaxinline]x\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] solves [mathjaxinline]P\\left(D\\right)x=f\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]y\\left(t\\right)=x\\left(t-t_0\\right)[/mathjaxinline] solves [mathjaxinline]P\\left(D\\right)y=f\\left(t-t_0\\right)[/mathjaxinline].      In words, this says that \u201cdelaying the input signal [mathjaxinline]f\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]t_{0}[/mathjaxinline] seconds delays the output signal [mathjaxinline]x\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]t_{0}[/mathjaxinline] seconds.\" If we know that [mathjaxinline]x\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to [mathjaxinline]P\\left(D\\right)x=f\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline], we can solve [mathjaxinline]P\\left(D\\right)y=f\\left(t-t_{0}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] by replacing [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]t-t_{0}[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]x\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline]. This is a useful property because it gives us the solutions to many differential equations for free.  A system that can be modeled using a linear time invariant operator is called an **LTI (linear time invariant)** system.  **Example 4.1** The function [mathjaxinline]x(t) = \\sin (t)[/mathjaxinline] solves the differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\dot x = \\cos t[/mathjaxinline].  What is a solution to the differential equation  [mathjax]\\dot y = \\cos (t +\\pi /2) ?[/mathjax]|   ---|---      By time-invariance, one solution is [mathjaxinline]y=\\sin (t+\\pi /2)[/mathjaxinline].  Note that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos (t +\\pi /2)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.1)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos t \\cos \\pi /2 - \\sin t\\sin \\pi /2[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.2)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\sin t[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.3)      And  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sin (t +\\pi /2)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.4)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sin t \\cos \\pi /2 + \\cos t\\sin \\pi /2[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.5)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos t[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.6)       **Example 4.2** Consider the differential equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}+x=\\cos t.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Variation of parameters or integrating factors tells us that the general solution to this differential equation is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x\\left(t\\right)=\\frac12\\cos t + \\frac12 \\sin t+c_1e^{-t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Now suppose that we want to solve the equation [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}+y=\\sin t[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]\\sin t=\\cos \\left(t-\\pi /2\\right)[/mathjaxinline], time invariance tells us that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =x\\left(t-\\frac{\\pi }{2}\\right)=\\frac12\\cos \\left(t-\\pi /2\\right) + \\frac12 \\sin \\left(t-\\pi /2\\right)+c_1e^{-\\left(t-\\pi /2\\right)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\frac12\\sin \\left(t\\right) - \\frac12 \\cos \\left(t\\right)+\\underbrace{c_1e^{\\pi /2}}_{\\textrm{call this }c_{2}}e^{-t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\frac12\\sin \\left(t\\right) - \\frac12 \\cos \\left(t\\right)+c_2e^{-t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      should solve [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}+y=\\sin t[/mathjaxinline]. This agrees with the solution we'd get if we had used variation of parameters or integrating factors, but we had to do almost no work to get this solution from the first.  ![An LTI system is represented by a rectangle. When the function f of t is the input, the output is x of t. When the function f of t minus t sub 0, the output is x of t minus t sub 0.](/static/images/LTI.svg)  Time Invariance", "filename": "09_exponentialresponse-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Time Invariance"}

{"pageid": 16, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab15", "text": "Using separation of variables (in the homogeneous case) and variation of parameters (in the inhomogeneous case), we showed that every first-order linear ODE has a [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]-parameter family of solutions. To nail down a specific solution in this family, we need one initial condition, such as [mathjaxinline]y(0)[/mathjaxinline].  You may wonder if there are other solutions. Here is a general result which says that there aren't and confirms that our methods find all the solutions.  **Existence and uniqueness theorem for a linear ODE.** Let [mathjaxinline]p(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]q(t)[/mathjaxinline] be continuous functions on an open interval [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline]. Let [mathjaxinline]a \\in I[/mathjaxinline], and let [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] be a given number. Then there **exists** a **unique** solution defined on the entire interval [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline] to the first order linear ODE  [mathjax]\\dot y + p(t) \\, y = q(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      satisfying the initial condition  [mathjax]y(a)=b.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Existence** means that there is **at least** one solution.  **Uniqueness** means that there is **only** one solution.  Existence and uniqueness of solutions", "filename": "02_solvingafirstorderode-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Existence and uniqueness of solutions"}

{"pageid": 17, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab3", "text": "The general principle behind the problem you just solved is that any linear combination of cosine and sine  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t)=c_1\\cos (t)+c_2\\sin (t)\\qquad (c_1, c_2 \\, \\, \\text{any real numbers}),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.67)   ---|---|---|---      is a solution to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\ddot x+x =0[/mathjaxinline]. This is a consequence of the superposition principle for **linear homogeneous** differential equations.     **Superposition for linear homogeneous differential equations:**    The solutions to a homogeneous linear second order ODE,  [mathjax]p_2(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\ddot y}} + p_1(t){\\color{blue}{\\dot y}} + p_0(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = 0 ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      or more generally, the solutions to a linear homogeneous order [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] equation  [mathjax]p_n(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + p_{n-1}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n-1)}}} + \\cdots + p_0(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      have the following properties:    1. The zero function [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] is a solution.     2. Multiplying any one solution by a scalar gives another solution.     3. Adding any two solutions gives another solution.   In summary,  > **all linear combinations of homogeneous solutions are homogeneous > solutions.**   >  This is why homogeneous linear ODEs are so nice. If you know some solutions, you can form linear combinations to build new solutions, with no extra work. We will use it over and over again in applications throughout the course.  Later on, we'll see that the list of properties above means that the collection of all homogeneous solutions forms what is known as a _vector space_.    Superposition for homogeneous solutions", "filename": "06_higherorderlinearodes-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Superposition for homogeneous solutions"}

{"pageid": 18, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab6", "text": "We can use **complex replacement** to solve any ODE of the form  [mathjax]P(D)x = e^{at}\\cos (\\omega t -\\phi ).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Let us see how by working through an example.  **Example 6.1** Find a solution to [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x} + 2x = e^{-t}\\cos (3t - \\phi )[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]\\phi[/mathjaxinline] is a real number.  **Solution:**    1. Replace the right hand side with a complex exponential:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{-t}e^{i3 t - i\\phi }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{-i\\phi }e^{(-1+3i)t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      The complexified equation is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\ddot{z} + 2z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = e^{-i\\phi }e^{(-1+3i)t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---     2. Apply ERF. The characteristic polynomial is   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P(r)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle r^2+2,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.22)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P(-1+3i)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (-1+3i)^2 + 2 = -6-6i,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.23)      and the complex solution is  [mathjax]z_p = \\frac{e^{-i\\phi }e^{(-1+3i)t}}{-6 - 6i}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      A solution to the original problem is then [mathjaxinline]x_p = \\mathrm{Re\\, }(z_p)[/mathjaxinline]. The solution involves a sinusoid. Polar form is the most convenient for this problem, so we put the denominator in polar form:  [mathjax]-6 - 6i = 6\\sqrt{2}e^{-i3\\pi /4}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z_p[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{e^{-i\\phi }e^{(-1+3i)t}}{-6 - 6i} = \\frac1{6\\sqrt{2}}e^{-i\\phi +i3\\pi /4}e^{(-1+3i)t},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.24)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      and  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_p[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Re\\, }(z_p)= \\frac1{6\\sqrt{2}}e^{-t}\\cos (3t-\\phi + 3\\pi /4).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.25)   ---|---|---|---|---|---    Damped sinusoidal inputs", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Damped sinusoidal inputs"}

To rewrite the DE in terms of [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline], substitute [mathjaxinline]y=1/u[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y} = -\\dot{u}/u^2[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac{\\dot{u}}{u^2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{1}{u^2} -t[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{u}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -1 + t u^2.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      This is equivalent to the original DE, but now, when [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] is large, [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] is small, and Euler's method can be used to find the time when [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] crosses [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], which is when [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] blows up. {"pageid": 31, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab8", "text": "### Case 2: Two distinct complex roots   **Example 8.1** Suppose that the equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot y + A\\dot y + By = 0\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]A,\\, B[/mathjaxinline] are real, has characteristic roots [mathjaxinline]a \\pm ib[/mathjaxinline]. Give the general **real** solution.  **Solution:** Since the roots of characteristic polynomial are [mathjaxinline]a\\pm ib,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the two complex exponentials [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{(a+ib)t},\\, e^{(a-ib) t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] form a basis of the collection of all solutions. Now, because all the coefficients in the DE (and in the characteristic polynomial) are **real** , the real and imaginary parts of either exponential solution,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Re\\, }(e^{(a+ib)t})[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{at} \\mathrm{Re\\, }(e^{+ibt})[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{at}\\cos (bt)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.81)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Im\\, }(e^{(a+ib)t})[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{at} \\mathrm{Im\\, }(e^{+ibt})[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{at}\\sin (bt),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.82)      are also solutions to the DE. (Check that yourselves!) These two solutions are **real** and linearly independents, and give the general real solution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1e^{at}\\cos (bt) + c_2 e^{at}\\sin (bt)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.83)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline] are arbitrary real numbers.  Below are the graphs of the two functions [mathjaxinline]e^{at} \\cos (bt)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]e^{at} \\sin (bt)[/mathjaxinline] when [mathjaxinline]a<0[/mathjaxinline]:  ![The function starts at a positive y value in the y versus t plane. The function first decreases, then oscillates about the horizontal axis t equals 0. The amplitude of the function decreases as t increases, bounded by the functions e to the a t and minus e to the a t.](/static/images/u1c2s3_expcos.svg)| ![The function starts at the origin in the y versus t plane. The function first increases ,then oscillates about the horizontal axis t equals 0. The amplitude of the function decreases as t increases, bounded by the functions e to the a t and minus e to the a t.](/static/images/u1c2s3_expsin.svg)   ---|---   Graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{at}\\cos (bt)\\,[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]\\, a<0[/mathjaxinline] |  Graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{at}\\sin (bt)\\,[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]\\, a<0[/mathjaxinline]      In the next lecture, we will study these in more detail. We all also find that the graphs of linear combinations of these look very similar.  ###  Why are the real and imaginary parts of a complex solution also solutions?  If [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)=u(t)+iv(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to a second order homogenous linear DE with **real** coefficients:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{y} + A\\dot{y}+By[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0\\qquad \\text{where}\\, \\, A,\\, B\\, \\text{real}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.84)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Then plugging [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] into the equation, we have  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{(u+iv)} + A\\dot{(u+iv)}+B(u+iv)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.85)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\underbrace{ \\left( \\ddot u+A \\dot u+ Bu\\right)}_{\\text{real}} +\\underbrace{i \\left( \\ddot v+A \\dot v+ Bv\\right)}_{\\text{imaginary}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.86)      Since the coefficients [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline] are **real** , the real and imaginary parts of left hand side of this DE are respectively enclosed in the two brackets above, and therefore both [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v[/mathjaxinline] are solutions to the original DE. Note that it is crucial in this last step that all coefficients of the DE are **real**.    **Remark:** The same reasoning would work even if [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline] vary with the independent variable [mathjaxinline]t.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Also, analogous reasoning works for higher order linear homogeneous DEs with real coefficients. {"pageid": 32, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@01_odeintro/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@01_odeintro-tab9", "text": "**Example 9.1** I have a savings account earning interest compounded daily, and I make frequent deposits or withdrawals into the account. Find an ODE with initial condition to model the balance.  **Simplifying assumptions:**    * Daily compounding is almost the same as continuous compounding, so let's assume that interest is paid continuously instead of at the end of each day.     * Similarly, let's assume that my deposits/withdrawals are frequent enough that they can be approximated by a continuous money flow at a certain rate, the **net deposit rate** (which is negative when I am withdrawing).   **Variables and functions (with units):** Define the following:  [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] |  the initial amount that the account starts with ([mathjaxinline]\\text{dollars}[/mathjaxinline])   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] |  time from the start ([mathjaxinline]\\text{years}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] |  balance ([mathjaxinline]\\text{dollars}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline] |  the interest rate ([mathjaxinline]\\text{year}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]; for example [mathjaxinline]4\\% /\\text{year}=0.04\\, \\text{year}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]q[/mathjaxinline] |  the net deposit rate ([mathjaxinline]\\text{dollars}/\\text{year}[/mathjaxinline]).      Here [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is the independent variable, [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] is a constant, and [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]q[/mathjaxinline] are functions of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].  **Equations:** Now we want to decide how the balance changes as time changes. We'll estimate the change in the balance [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] as time increases from some time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] to a time [mathjaxinline]t+\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline]. We can approximate the interest earned per dollar to be:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{interest earned }{\\color{orange}{\\text{per dollar}}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle I(t) \\, \\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      The balance in the account at time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]x(t).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Therefore, the total interest earned from time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]t+\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] is approximately  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{total interest earned}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle I(t) x(t) \\, \\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Meanwhile money is put into the account at a rate [mathjaxinline]q(t)[/mathjaxinline], so  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{net amount deposited into the account}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q(t) \\, \\Delta t.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Putting it all together, the change in balance is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle I(t) x(t) \\, \\Delta t + q(t) \\, \\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\implies \\frac{\\Delta x}{\\Delta t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle I(t) x(t) + q(t).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The smaller [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] is, the better the approximation becomes, and in the limit as [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t\\rightarrow 0[/mathjaxinline]  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lim \\limits _{\\Delta t\\rightarrow 0}\\frac{\\Delta x}{\\Delta t}=\\frac{dx}{dt}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      This yields the **differential equation**  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dx}{dt}=I(t)x(t)+q(t).[/mathjaxinline] | |   ---|---|---|---      Note that the units in each of the three terms are [mathjaxinline]\\text{dollars}/\\text{year}[/mathjaxinline]. Also, there is the initial condition [mathjaxinline]x(0)=P[/mathjaxinline]. Thus we have an ODE with initial condition:  [mathjax]\\dot{x} = I(t) x + q(t),\\qquad x(0)=P.[/mathjax]| (2.7)   ---|---      Now that the modeling is done, the next step might be to **solve** this DE, but we won't do that yet.  **Remark 9.2** The notation we chose suggested that the interest rate [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline] depended only on time. However, [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline] could have depended on [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] as well. This would not change the modeling process. If [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline] does not depend on [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], we obtain a linear differential equation. If it does, the equation is nonlinear.  A Savings Account", "filename": "01_odeintro-tab9-text1.html", "title": "A Savings Account"}

Variation of parameters.     2. {"pageid": 36, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab12", "text": "**Example 12.1** Solve the [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x + 5\\dot x + 4x = 0[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Worked Solution  The characteristic equation is [mathjaxinline]r^2 + 5r + 4 = 0[/mathjaxinline], which factors as [mathjaxinline](r+1)(r+4) = 0[/mathjaxinline]. The roots are [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]-4[/mathjaxinline].  A basis for the solutions are [mathjaxinline]x_1(t) = e^{-t}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x_2(t) = e^{-4t}[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore, the general solution is the span of these two basis solutions, which in general form can be written as a linear combination  [mathjax]x(t) = c_1e^{-t} + c_2e^{-4t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 12.2** Solve the equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x + 4\\dot x + 5x = 0[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Worked Solution  The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]r^2 + 4r + 5[/mathjaxinline]. Using the quadratic formula the roots are  [mathjax]r = \\frac{-4 \\pm \\sqrt{16-20}}{2} = -2 \\pm \\sqrt{-1} = -2 \\pm i.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      So a basis for the the solutions are  [mathjax]z(t) = e^{(-2+i)t} \\quad \\text{ and } \\quad \\bar{z}(t) = e^{(-2-i)t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We use the letter [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] here to indicate the functions are complex valued.  The general solution is a linear combination of these two **basis** solutions. But, because the DE has real coefficients, we were expecting **real** valued solutions. Instead, we can take the basis formed by the real and imaginary parts of [mathjaxinline]z(t)[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]z(t) = e^{(-2+i)t} = e^{-2t}\\cos t + ie^{-2t}\\sin t.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The real part of [mathjaxinline]e^{-2t}\\cos t + ie^{-2t}\\sin t[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]e^{-2t}\\cos t[/mathjaxinline] and the imaginary part is [mathjaxinline]e^{-2t}\\sin t[/mathjaxinline].  We now have a basis of two real valued functions, and can use superposition to find the general **real valued** solution  [mathjax]x(t) = c_1e^{-2t}\\cos (t) + c_2e^{-2t}\\sin (t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      As discussed previously in a video, we can find the basis of solutions by taking the real and imaginary parts of [mathjaxinline]\\bar{z}(t)[/mathjaxinline] instead:  [mathjax]\\bar{z}(t) = e^{(-2-i)t} = e^{-2t}(\\cos (-t) + i\\sin (-t))[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then the real-valued **basis** solutions would be  [mathjax]e^{-2t}\\cos (-t) = e^{-2t}\\cos (t) \\, \\text{ and } \\, e^{-2t}\\sin (-t) = -e^{-2t}\\sin (t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Up to a sign these are the same basic solutions as was obtained from [mathjaxinline]\\, z(t),\\,[/mathjaxinline] so [mathjaxinline]\\, \\bar{z}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] would have work just as well.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 12.3** Solve [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x + \\dot x + x = 0[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Worked Solution  Characteristic equation: [mathjaxinline]r^2 + r + 1 = 0[/mathjaxinline].    Roots: [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle { \\frac{-1 \\pm \\sqrt{1 - 4}}{2} = \\frac{-1}{2} \\pm i\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}.\\\\\\ }[/mathjaxinline]    Basis of complex exponential solutions: [mathjaxinline]z(t) = e^{(-1+i\\sqrt3)t/2}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\bar{z}(t) = e^{(-1-i\\sqrt3)t/2}[/mathjaxinline]    Basis of real solutions: [mathjaxinline]x_1(t) = \\text{Re}(z(t)) = e^{-t/2}\\cos (\\sqrt3t /2), \\, \\text{Im}(z(t)) = e^{-t/2}\\sin (\\sqrt3 t/2).[/mathjaxinline]    General real solution: [mathjaxinline]x(t) = e^{-t/2}(c_1\\cos (\\sqrt3t /2) + c_2\\sin (\\sqrt3\\, t /2))[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Worked Examples", "filename": "06_higherorderlinearodes-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Worked Examples"}

{"pageid": 37, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab12", "text": "Recall the method for [finding a basis of solutions](/jump_to_id/06_higherorderlinearodes-tab6) to a constant- coefficient homogeneous linear ODE, now written as [mathjaxinline]P(D) y = 0[/mathjaxinline]. Using operators, we can explain why it works.  **Example 12.1** Consider the ODE  [mathjax]y^{\\prime \\prime \\prime } - 10 y^{\\prime \\prime } + 31y'-30y = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Rewriting this using operator notation we have [mathjaxinline]P(D)y = 0,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]P(r) = r^3-10r^2+31r-30[/mathjaxinline] is the characteristic polynomial of the ODE. The trick now is to factor the operator, and proceed from there. The characteristic polynomial factors as [mathjaxinline]P(r) = (r-2)(r-3)(r-5)[/mathjaxinline]. The order is [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline], so the dimension of the vector space of solutions is [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline].  Now  > [mathjaxinline]e^{2t}[/mathjaxinline] is a solution since > [mathjaxinline]P(D) e^{2t} = P(2) e^{2t} = 0 e^{2t} = 0[/mathjaxinline],   > [mathjaxinline]e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline] is a solution since > [mathjaxinline]P(D) e^{3t} = P(3) e^{3t} = 0 e^{3t} = 0[/mathjaxinline], and   > [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] is a solution since > [mathjaxinline]P(D) e^{5t} = P(5) e^{5t} = 0 e^{5t} = 0[/mathjaxinline].  Just because we wrote down [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] solutions does not mean that they form a basis: If we had written down [mathjaxinline]e^{2t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]4e^{2t}+6e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline], then they would **not** have been a basis, because they are linearly dependent (and their span is only [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional).  To know that [mathjaxinline]e^{2t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] really form a basis, we need to know that they are **linearly independent.** Could it instead be that  [mathjax]e^{5t} = c_1 e^{2t} + c_2 e^{3t} \\qquad \\text{(as functions)}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some numbers [mathjaxinline]c_1,c_2[/mathjaxinline]?  One way to see that this is not possible is to apply [mathjaxinline](D-2)(D-3)[/mathjaxinline] to both sides, which would give  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle (D-2)(D-3)e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (D-2)(D-3)\\left( c_1 e^{2t} + c_2 e^{3t} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.16)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1(D-2)(D-3)e^{2t} + c_2 (D-2)(D-3) e^{3t} \\qquad \\text{(by linearity)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.17)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1\\cdot 0 + c_2 \\cdot 0 = 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.18)      The left hand side gives us  [mathjax](D-2)(D-3)e^{5t} = (5-2)(5-3) e^{5t} \\neq 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This contradiction implies that [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] is not a linear combination of [mathjaxinline]e^{2t}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline]. The same argument shows that no one of [mathjaxinline]e^{2t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] is a linear combination of the other two. Since [mathjaxinline]e^{2t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] are linearly independent, they form a basis for a [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional space (which must be the space of all solutions, since that too is [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional).  Basis of solutions for a constant-coefficient homogeneous linear ODE", "filename": "09_exponentialresponse-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Basis of solutions for a constant-coefficient homogeneous linear ODE"}

{"pageid": 41, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@07_dampedoscillators/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@07_dampedoscillators-tab7", "text": "**Case 3:** [mathjaxinline]\\, b^2 = 4mk\\,[/mathjaxinline] **critically damped** .    The critically damped case happens when [mathjaxinline]b^2=4mk,\\,[/mathjaxinline] at the border between the underdamped case when [mathjaxinline]\\, b^2<4mk,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the overdamped case, when [mathjaxinline]\\, b^2>4mk[/mathjaxinline].    There is a repeated (negative) real root, which we denote by [mathjaxinline]\\, -p\\,[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, p=\\frac{b}{2m}\\,[/mathjaxinline] as before. The repeated root gives only one exponential solution [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{-bt/2m}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] What is another solution?    For a second order (homogeneous linear constant coefficient) ODE with repeated (real) characteristic roots [mathjaxinline]\\, r,\\,[/mathjaxinline] a basis of the solutions is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{e^{rt}}} ,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{ te^{rt} }} ,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.70)   ---|---|---|---|---      giving the general (real) solution [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{c_1 e^{rt}+c_2 te^{rt}}} .[/mathjaxinline]    **Example 7.1** Solve [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x + 4\\dot x + 4x = 0.[/mathjaxinline]  ###  Worked Solution  The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]p(r) = (r+2)^2[/mathjaxinline] has r = -2 as a repeated root. The only exponential solution is [mathjaxinline]e^{-2t}[/mathjaxinline]. Another solution, which is not a constant multiple of [mathjaxinline]e^{-2t}[/mathjaxinline], is given by [mathjaxinline]te^{-2t}[/mathjaxinline] . We will not check this for now, you know how to do it: plug in and use the product rule.  So the general solution is the linear combination of these two basis solutions:  [mathjax]x(t) = c_1e^{-2t} + c_2te^{-2t} \\, \\text{ or } \\, x(t) = e^{-2t}(c_1 + c_2t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})       **Summary of results for the critically damped case:**    Basis of solution space: |  [mathjaxinline]e^{-pt}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]te^{-pt}[/mathjaxinline].   ---|---   General real solution: |  [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{e^{-pt} (a + b t)}}[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]a,b[/mathjaxinline] are real constants.      What happens to the solutions as [mathjaxinline]t \\to +\\infty[/mathjaxinline]? The solution [mathjaxinline]e^{-pt}[/mathjaxinline] tends to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]. So does [mathjaxinline]t e^{-pt} = \\frac{t}{e^{pt}}[/mathjaxinline]: even though the numerator [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is tending to [mathjaxinline]+\\infty[/mathjaxinline], the denominator [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{pt}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is tending to [mathjaxinline]+\\infty[/mathjaxinline] faster (in a contest between exponentials and polynomials, exponentials always win). Thus all solutions eventually decay.    This case is when there is just enough damping to eliminate oscillation. The system is called **critically damped.**  Case 3: critically damped", "filename": "07_dampedoscillators-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Case 3: critically damped"}

{"pageid": 42, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@04_complexexponential/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@04_complexexponential-tab2", "text": "In the last lecture, we used Euler's formula to write a complex number [mathjaxinline]a+bi[/mathjaxinline] in polar form [mathjaxinline]re^{i\\theta }[/mathjaxinline]. In solving ODEs, it is going to be useful to define the complex exponential [mathjaxinline]e^z[/mathjaxinline] for any complex number [mathjaxinline]z=a+ib[/mathjaxinline].  Moreover:  **Definition 2.1** For any complex number [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline], the complex function [mathjaxinline]e^{zt}[/mathjaxinline] of a real variable [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is defined as the solution to the initial value problem  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dt} e^{zt} = z\\, e^{zt}, \\qquad e^{z0} = 1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ### Properties of [mathjaxinline]e^{it}[/mathjaxinline]  For every real number [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline],    1. [mathjaxinline]e^{it} = \\cos t + i \\sin t[/mathjaxinline] ( **Euler's formula** ),     2. [mathjaxinline]e^{-it} = \\overline{e^{it}} = \\cos t - i \\sin t[/mathjaxinline],     3. [mathjaxinline]|e^{it}| = 1[/mathjaxinline].   1\\. (This is the justification from the previous lecture.) The calculation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\left(\\cos t + i \\sin t \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\sin t + i \\cos t[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = i(\\cos t + i \\sin t)[/mathjaxinline] |  |      shows that the function [mathjaxinline]F(t) = \\cos t + i \\sin t[/mathjaxinline] is the solution to the DE with initial condition  [mathjax]\\dot F(t) = i F(t), \\qquad F(0) = 1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      But by definition [mathjaxinline]G(t) = e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] also satisfies  [mathjax]\\dot G(t) = i G(t), \\qquad G(0) = 1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The Existence and Uniqueness theorem for (first order) differential equations applies to complex-valued functions of a real variable. The uniqueness theorem tells us that [mathjaxinline]F(t) = G(t)[/mathjaxinline], or  [mathjax]e^{it} = \\cos t + i \\sin t.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The proof of 2. and 3. follow using 1.      ### Properties of the complex exponential [mathjaxinline]e^{z}[/mathjaxinline]    1. [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{a+ib} = e^a(\\cos b + i \\sin b)[/mathjaxinline] for all real numbers [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] ( **Generalized Euler equation** ).     2. [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{z+w} = e^z e^w[/mathjaxinline] for all complex numbers [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]w[/mathjaxinline].     3. [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (e^z)^n = e^{nz}[/mathjaxinline] for every complex number [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] and integer [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline].       * The [mathjaxinline]n=0[/mathjaxinline] case says [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (e^{z})^{0} = e^{0+i0} = \\cos 0 + i\\sin 0 = 1[/mathjaxinline].       * The [mathjaxinline]n=-1[/mathjaxinline] case says [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{e^z} = (e^z)^{-1} = e^{-z}[/mathjaxinline].     4. ###  (Optional) Taylor series  The Taylor series for [mathjaxinline]e^z[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjax]e^z = 1 + z + \\frac{z^2}{2!} + \\frac{z^3}{3!} + \\cdots .[/mathjax]| (3.48)   ---|---   This formula can be deduced by multiplying [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], which gives [mathjax]e^{zt} = 1 + zt + \\frac{(zt)^2}{2!} + \\frac{(zt)^3}{3!} + \\cdots .[/mathjax]| (3.49)   ---|---   and showing that the right hand side satisfies the initial value problem [mathjaxinline]\\dot F = zF[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]F(0) = 1[/mathjaxinline]. Uniqueness guarantees that the two sides are then equal. By setting [mathjaxinline]t=1[/mathjaxinline], the original statement is shown.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Remark 2.2** Some books use the **generalized Euler equation** or the **Taylor series for [mathjaxinline]e^z[/mathjaxinline]** as the **definition** of the complex exponential function. The definition we gave in terms of the initial value problem [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} e^{zt} = ze^{zt}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]e^{z0} = 1[/mathjaxinline] focuses on what makes the function useful.  ###  (Optional) Proof of the properties  The proofs of these facts are similar to the proof of Euler's formula above.    1. We show that [mathjaxinline]e^{a+ib} = e^a e^{ib} = e^a(\\cos b + i \\sin b)[/mathjaxinline] by showing that [mathjaxinline]e^{(a+ib)t} = e^{at}(\\cos (bt)+ i \\sin (bt))[/mathjaxinline] for real numbers.   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}e^{at}(\\cos bt + i \\sin bt)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\, \\, a e^{at}(\\cos bt + i \\sin bt)+e^{at}(-b\\sin bt + ib \\cos bt)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\, \\, a e^{at}(\\cos bt + i \\sin bt)+e^{at}ib(\\cos bt + i \\sin bt)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\, \\, (a+ib)\\ e^{at}(\\cos bt + i \\sin bt)[/mathjaxinline] |  |      This shows that [mathjaxinline]e^{at}(\\cos bt + i \\sin bt)[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the initial value problem  [mathjax]\\dot F = (a+ib)\\ F, \\qquad F(0) = 1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      But [mathjaxinline]e^{(a+ib)t}[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to this initial value problem by definition. In particular, they are equal when [mathjaxinline]t=1[/mathjaxinline].    3. If [mathjaxinline]n=0[/mathjaxinline], then this is [mathjaxinline]1=1[/mathjaxinline] by definition. If [mathjaxinline]n>0[/mathjaxinline],   [mathjax](e^z)^n \\quad =\\quad \\overbrace{e^z e^z \\cdots e^z}^{{\\color{orange}{n \\textrm{ copies}}} } \\quad \\stackrel{\\textrm{item } 2 \\textrm{ repeatedly}}= \\quad e^{\\overbrace{z+z+\\cdots +z}^{{\\color{orange}{n \\textrm{ copies}}} }} \\quad =\\quad e^{nz}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If [mathjaxinline]n=-m<0[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax](e^z)^{-m} \\quad =\\quad \\frac{1}{(e^z)^m} \\quad \\stackrel{\\textrm{(just shown)}}=\\quad \\frac{1}{e^{mz}} \\quad =\\quad e^{-mz}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      since [mathjaxinline]e^{mz} e^{-mz} = e^{mz + (-mz)} = e^0 = 1[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 43, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@11_resonance/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@11_resonance-tab7", "text": "**Example 7.1** Find a particular solution to the equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot x + 8\\dot x + 15 x = e^{-5t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      ###  Answer  The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]P(r) = r^2 + 8r + 15[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]P(-5) = 0[/mathjaxinline] we need to use the generalized ERF. Computing we see that [mathjaxinline]P'(r) = 2r + 8[/mathjaxinline], which implies [mathjaxinline]P'(-5) = -2[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore the generalized ERF gives [mathjax]x_p = \\frac{te^{-5t}}{P'(-5)} = -\\frac{te^{-5t}}{2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 7.2** Find a particular solution to  [mathjax]\\ddot x + 2\\dot x + 2x = e^{-t}\\cos t.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ###  Answer  First we complexify the equation [mathjax]\\ddot z + 2\\dot z + 2z = e^{(-1+i)t}, \\qquad \\text{where} \\qquad x = \\mathrm{Re\\, }z.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]P(r) = r^2 + 2r +2[/mathjaxinline]. Computing we see that, [mathjax]P(-1+i) = (-1+i)^2 + 2(-1+i) + 2 = 0, \\quad P'(r) = 2r + 2, \\quad P'(-1+i) = 2i.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   Since [mathjaxinline]P(-1+i) = 0[/mathjaxinline] we use the generalized ERF [mathjax]z_p = \\frac{te^{(-1+i)t}}{P'(-1+i)} = \\frac{te^{(-1+i)t}}{2i} = \\frac{te^{-t}(\\cos t + i\\sin t)}{2i}[/mathjax]|   ---|---   Finally we take the real part to get [mathjax]x_p = \\mathrm{Re\\, }z_p = \\frac{te^{-t}\\sin t}{2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Worked examples", "filename": "11_resonance-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Worked examples"}

{"pageid": 44, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab1", "text": "**Objectives**    * Write **linear constant coefficient** differential equations using **operator** notation, that is using **linear time invariant (LTI) operators** .     * Use **time-shifts** to solve LTI differential equations.     * Solve inhomogeneous constant coefficient ODEs with exponential inputs using the **Exponential Response Formula (ERF)** .     * Recognize when ERF **fails** and how to apply **ERF'** and the **Generalized ERF** in these situations.     * Apply superposition to higher order, linear **inhomogeneous** differential equations.   Objectives", "filename": "09_exponentialresponse-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 45, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation12_for_edx/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation12_for_edx-tab2", "text": "**Question 2.2** It seems that all the solutions become asymptotic to each other as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow \\infty[/mathjaxinline]. Explain why solutions get trapped between parallel lines of some fixed slope.  ###  See explanation  All isoclines have the form [mathjaxinline]\\, c= x-2y[/mathjaxinline], rearranging to [mathjaxinline]y = x/2 - c/2,\\,[/mathjaxinline], this tells us that every isocline has slope [mathjaxinline]\\, \\frac12.\\,[/mathjaxinline]. Thus the isoclines are all parallel lines.  The [mathjaxinline]\\, c>1/2\\,[/mathjaxinline] isoclines are the parallel lines below our straight line integral curve [mathjaxinline]\\, y=x/2 - 1/4.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The slope is positive and greater than the slope of the isoclines themselves, which means that every integral curve that starts below the [mathjaxinline]\\, c=1/2\\,[/mathjaxinline] integral curves moves upwards across the isoclines [mathjaxinline]\\, c>1/2[/mathjaxinline].  The [mathjaxinline]\\, c<1/2\\,[/mathjaxinline] isoclines are the parallel lines above our straight line integral curve [mathjaxinline]y=x/2 - 1/4.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Any integral curve through this region must pass through the isocline since the slope of a solution curve through the isocline is always less than the slope of the isocline.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Another question to ponder", "filename": "recitation12_for_edx-tab2-text2.html", "title": "Another question to ponder"}

{"pageid": 46, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab5", "text": "**Example 5.1** Find a solution to [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x} + 4x = \\cos (2t)[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:**     _Step 1._ Replace [mathjaxinline]\\cos (2t)[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }e^{2it}[/mathjaxinline], and complexify the ODE:  [mathjax]\\ddot{z} + 4z = e^{2it}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      _Step 2._ Find the characteristic polynomial and apply ERF: [mathjaxinline]P(r) =r^2+4[/mathjaxinline]. We find that [mathjaxinline]P(2i)=0[/mathjaxinline], so we must use the ERF[mathjaxinline]{}'[/mathjaxinline]: [mathjaxinline]P'(r) = 2r[/mathjaxinline]. The particular solution is  [mathjax]z_p =\\frac{ te^{2it}}{P'(2i)} = \\frac{ te^{2it}}{4i}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      _Step 3._ Take the real part to find the solution to the original equation  [mathjax]x_p = \\mathrm{Re\\, }(z_p) = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(\\frac{t(\\cos (2t) + i\\sin (2t))}{4i}\\right) = \\frac{t}{4}\\sin (2t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Example 5.2** Find a particular solution [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline] to  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + \\dot{x} + 2x = {\\color{orange}{\\cos (2t)}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Solution:**     _Step 1._ Since [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{\\cos (2t)}}[/mathjaxinline] is the real part of [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{e^{2it}}}[/mathjaxinline], replace [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{\\cos (2t)}}[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{e^{2it}}}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\ddot{z}}} + {\\color{blue}{\\dot{z}}} + 2{\\color{blue}{z}} = {\\color{orange}{e^{2it}}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      _Step 2._ Find the characteristic polynomial [mathjaxinline]P(r) = r^2+r+2[/mathjaxinline] and apply ERF, which says that one particular solution to this new ODE is  [mathjax]z_p = \\frac{1}{P(2i)} e^{2it} = \\frac{1}{-2+2i} e^{2it}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      _Step 3._ A particular solution to the original ODE is  [mathjax]{\\color{orange}{x_p = \\mathrm{Re\\, }(z_p) = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( \\frac{1}{-2+2i} e^{2it} \\right).}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is a sinusoid expressed in complex form.  It might be more useful to have the answer in amplitude-phase form or as a linear combination of cosine and sine.  **Converting to amplitude-phase form.** We have  [mathjax]z_p = \\frac{1}{-2+2i} e^{2it}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      To get the amplitude-phase form, we convert numerator and denominator to polar form so the division is easier. The denominator [mathjaxinline]-2+2i[/mathjaxinline] has absolute value [mathjaxinline]2 \\sqrt{2}[/mathjaxinline] and angle [mathjaxinline]3\\pi /4[/mathjaxinline], so in polar form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -2+2i[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2\\sqrt{2} e^{i(3\\pi /4)},[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z_p[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{e^{2it}}{2\\sqrt{2} e^{i(3\\pi /4)}} = \\frac{1}{2\\sqrt{2}} e^{i(2t-3\\pi /4)}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Conclusion:** In amplitude-phase form,  [mathjax]\\boxed {x_p = \\frac{1}{2\\sqrt{2}} \\cos (2t - 3\\pi /4). }[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Converting to a linear combination of** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\cos }}[/mathjaxinline] **and** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\sin }}[/mathjaxinline] **:** We have  [mathjax]z_p = \\frac{1}{-2+2i} e^{2it}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      To get the linear combination, we express numerator and denominator in rectangular form and then rationalize the denominator. We have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{2it}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos 2t + i \\sin 2t[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\cos 2t + i \\sin 2t}{-2+2i}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\cos 2t + i \\sin 2t}{-2+2i} \\left(\\frac{-2-2i}{-2-2i}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\cos 2t + i \\sin 2t) \\frac{-2-2i}{8} =(\\cos 2t + i \\sin 2t) \\frac{-1-i}{4}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{(-\\cos 2t +\\sin 2t) - i(\\cos 2t +\\sin 2t)}{4}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Conclusion:**  [mathjax]\\boxed {x_p = -\\frac{1}{4} \\cos (2t) + \\frac{1}{4} \\sin (2t)}[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Worked examples using complex replacement", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Worked examples using complex replacement"}

{"pageid": 47, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@33_numericalmethods/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@33_numericalmethods-tab3", "text": "One of the first questions to ask about the Euler method is whether the approximation it gives is too high or too low. This is in general difficult to decide, but when the actual solution is known to be either concave or convex, we do know the answer.    Recall in Euler's method, we start with the initial value problem  [mathjax]y'\\, =\\, f(t,y),\\qquad y(t_0)=y_0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Let[mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] be the actual solution and let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\bar{y}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] be the approximate solution given by Euler's method with stepsize [mathjaxinline]\\, h.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] As before, [mathjaxinline]\\, t_n=t_0+nh\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the time after [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] steps.      * If[mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is **convex** (or **concave up** ), that is, if [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y}>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the interval [mathjaxinline]\\, [t_0, \\, t_n][/mathjaxinline], and in a region along the Euler polygon [mathjaxinline]\\bar{y}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\, \\bar{y}(t_n)< y(t_n)[/mathjaxinline].    ![A graph of the concave up function y of t is plotted in the first quadrant. The point t sub 0, y sub 0 is indicated. Several steps of Euler's method are carried out leading to the approximation of y at t sub n to be less than the true value of y of t sub n.](/static/images/u1c5s3_convex.svg)    * If[mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is **concave** (or **concave down** ), that is, if [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y} <0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the interval [mathjaxinline]\\, [t_0, \\, t_n][/mathjaxinline], and in a region along the Euler polygon [mathjaxinline]\\bar{y}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\, \\bar{y}(t_n)> y(t_n)[/mathjaxinline].    ![A graph of the concave down function y of t is plotted in the first quadrant. The point t sub 0, y sub 0 is indicated. Several steps of Euler's method are carried out leading to the approximation of y at t sub n to be greater than the true value of y of t sub n.](/static/images/u1c5s3_concave.svg)  Often we do not know whether the actual solution [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] is convex or concave in an entire interval. What we are able to compute without knowledge of the solution is the value of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\ddot{y}[/mathjaxinline] at the starting point [mathjaxinline]\\, t_0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This is still useful because this means that as long as we carry out Euler's method for a short enough time interval, we can still predict whether the Euler approximation overshoots or undershoots.    To find [mathjaxinline]\\, \\ddot{y}[/mathjaxinline] at the starting point [mathjaxinline]\\, t_0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] we differentiate the DE [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}=f(t,y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] to find [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The differentiation is often called implicit because the variable [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] depends on [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. This gives us a formula for [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y}[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]t,\\, y,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] To evaluate [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y}(t_0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] plug in the initial condition [mathjaxinline]t_0,\\, y(t_0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] as well as[mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}(t_0)=f(t_0,y_0).[/mathjaxinline]    Overestimate, underestimate and concavity", "filename": "33_numericalmethods-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Overestimate, underestimate and concavity"}

{"pageid": 48, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@04_complexexponential/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@04_complexexponential-tab7", "text": "**Example 7.1** What are the complex solutions to [mathjaxinline]z^5 = -32[/mathjaxinline]?  **Solution:** Whenever we want to find roots, we write the equation in polar form [mathjaxinline]z=r e^{i\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, (r>0):[/mathjaxinline]  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle (r e^{i\\theta })^5[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 32 e^{i \\pi }[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle r^5 e^{i(5\\theta )}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 32 e^{i \\pi }[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The modulus or absolute value of the roots must satisfy the equation [mathjaxinline]r^5 = 32[/mathjaxinline]. The angles must satisfy [mathjaxinline]5 \\theta = \\pi + 2 \\pi k[/mathjaxinline] for some integer [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline]. Thus  [mathjax]r = 2 \\qquad \\textrm{ and } \\qquad \\theta = \\frac{\\pi + 2\\pi k}{5} \\textrm{ for some integer } k .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In other words,  [mathjax]z = 2 e^{i(\\pi + 2\\pi k)/5} \\textrm{ for some integer } k.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      These are numbers on a circle of radius [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]; to get from one to the next (increasing [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]), rotate by [mathjaxinline]2\\pi /5[/mathjaxinline]. Increasing [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] five times brings the number back to its original position. So it's enough to take [mathjaxinline]k=0,1,2,3,4[/mathjaxinline]. Answer:  [mathjax]2 e^{i(\\pi /5)} , \\; 2 e^{i(3\\pi /5)}, \\; 2 e^{i(5\\pi /5)}, \\; 2 e^{i(7\\pi /5)}, \\; 2 e^{i(9\\pi /5)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   ![In the complex plane, 2 e to the i pi over 5 is in the first quadrant, 2 e to the 3 i pi over 5 is in the second quadrant, 2 e to the 5 i pi over 5 is on the negative x axis, 2 e to the 7 i pi over 5 is in the third quadrant, and 2 e to the 9 i pi over 5 is in the fourth quadrant.](/static/images/5th- roots.svg)  **Remark 7.2** The fundamental theorem of algebra predicts that the polynomial [mathjaxinline]z^5 + 32[/mathjaxinline] has [mathjaxinline]5[/mathjaxinline] roots when counted with multiplicity. We found [mathjaxinline]5[/mathjaxinline] roots, so each must have multiplicity [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline].  Finding roots", "filename": "04_complexexponential-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Finding roots"}

{"pageid": 49, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab8", "text": "This method is exactly the same as variation of parameters. It is algebraically equivalent, but comes at the approach from a slightly different angle. We are adding it here because some texts and courses will refer to the term integrating factor, and we want you to be familiar with it.  The set up is the same, we start with a first order, linear, inhomogeneous ODE:  [mathjax]\\dot{y} + p(t) y = q(t)[/mathjax]| (2.54)   ---|---      To find an **integrating factor** :    1. Find an antiderivative [mathjaxinline]P(t)[/mathjaxinline] of [mathjaxinline]p(t)[/mathjaxinline]. The integrating factor is [mathjaxinline]e^{P(t)}[/mathjaxinline].     2. Multiply both sides of the ODE by the integrating factor [mathjaxinline]e^{P(t)}[/mathjaxinline].   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{P(t)} \\dot{y} + e^{P(t)} p(t) \\, y[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q(t) e^{P(t)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      We do this multiplication because it is now possible to express the left side as the derivative of something:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{P(t)} \\dot{y}(t) + e^{P(t)} p(t) \\, y(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} \\left( e^{P(t)} y(t) \\right) .[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Now we can carry out the integration.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} \\left( e^{P} y \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q e^{P}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{P} y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int q e^{P} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{-P} \\int q e^{P} \\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The indefinite integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int q(t) e^{P(t)} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] represents a family of solutions because there is a constant of integration. If we fix one antiderivative, say [mathjaxinline]R(t)[/mathjaxinline], then the others are [mathjaxinline]R(t) + C[/mathjaxinline] for a constant [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline]. So the general solution is  [mathjax]y = R(t) e^{-P(t)} + C e^{-P(t)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---    **Remark 8.1** The integrating factor [mathjaxinline]e^{P(t)}[/mathjaxinline] is the reciprocal of a solution to the homogeneous equation.  **Remark 8.2** This process is equivalent to variation of parameters. The connection between the methods is that the unknown in variation by parameters is  [mathjax]u = \\frac{y}{y_h} = ye^{P}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Inhomogeneous equations: integrating factor", "filename": "02_solvingafirstorderode-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Inhomogeneous equations: integrating factor"}
