{"pageid": 52, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation13_for_edx/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation13_for_edx-tab2", "text": "Horseshoe crab blood (which is bright blue since it is based on copper rather than iron) contains cells that respond to bacteria at about one part in a trillion. Starting in 1970 it has been used to detect bacterial infections in humans. A start-up in Maryland is considering creating a horseshoe crab farm, and seeks advice about how large a herd they should create in order to sustain the level of harvesting that would make a profit, namely, 250 crabs per month.  Here's a model. The unknown [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] is proportional to the size of the farm. This proportionality constant is the maximum population in the absence of harvesting (measured in kilocrabs). The larger the farm, the larger the maximum population with no harvesting. Crabs multiply fast in an unconstrained environment, at the rate of 1 month[mathjaxinline]{}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]. So the logistic growth rate is [mathjaxinline](1-y/a)[/mathjaxinline], and the logistic equation is  [mathjax]\\dot y=(1-(y/a))y=y-y^2/a\\, .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If we now include the desired harvest rate we get  [mathjax]\\dot y=-\\frac{1}{4}+y-\\frac{y^2}{a}\\, .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Our job is to determine the behavior of the crab population for various values of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].  Phase lines", "filename": "recitation13_for_edx-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Phase lines"}

{"pageid": 53, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab3", "text": "The figure below is the geometric picture of the differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\, y' = f(x,y).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] In the video, this sketch is called a direction field. In these notes, we will call it a **slope field** instead. We reserve the word direction field for diagrams whose line elements have arrows.    ![Small line segments are drawn at several points in the x y plane indicating the slope of the function f at that point.](/static/images/u2s1_slopefield.svg)   The line element at [mathjaxinline]\\, (x,y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] has slope [mathjaxinline]\\, f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline]     **Definition 3.1** For a differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\, y'=f(x,y),\\,[/mathjaxinline] a **slope field** is a diagram which includes at each point [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline] a short line element (or line segment) whose slope is the **value** [mathjaxinline]f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline].  ![Small line segments are drawn at several points in the x y plane indicating the slope of the function f at that point. A solution is drawn as a single curve that is tangent to each line segment that it touches.](/static/images/u2s1_slopefieldsolutioncurve.svg)   A solution curve (blue) is tangent to each line segment that it touches.        The graph of a solution [mathjaxinline]y_1(x)[/mathjaxinline] to the DE in the [mathjaxinline]\\, xy[/mathjaxinline]-plane is called a **solution curve** or an **integral curve** .    An integral curve must be tangent to the slope field at every point: [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, y_1'(x)=f\\left(x, y_1(x)\\right).[/mathjaxinline]    Geometric View of DEs", "filename": "28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Geometric View of DEs"}

{"pageid": 54, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab2", "text": "**Complex numbers** are expressions of the form [mathjaxinline]a+bi[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are real numbers, and [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] is a new symbol. Just as real numbers can be plotted on a line, complex numbers can be plotted in a plane: plot [mathjaxinline]a+bi[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline].  ![A set of axes with the vertical labeled imaginary axis and the horizontal labeled real axis. As an example, the point 2 minus i is plotted at the coordinate 2 comma negative 1.](/static/images/complex_plane03.svg)   **Figure :** A point in the complex plane.        * A complex number of the form [mathjaxinline]0+ib[/mathjaxinline] is called **purely imaginary.**    * A complex number of the form [mathjaxinline]a+0i[/mathjaxinline] is called **real.**  Multiplication will eventually be defined so that [mathjaxinline]i^2=-1[/mathjaxinline]. (Electrical engineers sometimes write [mathjaxinline]j[/mathjaxinline] instead of [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline], because they want to reserve [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] for current, but everybody else thinks that's weird.) Just as the set of all real numbers is denoted [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}[/mathjaxinline], the set of all complex numbers is denoted [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbb {C}}}[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Historical origin of complex numbers  Most people think that complex numbers arose from attempts to solve quadratic equations, but actually they first appeared in connection with cubic equations. Everyone knew that certain quadratic equations, like  [mathjax]x^2 + 1 = 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      or  [mathjax]x^2 +2x+5 = 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      had no solutions. The problem was with certain cubic equations, for example .  [mathjax]x^3 - 6x - 2 = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This equation was known to have three real roots, given by simple combinations of the expressions  [mathjax]A = \\sqrt[3]{1 +\\sqrt{-7}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---   [mathjax]B=\\sqrt[3]{1 -\\sqrt{-7}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Check that one of the roots is A+B; it may not look like a real number, but it turns out to be one! {"pageid": 56, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab15", "text": "### Damped sinusoidal signals  Complex Replacement and the Exponential Response Formula can be used to solve equations of the form  [mathjax]P\\left(D\\right)x=e^{at}\\cos (\\omega t-\\phi )[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]P(D)[/mathjaxinline] is any LTI differential operator.  **Example 15.1** Solve  [mathjax]2\\ddot x+\\dot x+x=e^{-t}\\cos t.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ###  Worked Solution  We found the general solution to the homogeneous version of the ODE in example 14.1 [here](/jump_to_id/09_exponentialresponse-tab14). To solve this ODE in general we just need to find a particular solution. To do this, we complexify the ODE:  [mathjax]2\\ddot{z}+\\dot{z}+z=e^{(-1+i)t},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then apply the Exponential Response Formula:  [mathjax]z_p=\\frac{e^{(-1+i)t}}{P(-1+i)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      To get [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline] we have to extract the real part of [mathjaxinline]z_p[/mathjaxinline]. We have the choice to put [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline] in rectangular form or polar form. To put [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline] in rectangular form, we expand  [mathjax]P(-1+i)=2(-1+i)^2+(-1+i)+1=-3i[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so [mathjaxinline]z_p=ie^{(-1+i)t}/3[/mathjaxinline], and the real part is  [mathjax]x_p=-(1/3)e^{-t}\\sin (t)\\, .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      To put [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline] in polar form, we write  [mathjax]\\frac{1}{P(-1+i)}=ge^{-i\\phi }[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so that  [mathjax]z_p=ge^{-i\\phi }e^{(-1+i)t}=ge^{-t}e^{i(t-\\phi )}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the real part is  [mathjax]x_p=ge^{-t}\\cos (t-\\phi )[/mathjax]|   ---|---      It's easy to check that you get the same answer!  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Worked Examples", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Worked Examples"}

{"pageid": 60, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@08_higherorder/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@08_higherorder-tab11", "text": "We now know how to find the general solution to a DE of the form  [mathjax]a_n {\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + \\cdots + a_1 {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + a_0 {\\color{blue}{y}} = 0,[/mathjax]| (4.102)   ---|---      but what do we need in order to pin down one specific solution? The answer is provided by the existence and uniqueness theorem below, which we have only stated for first order linear ODEs before:  **Existence and uniqueness theorem for a linear ODE.**  Let [mathjaxinline]\\, p_{n-1}(t),\\, \\ldots ,\\, p_0(t),\\, q(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] be continuous functions on an open interval [mathjaxinline]\\, I.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Let [mathjaxinline]\\, a \\in I,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and let [mathjaxinline]\\, b_0,\\, \\ldots ,\\, b_{n-1}\\,[/mathjaxinline] be given numbers. Then there exists a unique solution on [mathjaxinline]\\, I\\,[/mathjaxinline] to the [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order linear ODE  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + p_{n-1}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n-1)}}} + \\cdots + p_1(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p_0(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = {\\color{orange}{q(t)}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      satisfying the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] initial conditions  [mathjax]y(a)=b_0, \\quad \\dot{y}(a)=b_1, \\quad \\ldots , \\quad y^{(n-1)}(a)=b_{n-1}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      As before, **existence** means that there is **at least** one solution; **uniqueness** means that there is **only** one solution.    The theorem says that, given an [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order linear ODE, a single solution can be found by giving [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] numbers, namely the values of [mathjaxinline]\\, y(a),\\, \\dot{y}(a),\\, \\ldots ,\\, y^{(n-1)}(a),\\,[/mathjaxinline] the initial conditions.  **Remark 11.1** The existence and uniqueness theorem in the homogeneous case explains the dimension theorem we stated previously. Each solution [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] determines a set of initial conditions, given by  [mathjax]y(t)\\to \\left(\\, y(a),\\dot{y} (a), \\, \\ldots , \\, y^{(n-1)}(a) \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      On the other hand, the existence and uniqueness theorem says that each set of initial conditions specifies exactly one solution. The sequence of numbers [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\, y(a),\\dot{y} (a), \\, \\ldots , \\, y^{(n-1)}(a) \\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] constitutes a vector in [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbb {R}^n,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the 1-to-1 correspondence between solutions and sets of initial conditions given by existence and uniqueness theorem proves the dimension theorem.  Existence and uniqueness of solutions", "filename": "08_higherorder-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Existence and uniqueness of solutions"}

{"pageid": 62, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@01_odeintro/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@01_odeintro-tab8", "text": "There are two kinds of modeling. We're not going to talk about the kind that involves fancy clothes and photographs. The other kind, **mathematical modeling** , is converting a real-world problem into mathematical equations.  Guidelines:    1. Identify relevant quantities, both known and unknown, and give them symbols. Find the units for each.     2. Identify the independent variable(s). The other quantities will be functions of them, or constants. Often **time** is the only independent variable.     3. Write down equations expressing how the functions change in response to small changes in the independent variable(s). Also write down any \u201claws of nature\" relating the variables. As a check, make sure that all summands in an equation have the same units.   Often simplifying assumptions need to be made; the challenge is to simplify the equations so that they can be solved but so that they still describe the real-world system well. {"pageid": 66, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@11_resonance/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@11_resonance-tab4", "text": "The case in which we drive a harmonic oscillator by the natural frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline] is known as **pure resonance** .  [mathjax](D^2 + \\omega _n^2)x = \\cos (\\omega _n t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      To find a particular solution, we find a particular solution instead to the complexified equation  [mathjax](D^2 + \\omega _n^2)z = e^{i \\omega _n t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that [mathjaxinline]i \\omega _n[/mathjaxinline] is a root of the characteristic polynomial [mathjaxinline]P(r) = r^2 + \\omega _n^2[/mathjaxinline]. But [mathjaxinline]P'(r) = 2r[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]P'(i\\omega _n) = 2i \\omega _n \\neq 0[/mathjaxinline] and we use ERF[mathjaxinline]{}'[/mathjaxinline] to find a complex particular solution  [mathjax]z_p = \\frac{te^{i\\omega _n t}}{P'(i \\omega _n)}= \\frac{te^{i\\omega _n t}}{2 i \\omega _n} = \\frac{t(\\cos \\omega _n t + i\\sin \\omega _n t)}{2 i \\omega _n}).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The real part of [mathjaxinline]z_p[/mathjaxinline] is a real-valued particular solution  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(z_p)=x_p = \\frac{t\\sin (\\omega _n t)}{2\\omega _n}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Even though our input signal is sinusoidal, the response is not a sinusoid. The response is an oscillating function whose oscillations grow linearly without bound as time increases.  **Pure resonance** is a phenomenon that occurs when a harmonic oscillator is driven with an input sinusoid whose frequency is at the natural frequency:    * the gain becomes larger and larger as the input frequency approaches the natural frequency, and     * when the input frequency _equals_ the natural frequency, any particular solution is unbounded. {"pageid": 67, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab14", "text": "In the last lecture we derived a differential equation governing yeast growth. {"pageid": 70, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation13_for_edx/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation13_for_edx-tab3", "text": "Our model for a profitable horseshoe crab farm with harvest rate [mathjaxinline]250[/mathjaxinline] crabs per month is given by [mathjax]\\dot y=-\\frac{1}{4}+y-\\frac{y^2}{a}\\,[/mathjax]|   ---|---   where [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] has units of kilocrabs. {"pageid": 71, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab10", "text": "In order to justify Euler's formula, we want to show that [mathjaxinline]e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] satisfies the exponential principle. To do this, we need to explain how to take the derivative of a complex-valued function of a real variable.  ### Complex-valued functions of a real variable  Suppose that [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] is a complex-valued function of a real variable [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. Then  [mathjax]y(t) = f(t) + i\\, g(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some **real-valued** functions of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. Here [mathjaxinline]f(t) \\colon =\\mathrm{Re\\, }y(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g(t) \\colon =\\mathrm{Im\\, }y(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Differentiation and integration can be done component-wise:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y'(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = f'(t) + i \\, g'(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int y(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int f(t) \\, dt + i \\int g(t) \\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      This is exactly same as for vector-valued functions.  ### Justification of Euler's formula:  We justify the Euler's formula by showing [mathjaxinline]e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] satisfies the initial value problem [mathjaxinline]y' = iy, \\quad y(0) =1[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\left(\\cos t + i\\sin t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.36)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Recall that to differentiate a complex function of a real variable, we differentiate the real and imaginary parts.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\left(\\cos t + i\\sin t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\sin t + i\\cos t[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.37)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle i(i\\sin t + \\cos t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.38)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ie^{it}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.39)      Last we need to check the initial condition, which works out as expected  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{i\\cdot 0} = \\cos 0 + i \\sin 0 = 1.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.40)   ---|---|---|---      Together with the exponential law, this proves Euler's genius in using the exponential notation to simplify the polar form of a complex number with modulus [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 78, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab4", "text": "Let us get back to our spring mass system, modelled by the DE  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot x+x = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.68)   ---|---|---|---      We have found that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle x(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1 \\cos (t) +c_2 \\sin (t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.69)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      is a solution for any values of the two parameters [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, c_2.\\,[/mathjaxinline] It turns out that this **2-parameter family** of solutions comprise **all** the solutions to the given **second order** DE.    **All solutions to a second order linear homogeneous DE:**    The collection of all solutions to any second order linear homogeneous DE is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle x(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1 x_1(t) +c_2 x_2(t),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.70)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, x_1(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, x_2(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] are solutions to the second order DE, and the two parameters [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline] can take any constant values. This two- parameter family of solutions is also called the **general solution** to the second order linear DE.     **Important:** [mathjaxinline]\\, x_1(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, x_2(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] must be _linearly independent_! This means [mathjaxinline]\\, x_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, x_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] cannot be a constant multiple of the other. In particular, this means neither [mathjaxinline]\\, x_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] nor [mathjaxinline]\\, x_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] can be zero. In this case, we say that [mathjaxinline]\\, x_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, x_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] form a **basis** for the set of all homogeneous solutions.    The definition of linear independence of more than two elements is more complicated, and we will come back to it in a later lecture.     **Remark 4.1** This means that the problem of solving a second order linear ODE is reduced to finding only two linearly independent solutions, since all others can be built by taking linear combinations of these.     **Remark 4.2** There are **two** parameters in the general solution to a **second order** DE roughly because to solve a second order DE, in one way or another (and it may be concealed), we need to integrate twice, and with each integration comes a constant of integration. Later on, we will find that in general, the number of arbitrary constants in the general solution corresponds to the order of a linear ODE.     **Initial conditions:**    Every second-order linear ODE has a 2-parameter family of solutions. To nail down a specific solution, we need to specify two pieces of data for the solution. It is a beautiful fact that this data can be provided always by two initial conditions at the same starting time, such as [mathjaxinline]y(0)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\dot y(0)[/mathjaxinline]. The starting time could also be some number [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] other than [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline].    Once we have found a basis [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x_2[/mathjaxinline] for the solutions, the initial conditions are satisfied by choosing the values for the two parameters [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline].    Compare this with what we have learned for first order linear equations. Using separation of variables (in the homogeneous case) and variation of parameters (in the inhomogeneous case), we showed that every first-order linear ODE has a 1-parameter family of solutions. To nail down a specific solution in this family, we need only one initial condition, such as y(0).    All solutions to second order linear homogeneous ODE", "filename": "06_higherorderlinearodes-tab4-text1.html", "title": "All solutions to second order linear homogeneous ODE"}

\\vdots[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P(r_0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Differentiate both sides of the equation [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] times with respect to [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] to obtain a relationship:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle P(D)\\left(t^m e^{rt}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(P^{(m)}(r) + m\\ t\\ P^{(m-1)}(r) + \\frac{m(m-1)}2 t^2P^{(m-2)}(r) + \\dotsb + t^mP(r)\\right)e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Evaluating at [mathjaxinline]r_0[/mathjaxinline], only the [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline]th derivative term survives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle P(D)\\left(t^m e^{r_0t}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P^{(m)}(r_0)e^{r_0t},[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      which gives a particular solution to the differential equation [mathjaxinline]P(D)y = e^{r_0t}[/mathjaxinline] of the form [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_p= \\frac{t^me^{r_0t}}{P^{(m)}(r_0)}[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 10.2** Solve the system [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x}+x=e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] with initial conditions [mathjaxinline]x\\left(0\\right)=1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}\\left(0\\right)=0[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Worked solution  The characteristic polynomial of the differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x}+x=e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]P\\left(r\\right)=r^2+1[/mathjaxinline], with roots [mathjaxinline]\\pm i[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] is a root of the characteristic polynomial, the **Generalized ERF** tells us to find the smallest integer [mathjaxinline]s[/mathjaxinline] for which [mathjaxinline]P^{\\left(s\\right)}\\left(i\\right)\\neq 0[/mathjaxinline]. In this case, [mathjaxinline]P^{\\prime }\\left(r\\right)=2r[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]P^{\\prime }\\left(i\\right)=2i[/mathjaxinline], which is not zero, so [mathjaxinline]s=1[/mathjaxinline]. The Generalized ERF tells us that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_p\\left(t\\right)=\\frac{1}{P^{\\prime }\\left(i\\right)}t^{1}e^{it}=\\frac{1}{2i}te^{it}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      is a particular solution to the inhomogeneous ODE. Since [mathjaxinline]\\frac1i=e^{-i\\pi /2}[/mathjaxinline], we can write [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline] as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_p\\left(t\\right)=\\frac{1}{2}te^{it-i\\pi /2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Since the characteristic polynomial has roots [mathjaxinline]\\pm i[/mathjaxinline], we know that the pair  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{it},e^{-it}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      form a basis for the space of solutions to the homogeneous equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x}+x=0[/mathjaxinline]. Hence, the general solution to the inhomogeneous equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x}+x=e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x\\left(t\\right)=\\underbrace{c_{1}e^{it}+c_{2}e^{-it}}_{\\text{general solution to homogeneous ODE}}+\\underbrace{\\frac{1}{2}te^{it-i\\pi /2}.}_{{\\color{orange}{\\text{particular solution}}} }[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Now we just need to solve for the constants [mathjaxinline]c_{1}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_{2}[/mathjaxinline] from the initial conditions [mathjaxinline]x\\left(0\\right)=1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}\\left(0\\right)=0[/mathjaxinline]. We see that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x\\left(0\\right)=1=c_{1}+c_{2},[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      so [mathjaxinline]c_{2}=1-c_{1}[/mathjaxinline], and we can write [mathjaxinline]x\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x\\left(t\\right)=c_{1}e^{it}+\\left(1-c_{1}\\right)e^{-it}+\\frac{1}{2}te^{it-i\\pi /2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      We see that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}\\left(t\\right)=ic_{1}e^{it}-i\\left(1-c_{1}\\right)e^{-it}+\\frac{1}{2}e^{it-i\\pi /2}+\\frac{1}{2}te^{it},[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      so  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}\\left(0\\right)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =ic_{1}-i\\left(1-c_{1}\\right)+\\frac{1}{2}e^{-i\\pi /2}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =ic_{1}-i\\left(1-c_{1}\\right)-\\frac{i}{2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Using the initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}\\left(0\\right)=0[/mathjaxinline] and solving for [mathjaxinline]c_{1}[/mathjaxinline] we see that [mathjaxinline]c_{1}=3/4[/mathjaxinline]. Substituting this into the equation [mathjaxinline]c_{2}=1-c_1[/mathjaxinline], we see that [mathjaxinline]c_{2}=1/4[/mathjaxinline]. Thus the solution to the system [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x}+x=e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] with initial conditions [mathjaxinline]x\\left(0\\right)=1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}\\left(0\\right)=0[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x\\left(t\\right)=\\frac{3}{4}e^{it}+\\frac{1}{4}e^{-it}+\\frac{1}{2}te^{it-i\\pi /2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  The generalized Exponential Response Formula", "filename": "09_exponentialresponse-tab10-text1.html", "title": "The generalized Exponential Response Formula"}

{"pageid": 86, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab7", "text": "Recall that our task at hand is to prepare a salt-water solution with salt concentration of 34 g/L for ocean fish to live in. We do so by pumping a concentrated salt-water solution, of concentration 75 g/L, at a rate of 5 L/min into a tank that initially contains 800L of pure fresh water, and allowing the mixed solution to flow out of a drain at a rate of 3L/min.    According to the discussion in the videos, the initial value problem that describes the total amount of salt [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] (in grams) in the tank is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dx}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 375-\\frac{3x}{800+2t}\\qquad x(0)=0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.39)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      By variation of parameters, we then obtained the solution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(60000+150t\\right)-\\left(\\frac{4.8 \\times 10^8}{(400+t)^{3/2}}\\right),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.40)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where the linear function in first bracket is the long time (or steady state) solution. The decreasing function in the second bracket tends to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t\\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline] and is the transient solution. In order for the term in the second bracket to tend to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], the exponent [mathjaxinline]3/2[/mathjaxinline] of the denominator only needs to be positive (rather than greater than [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] as stated in the video). {"pageid": 88, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab13", "text": "What about the case of repeated roots?  This case is less important than the others, because if someone hands you a polynomial it's unlikely that two or more of its roots will coincide. But it does happen, and it is interesting to think about what happens.  **Example 13.1** Find a basis of solutions to [mathjaxinline]D^3 y = 0[/mathjaxinline]. (The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]r^3[/mathjaxinline], whose roots with multiplicity are [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline].)  **Solution:** Integrate three times:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D^2 y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = c_1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = c_1 t + c_2[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = c_1 \\frac{t^2}{2} + c_2 t + c_3[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\textrm{general solution}}} }{C_1 t^2 + c_2 t + c_3}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      for some numbers [mathjaxinline]C_1=c_1/2[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]c_3[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]t^2[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] are linearly independent, they form a basis for the space of solutions.  **Example 13.2** Find a basis of solutions to [mathjaxinline](D-5)^3 y = 0[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:**  The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline](r-5)^3[/mathjaxinline], which has a repeated root [mathjaxinline]5,5,5[/mathjaxinline], so based on the previous example, we might hope that [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]t e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]t^2 e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] are a basis. Let's now explain **why** these are solutions.  We know that [mathjaxinline]D-5[/mathjaxinline] sends [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]. What does [mathjaxinline]D-5[/mathjaxinline] do to [mathjaxinline]u e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline], if [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] is a function of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]? Using the product rule:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (D-5) \\, u e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\left( \\dot{u}\\cdot e^{5t} + u \\cdot 5 e^{5t} \\right) - 5 u \\cdot e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\dot{u} \\cdot e^{5t}.[/mathjaxinline] | |      Replacing [mathjaxinline](D-5)[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline](D-5)^2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](D-5)^3[/mathjaxinline] on the left we get the following:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (D-5)^2 \\, u e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\ddot{u} e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (D-5)^3 \\, u e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = u^{(3)} e^{5t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      So our guess was right! In order for [mathjaxinline]u e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] to be a solution to [mathjaxinline](D-5)^3 y = 0[/mathjaxinline] the function [mathjaxinline]u^{(3)}[/mathjaxinline] must be [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]; i.e., [mathjaxinline]u = a + b t + c t^2[/mathjaxinline] for some numbers [mathjaxinline]a,b,c[/mathjaxinline], so the solutions are  [mathjax]\\displaystyle u e^{5t} = a \\, e^{5t} + b \\, t e^{5t} + c \\, t^2 e^{5t},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      as expected.  Since [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]t^2[/mathjaxinline] are linearly independent functions, so are [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]te^{5t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]t^2e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] (any relation between the last three functions could be divided by [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] to get a relation between the first three). Thus [mathjaxinline]e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]t e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]t^2 e^{5t}[/mathjaxinline] form a basis.  If a characteristic polynomial [mathjaxinline]P(r)[/mathjaxinline] has a root [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] is repeated [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] times, then [mathjaxinline]e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]te^{rt}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]t^2e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline] , [mathjaxinline]t^{k-1}e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline] are independent solutions to the differential equation [mathjaxinline]P(D)y=0[/mathjaxinline].  The Case of Repeated Roots", "filename": "09_exponentialresponse-tab13-text1.html", "title": "The Case of Repeated Roots"}

{"pageid": 94, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@29_autonomousequations2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@29_autonomousequations2-tab7", "text": "**Example 7.1** Describe qualitatively the solutions to [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y} = 3y-y^2[/mathjaxinline]. (This is a special case of the logistic equation [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y} = ay-by^2[/mathjaxinline].)  **Solution:**  To find qualitative behavior of the solutions, we follow the two steps described before:    1. Find the critical points by solving [mathjaxinline]f(y)=0[/mathjaxinline].   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle f(y)=3y-y^2=0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y=0\\, \\, \\, \\text{or} \\, \\, \\, y=3.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.36)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      So the constant solutions are [mathjaxinline]y(t)=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y(t)=3[/mathjaxinline].    2. Determine the intervals of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] in which [mathjaxinline]f(y)>0[/mathjaxinline] and in which [mathjaxinline]f(y)<0[/mathjaxinline]. To do this, we can graph the function [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline] as in the video, or simply test one point in each region.       * Since [mathjaxinline]f(-1)<0[/mathjaxinline], the region [mathjaxinline]y<0[/mathjaxinline] is a down region.       * Since [mathjaxinline]f(1)>0[/mathjaxinline], the region [mathjaxinline]0<y<3[/mathjaxinline] is an up region.       * Since [mathjaxinline]f(4)<0[/mathjaxinline], the region [mathjaxinline]y>3[/mathjaxinline] is a down region.   We can summarize the above information by a phase line:  ![A horizontal phase line is shown with positive infinity on the right and negative infinity on the left. The values 0 and 3 are indicated. The arrow to the left of 0 points leftward. The arrow between 0 and 3 points rightward. The arrow to the right of 3 points leftward.](/static/images/u2s2_horizontalphaseline2.svg)    **Problem 7.2** Sketch some solutions to the equation [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y} = 3y-y^2.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Make sure you include at least one of each type.  ###  Solution:  ![A slope field with vertical axis y and horizontal axis t is shown. To the left of the slope field, the phase line is shown and is rotated so that it is vertical with positive infinity is at the top and negative infinity at the bottom. The points 0 and 3 are indicated on the phase line. The arrow above 3 points downward, the arrow between 0 and 3 points upward, and the arrow below 0 points downward. The values 0 and 3 corresponds to the zero isocline y equals 0 and y equals 3 in the slope field, respectively. Solutions above the line y equals 3 have negative slopes and tend to y equals 3 as t goes to infinity. Solutions between the lines y equals 0 and y equals 3 have positive slopes. These solutions tend to 3 as t goes to infinity but tend to 0 as t goes to negative infinity. Solutions below the line y equals 0 have negative slopes and tend to negative infinity as t goes to infinity.](/static/images/logisticsolutions.svg)   Phase line drawn vertically (left); Sample solution curves on [mathjaxinline](t,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane (right)        There are five fundamental solutions, depending on the initial conditions:    * If [mathjaxinline]y(0)=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the solution will be [mathjaxinline]y(t)=0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]y(0)=3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the solution will be [mathjaxinline]y(t)=3[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]\\, 0<y(0)<3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] will increase as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] increases. It tends to [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\rightarrow +\\infty \\,[/mathjaxinline] and tends to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\rightarrow -\\infty .[/mathjaxinline]     * If [mathjaxinline]y(0)>3[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] decreases as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] increases, tending to [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] without reaching [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]y(0)<0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] decreases, and [mathjaxinline]y(t) \\to -\\infty[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] grows.   [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Food for thought:** For a solution [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\, 0<y(t)<3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] is it possible that [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] tends to a limit less than [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline]?    ###  Answer:  No. If [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] tends to any number [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] between [mathjaxinline]\\, 0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, 3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] then as the solution curve levels off while approaching [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] must tend to [mathjaxinline]0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] But we know that [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)>0\\,[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]0<a<3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] so this is impossible.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Qualitative behavior of the solutions to the logistic equation", "filename": "29_autonomousequations2-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Qualitative behavior of the solutions to the logistic equation"}

{"pageid": 102, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab3", "text": "### **Standard linear form**  Every **first-order linear** ODE can be written in **standard linear form** as follows:  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = {\\color{orange}{q(t)}} ,[/mathjax]| (2.22)   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]p(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]q(t)[/mathjaxinline] can be any functions of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].  When the right hand side [mathjaxinline]q(t)[/mathjaxinline] is zero, we call the equation **homogeneous.** An equation that is not homogeneous is **inhomogeneous** .  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Homogeneous: } \\quad {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Inhomogeneous: } \\quad {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{q(t)}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      ### Models that use first order linear ODEs  First-order linear equations are common in modeling. Here are some examples.    * Temperature conduction     * Concentration diffusion     * Radioactive decay     * Bank account interest     * Simple population growth   In this lecture we will focus in on the first example, and use a model for conduction called Newton Cooling. {"pageid": 104, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab11", "text": "To understand the general solution [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] to an inhomogeneous linear ODE  [mathjax]\\text{inhomogeneous:} \\quad \\dot y + p(t)y = q(t),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      do the following:    1. Find the general solution to the associated homogeneous equation   [mathjax]\\text{homogeneous:}\\qquad \\dot y + p(t)y = 0;[/mathjax]|   ---|---      i.e., write down the general solution [mathjaxinline]y_h[/mathjaxinline].    2. Find (in some way) any **one** particular solution [mathjaxinline]y_p[/mathjaxinline] to the **inhomogeneous** ODE.     3. Add [mathjaxinline]y_p[/mathjaxinline] to the general solution of the homogeneous ODE to get the general solution to the inhomogeneous ODE.   **Summary:**  [mathjax]\\underset {{\\text{general inhomogeneous solution}}}{y} = \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\text{particular solution}}} }{y_p} + \\underset {{\\color{blue}{\\text{general homogeneous solution}}} }{y_h}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (Note that here we are using [mathjaxinline]y_h[/mathjaxinline] for the general homogeneous solution rather than a specific homogeneous solution.)  Why does this work? Superposition says that adding [mathjaxinline]y_p[/mathjaxinline] to a homogeneous solution gives a solution to the DE with right hand side [mathjaxinline]q(t)+0=q(t)[/mathjaxinline]. All solutions to the DE with right hand side [mathjaxinline]q(t)[/mathjaxinline] arise this way, since **subtracting** [mathjaxinline]y_p[/mathjaxinline] from any solution gives a solution to the DE with right hand side [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline].  The result of this section is the key point of linearity in the inhomogeneous case. It allows us to combine solutions efficiently.  Consequence of superposition for an inhomogeneous linear ODE", "filename": "02_solvingafirstorderode-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Consequence of superposition for an inhomogeneous linear ODE"}

Movement to the right is considered to be in the positive direction.](/static/images/coupled-oscillator2.svg)  Consider this ideal spring system involving two masses, [mathjaxinline]m_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]m_2[/mathjaxinline] connected by 3 springs with spring constants [mathjaxinline]k_1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]k_2[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]k_3[/mathjaxinline] respectively. Let [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] be the displacement of the mass [mathjaxinline]m_1[/mathjaxinline] away from the equilibrium position. Similarly, let [mathjaxinline]x_2[/mathjaxinline] be the displacement of the mass [mathjaxinline]m_2[/mathjaxinline] away from equilibrium. The case [mathjaxinline]x_1=x_2=0[/mathjaxinline] corresponds to the situation where neither mass is displaced from its equilibrium position.    The displacements [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x_2[/mathjaxinline] satisfy two simultaneous second order equations involving both variables. It turns out that we can eliminate [mathjaxinline]x_2[/mathjaxinline] to get a single fourth order homogeneous ODE with constant coefficients for [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m_1 m_2 x_1^{(4)} +\\left(m_2(k_1+k_2) + m_1(k_2+k_3) \\right)\\ddot{x_1} +\\left(k_1k_2+k_1k_3+k_2 k_3\\right) x_1[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.87)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      ###  How did we get the equation of the displacement of the mass in the coupled oscillator?  Let us model the coupled oscillator.  ![Three springs are attached to two masses. The left end of the leftmost spring is attached to a wall. The right end of the leftmost spring is attached to mass 1. The left end of the center spring is attached to mass 1. The right end of the center spring is attached to mass 2. The left end of the rightmost spring is attached to mass 2. The right end of the rightmost spring is attached to a wall. The leftmost spring has spring constant k sub 1. The center spring has spring constant k sub 2. The rightmost spring has spring constant k sub 3. Mass 1 is labeled m sub 1. Mass two is labeled m sub 2. The position of mass 1 is denoted by x sub 1, and x sub 1 equals 0 when mass 1 is at equilibrium. The position of mass 2 is denoted by x sub 2, and x sub 2 equals 0 when mass 2 is at equilibrium. Movement to the right is considered to be in the positive direction.](/static/images/coupled-oscillator2.svg)    * The extension or compression of spring 1 is given by [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline].     * The extension or compression of spring 2 is given by [mathjaxinline]x_2-x_1[/mathjaxinline].     * And the extension or compression of spring 3 is given by [mathjaxinline]-x_2[/mathjaxinline].   We are assuming ideal springs, that is there is no damping.        **Force on mass 1:**   There are two spring forces acting on mass 1: the force [mathjaxinline]\\, F_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] due to spring 1 and the force [mathjaxinline]\\, F_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] due to spring 2. These are given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F_1=-k_1x_1;[/mathjaxinline] | |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F_2=k_2(x_2-x_1).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.88)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Combining these using Newton's second law, we have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m_1 \\ddot x_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F_1+F_2[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -k_1x_1 + k_2(x_2-x_1)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -(k_1+k_2)x_1 + k_2x_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.89)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---           **Force on mass 2:**   Similarly, there are two forces acting on mass 2: the force [mathjaxinline]\\, F_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] from spring 2, which acts on [mathjaxinline]m_2[/mathjaxinline] with the same magnitude but opposite direction as it acts on [mathjaxinline]\\, m_1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the force [mathjaxinline]\\, F_3\\,[/mathjaxinline] from spring 3, given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F_3=- k_3x_2.[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.90)   ---|---|---|---      Again using Newton's second law, we have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m_2 \\ddot x_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -F_2+F_3[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -k_2(x_2-x_1) - k_3x_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle k_2x_1 - (k_3+k_2)x_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.91)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---           **The differential equations:**   The two equations above together form a **coupled system** of differential equations:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m_1 \\ddot x_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -(k_2+k_1)x_1 + k_2x_2,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m_2 \\ddot x_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = k_2x_1 - (k_2+k_3)x_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      These two equations together is a system of two second order linear differential equations, each with two dependent variables [mathjaxinline]\\, x_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, x_2.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The approach we will take for now is to eliminate one of the dependent variables to obtain a single equation involving only the other dependent variable.    Notice that we can write [mathjaxinline]\\, x_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\ddot{x_1}\\,[/mathjaxinline] using the first DE:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{m_1}{k_2} \\ddot x_1 +\\frac{k_1+k_2}{k_2} x_1.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.92)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Plugging this into the second DE and regrouping terms , we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{m_1 m_2}{k_2} x_1^{(4)} +\\left(\\frac{m_2(k_1+k_2)}{k_2} + \\frac{m_1(k_2+k_3) }{k_2} \\right)\\ddot{x_1} +\\left(- k_2 +\\frac{(k_1+k_2)(k_2+k_3)}{k_2}\\right) x_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.93)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Multiplying by [mathjaxinline]k_2[/mathjaxinline], we have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m_1 m_2 x_1^{(4)} +\\left(m_2(k_1+k_2) + m_1(k_2+k_3) \\right)\\ddot{x_1} +\\left(k_1k_2+k_1k_3+k_2 k_3\\right) x_1[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.94)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This is a fourth order homogeneous constant coefficient ODE for [mathjaxinline]x_1. \\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]    We will learn a general method to set up and solve systems of linear differential equations and higher order linear ODEs in _2x2 systems of Differential Equations_ and _Linear Algebra and Systems of Differential Equations_. We will revisit the coupled oscillator and be able to deal with coupled spring systems with many springs and masses then.    [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Question 2.1** How do we solve a higher order ODE such as the one above?  **Answer:**   Use characteristic polynomials in the same way as we did to solve second order ODEs with constant coefficients. The characteristic polynomial of the DE above is of 4th order. It has 4 (possibly complex) roots counted with multiplicity.    For second order linear homogeneous ODEs, we need 2 linearly independent solutions corresponding to the 2 characteristic roots. For an [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order linear ODE, we need [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] linearly independent solutions. What does linear independence mean for a set of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] functions? Linear independence of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] functions is a much more sophisticated notion than linear independence of [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] functions.    Our first task in this lecture is to discuss carefully what we mean by linear independence and to define dimension. These ideas are essential to describing solutions to higher order ODEs.    Motivation: the coupled oscillator", "filename": "08_higherorder-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Motivation: the coupled oscillator"}

{"pageid": 108, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@33_numericalmethods/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@33_numericalmethods-tab7", "text": "**Question 7.1** How can we decide whether answers obtained numerically can be trusted?  Here are some heuristic tests. (\u201cHeuristic\" means that loosely speaking, these tests work in practice, but they are not proved to work always.)    * **Self-consistency:** Solution curves should not cross! If numerically computed solution curves cross, a smaller step size is needed. (E.g., try the mathlet \u201cEuler's Method\" with [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}=y^2-x[/mathjaxinline], step size [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], and starting points [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](0,1/2)[/mathjaxinline].)     * **Convergence as** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{h \\to 0}}[/mathjaxinline] **:** The estimate for [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] at a fixed later time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] should converge to the true value as [mathjaxinline]h \\to 0[/mathjaxinline]. If shrinking [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] causes the estimate to change a lot, then [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] is probably not small enough yet. (E.g., try the mathlet \u201cEuler's Method\" with [mathjaxinline]y'=y^2-x[/mathjaxinline] with starting point [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] and various step sizes.)     * **Structural stability:** Small changes in the DE's parameters should not change the outcome completely. If small changes in the parameters drastically change the outcome, the answer should not be trusted.    *  **Stability:** Small changes in the DE's initial conditions do not change the outcome much. One reason for instability could be a separatrix, a curve such that nearby starting points on different sides lead to qualitatively different outcomes; this is not a fault of the numerical method, but rather an instability in the answer.   Tests for reliability", "filename": "33_numericalmethods-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Tests for reliability"}

Here is another example demonstrating this.  **Example 11.2** Draw the solution curves for [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle y' = \\frac{2y}{x}[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:** Here [mathjaxinline]f(x,y) = \\frac{2y}{x},\\,[/mathjaxinline] which is undefined when [mathjaxinline]x=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] so things might go wrong along the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis, and in fact they **do** go wrong.  Solve the ODE by separation of variables:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{2y}{x} \\qquad (x\\neq 0)[/mathjaxinline] | | (6.7)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{2 \\, dx}{x} \\qquad (\\textrm{assuming also that }\\, \\, y \\neq 0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.8)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\frac{dy}{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int \\frac{2 \\, dx}{x}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.9)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln |y|[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 2 \\ln |x| + C \\qquad (\\textrm{for some constant } \\, C)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.10)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\pm e^{2 \\ln |x| + C}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.11)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\pm |x|^2 e^C[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.12)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = c x^2\\qquad (x\\neq 0),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.13)      where [mathjaxinline]\\, c\\, \\colon =\\pm e^C,\\,[/mathjaxinline] which can be any nonzero real number. To bring back the solution [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline], we allow [mathjaxinline]c=0[/mathjaxinline] as well.  ![ ](/static/images/u2s1_halfparabolas.svg)   Several half parabolas as solution curves to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle y' = \\frac{2y}{x}[/mathjaxinline]      Weird behavior happens along [mathjaxinline]x=0\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]y' = \\frac{2y}{x}[/mathjaxinline] is not even defined:    * Through any point [mathjaxinline]\\, (0,b)\\,[/mathjaxinline] on the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis, there is **no** solution curve. The existence theorem does not apply.     * Geometrically, the parabolas become tangent at the origin. This would be ruled out by uniqueness if the uniqueness theorem applied. The full parabolas are not solutions; the solution curves are half parabolas defined for either all [mathjaxinline]\\, x<0\\,[/mathjaxinline] or all [mathjaxinline]\\, x>0[/mathjaxinline].   Both existence and uniqueness apply to every point outside the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis. The rest of the plane (outside the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis) is covered with good solution curves, one through each point, none touching or crossing the others.    There is no connection between any half parabola on the left and any half parabola on the right.    When Existence and Uniqueness fails", "filename": "28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab11-text3.html", "title": "When Existence and Uniqueness fails"}

{"pageid": 115, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation7_for_edx/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation7_for_edx-tab5", "text": "**The setup:**    ![A sketch of the cross-section of a boat is represented as approximately a rounded rectangle. The central vertical axis is denoted by a dashed line. A horizontal line is drawn to represent the water partially submerging the boat. The area of the boat that is partially submerged is labeled A. The height of this area is labeled d. The beam of the boat at the waterline is labeled b. The center of gravity, labeled 0 comma G sub y, lies along the central axis and above the waterline. The center of buoyancy, labeled 0 comma B sub y of zero, lies along the central axis and below the waterline. A coordinate system with horizontal axis x and vertical axis y is introduced with the origin set at the bottom of the boat so that the y axis is aligned with the central axis. See text below for more details regarding the meaning of the variables.](/static/images/u1c3s2_r7_boatflat.svg)    Consider a boat with a symmetrical cross-section sitting flat in the water, as shown in the figure above. (Assume for simplicity that the boat has the same cross-section along its length.) Take the origin[mathjaxinline]\\, (0,0)\\,[/mathjaxinline] of the coordinate system to be at the bottom-center of the boat, and the [mathjaxinline]x-[/mathjaxinline]axis to be along the bottom of the boat.    Let the **center of gravity** be at the coordinates [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(0,G_{y}\\right).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, G_{y}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is independent of the rotation angle, [mathjaxinline]\\theta .\\,[/mathjaxinline] It is determined by the shape and mass distribution of the boat.    The **center of buoyancy** varies as the the rotation angle [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta \\,[/mathjaxinline] varies. Let its coordinates be [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(B_{x}\\left(\\theta \\right),B_{y}\\left(\\theta \\right)\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] when the boat is rotated by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta .\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The center of buoyancy is a purely geometric computation once you know where the waterline is; but where the waterline is does depend on the distribution of mass of the boat, even when the boat is at equilibrium.  Below are a list of some parameters of the boat that are independent of the rotation angle [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta[/mathjaxinline]:    * the **weight** of the boat, [mathjaxinline]\\, W\\,[/mathjaxinline] (in Newtons)     * the **beam** of the boat at the waterline, [mathjaxinline]\\, b \\,[/mathjaxinline] (in meters)     * the **height of the waterline** at the center of the boat, [mathjaxinline]\\, d \\,[/mathjaxinline] (in meters)     * the **area of (the cross-section of) displaced fluid when the boat is flat** (the green region in the figure above), [mathjaxinline]A\\,[/mathjaxinline] (in squared meters)     * the location of the **center of gravity** , [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(0,G_{y}\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] (each coordinate in meters)     * the location of the **center of buoyancy when boat is sitting flat** , [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(B_{x}\\left(0\\right),B_{y}\\left(0\\right)\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] (each coordinate in meters)   Assume also that the boat has **rectangular sides in the range of rotation angles** that are considered, as shown in the figure above. {"pageid": 117, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@12_rlc/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@12_rlc-tab6", "text": "**Example 6.1** A resistor of resistance [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline] and an inductor of inductance [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] are attached in parallel. A voltage source provides the combination with AC voltage of angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline]. Find the gain and phase lag of the resistor current relative to the total current (through the voltage source).  **Solution:**  ![Schematic of circuit.](/static/images/ParallelRL2.svg)  Let [mathjaxinline]V(t)[/mathjaxinline] be the sinusoidal voltage provided.  **Unknown functions:** Let [mathjaxinline]I_1[/mathjaxinline] be the resistor current. Let [mathjaxinline]I_2[/mathjaxinline] be the inductor current. Let [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline] be the total current.  **Equations:** Physics says  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle V[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = R I_1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle V[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = L \\dot{I}_2[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle I[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = I_1 + I_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The same relationships hold between the complex replacements:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\widetilde{V}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = R \\widetilde{I}_1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\widetilde{V}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = L \\dot{\\widetilde{I}}_2[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\widetilde{I}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\widetilde{I}_1 + \\widetilde{I}_2[/mathjaxinline] |  |      (because taking real parts is compatible with real scalar multiplication and with taking derivatives).  Suppose that [mathjaxinline]\\widetilde{V} = e^{i \\omega t}[/mathjaxinline]. (In general, [mathjaxinline]\\widetilde{V} = \\gamma e^{i \\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] for some [mathjaxinline]\\gamma \\in \\mathbb {C}[/mathjaxinline], but then everything will be multiplied by [mathjaxinline]\\gamma[/mathjaxinline], so when we take a ratio to get complex gain, [mathjaxinline]\\gamma[/mathjaxinline] will disappear.) How do we solve for the other three functions [mathjaxinline]\\widetilde{I_1}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\widetilde{I_2}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\widetilde{I}[/mathjaxinline]?  In the steady-state solution,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\widetilde{I_1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\alpha _1 e^{i \\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\widetilde{I_2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\alpha _2 e^{i \\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\widetilde{I}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\beta e^{i \\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      for some unknown complex numbers [mathjaxinline]\\alpha _1,\\alpha _2,\\beta[/mathjaxinline]. To find [mathjaxinline]\\alpha _1,\\alpha _2,\\beta[/mathjaxinline], substitute into the three complex replacement equations:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = R \\alpha _1 e^{i \\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = L \\alpha _2 e^{i \\omega t} i \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\beta e^{i \\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\alpha _1 e^{i \\omega t} + \\alpha _2 e^{i \\omega t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      This simplifies to  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = R \\alpha _1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = L \\alpha _2 i \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\beta[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\alpha _1 + \\alpha _2.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      So [mathjaxinline]\\alpha _1 = 1/R[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\alpha _2 = 1/(L i \\omega )[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\beta = 1/R + 1/(L i \\omega )[/mathjaxinline].The complex gain of [mathjaxinline]I_1[/mathjaxinline] relative to [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline] is the complex constant  [mathjax]G = \\frac{\\alpha _1}{\\beta } = \\frac{1/R}{1/R + 1/(L i \\omega )}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The gain is [mathjaxinline]|G|[/mathjaxinline], and the phase lag is [mathjaxinline]-\\arg G[/mathjaxinline].  Worked example: a parallel RL circuit", "filename": "12_rlc-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Worked example: a parallel RL circuit"}

{"pageid": 120, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab13", "text": "**Beats** occur when two very nearby pitches are sounded simultaneously.  **Problem 13.1** Consider two sinusoid sound waves of angular frequencies [mathjaxinline]\\omega +\\epsilon[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\omega -\\epsilon[/mathjaxinline], say [mathjaxinline]\\cos ((\\omega +\\epsilon )t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos ((\\omega -\\epsilon )t)[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]\\epsilon[/mathjaxinline] is much smaller than [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline]. What happens when they are superimposed?  **Solution:** The sum is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos ((\\omega +\\epsilon )t) + \\cos ((\\omega -\\epsilon )t)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathrm{Re\\, }(e^{i(\\omega +\\epsilon ) t}) + \\mathrm{Re\\, }(e^{i(\\omega -\\epsilon ) t})[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathrm{Re\\, }(e^{i\\omega t} (e^{i \\epsilon t} + e^{-i\\epsilon t}))[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathrm{Re\\, }(e^{i\\omega t} (2 \\cos \\epsilon t))[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = (2 \\cos \\epsilon t) \\mathrm{Re\\, }(e^{i\\omega t})[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 2 (\\cos \\epsilon t) (\\cos \\omega t).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The function [mathjaxinline]\\cos \\omega t[/mathjaxinline] oscillates rapidly between [mathjaxinline]\\pm 1[/mathjaxinline]. Multiplying it by the slowly varying function [mathjaxinline]2 \\cos \\epsilon t[/mathjaxinline] produces a rapid oscillation between [mathjaxinline]\\pm 2 \\cos \\epsilon t[/mathjaxinline], so one hears a sound wave of angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] whose amplitude is the slowly varying function [mathjaxinline]|2 \\cos \\epsilon t|[/mathjaxinline].  ![ ](/static/images/beats05.svg)  **Figure :** A plot of [mathjaxinline]2\\left(\\cos \\epsilon t\\right)\\left(\\cos \\omega t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]\\epsilon =1/8[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\omega =4[/mathjaxinline].  ### Practical application  You hear beats when tuning the strings of an instrument, or in tuning one instrument to another. The waa waa waa sound you hear is exactly these beats. The higher the frequency of the beats, the more out of tune. As the instruments or strings become closer and closer in tune, the frequency of the beats diminish until you cannot hear them at all.  Observe that changing the phase of one signal with respect to the other doesn't change the frequency of the beats! This is important. If you could hear phase shifts, it would be very difficult to tune your instrument by ear.  Beats", "filename": "06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Beats"}

{"pageid": 122, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@29_autonomousequations2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@29_autonomousequations2-tab5", "text": "### Phase line  We repeat the example in the video to introduce **phase lines** explicitly.    Recall the first order autonomous DE in the video:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{y}=f(y)= ry-w\\qquad (r,w>0).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.30)   ---|---|---|---      The variable [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] models the amount of money (in dollars) in a savings account; [mathjaxinline]r\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the interest rate (in units of [mathjaxinline]\\text{year}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]); and [mathjaxinline]\\, w\\,[/mathjaxinline] (in dollars per year) is the rate of money being stolen out of the account.    To find the qualitative behavior of the solutions, we follow the two steps described before.    1. Find the critical points.   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle f(y)=ry-w=0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y=\\frac{w}{r}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.31)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      So [mathjaxinline]\\, y=w/r\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the constant solution.    2. Determine the intervals of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] in which [mathjaxinline]f(y)>0[/mathjaxinline] and in which [mathjaxinline]f(y)<0[/mathjaxinline]. One way to do this is by graphing [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline].   ![The vertical axis is labeled dy over dt, and the horizontal axis is labeled y. The line f of y equals r y minus w is plotted as a line with positive slope r and positive intercept on the horizontal axis equal to w over r. When y is greater than w over r, f of y is greater than 0 which is indicated by an arrow on the horizontal axis pointing rightward. When y is less than w over r, y is less than 0, which is indiciated by an arrow on the horizontal axis pointing leftward.](/static/images/autonomouslinear.svg)    For [mathjaxinline]\\, y>w/r,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)>0[/mathjaxinline] and any solution [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] is increasing; for [mathjaxinline]\\, y<w/r,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)<0[/mathjaxinline] and any solution [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] is decreasing.    We can summarize the above information by adding arrows on the (horizontal) [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis as in the video. The critical points divides the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis into intervals. We place a right arrow (in the [mathjaxinline]+y[/mathjaxinline] direction) to each interval of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)>0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and any solution [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] is increasing. Similarly, we place a left arrow (in the [mathjaxinline]-y[/mathjaxinline] direction) to each interval where [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)<0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and solutions are decreasing. The [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis with this extra information is called a phase line.  **Definition 5.1** The **phase line** of a first order autonomous DE [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}=f(y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a plot of the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis with all critical points and with an arrow in each interval between the critical points indicating whether solutions increase or decrease  In our example, the phase line is:  ![The phase line is a horizontal line with positive infinity labeled on the right and negative infinity labeled on the left. The value w over r is indicated. An arrow to the right of w over r is pointing rightward and an arrow to the left of w over r is pointing leftward.](/static/images/u2s2_horizontalphaseline1.svg)   Phase line of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}=ry-w\\, \\, (r,w>0)[/mathjaxinline]  If the phase line is drawn vertically, the qualitative behaviour of solution curves can be read directly from it, as you see in the diagram below.  ![A slope field with vertical axis y and horizontal axis t is shown. To the left of the slope field, the phase line is shown and is rotated so that it is vertical with positive infinity at the top and negative infinity at the bottom. The arrow above w over r points upward while the arrow below w over r points downward. The value w over r corresponds to the zero isocline y equals w over r in the slope field. Solutions above this value have positive slopes and tend to infinity as t goes to infinity. Solutions below this value of negative slopes and tend to negative infinity as t goes to infinity.](/static/images/autonomousphaselinesolutioncurves2.svg)   Vertical phase line (left); Solution curves on the [mathjaxinline]ty[/mathjaxinline]-plane (right)     **Example 5.2** Use the phase line above to determine what happens to solutions with different initial conditions as time passes.  **Solution:**    * If [mathjaxinline]y(0)=w/r,\\,[/mathjaxinline] which is the critical point, then the solution will be [mathjaxinline]y(t)=w/r[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. This corresponds to the constant solution shown on [mathjaxinline](t,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane in the figure above.     * If [mathjaxinline]y(0)>w/r,\\,[/mathjaxinline] then the up arrow (in the positive [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] direction) on the phase line tells us that as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] increases, [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] increases and will tend to [mathjaxinline]+\\infty .\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This corresponds to a solution curve above the horizontal solution, such as the one shown on the [mathjaxinline](t,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane above.     * If [mathjaxinline]y(0)< w/r,\\,[/mathjaxinline] then the down arrow (in the negative [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] direction) on the phase line says that as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\,[/mathjaxinline] increases, [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] decreases and will tend to [mathjaxinline]-\\infty .\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This corresponds to a solution curve below the horizontal solution, such as the one shown on the [mathjaxinline](t,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane above.   Phase line", "filename": "29_autonomousequations2-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Phase line"}

{"pageid": 126, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab9", "text": "We show that [mathjaxinline]e^{it} = \\cos t + i \\sin t[/mathjaxinline] satisfies the exponential law.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle e^{it_1} e^{it_2}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(\\cos t_1 + i \\sin t_1 \\right)\\left(\\cos t_2 + i\\sin t_2 \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.32)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Multiplying out and collecting real and imaginary parts, this is equal to  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\phantom{e^{it_1} e^{it_2}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\underbrace{ \\left(\\cos t_1\\cos t_2 - \\sin t_1\\sin t_2 \\right)}_{\\cos (t_1+t_2)} + i \\underbrace{\\left(\\sin t_1 \\cos t_2 + \\sin t_2 \\cos t_1 \\right)}_{\\sin (t_1+t_2)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.33)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos (t_1 + t_2) + i \\sin (t_1+t_2)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.34)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{i(t_1+t_2)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.35)      Note that this gives a handy way to remember the trigonometric addition formulas!  Justification using exponential law", "filename": "03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Justification using exponential law"}

{"pageid": 127, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab1", "text": "**Objectives**    * Find the general solution to any **homogeneous** first order (linear) ODE using **separation of variables** .     * Find **a particular solution** to any **inhomogeneous** first order linear ODE using **variation of parameters** .     * Find the **general solution** to any **inhomogeneous** first order differential equation by first finding the solution to the associated homogeneous function, finding one particular solution, and applying **superposition** .     * Solve **initial value problems** for **first order linear** ODEs.
