{"pageid": 128, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab7", "text": "**Example 7.1** What is the general solution to  [mathjax]\\ddot{y} +5 \\dot{y} + 6y = 0\\; ?[/mathjax]| (3.74)   ---|---       **Solution:** The function [mathjaxinline]y=e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the DE exactly when [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] is a roots of the characteristic polynomial. Since the characteristic polynomial of the DE is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle p(r)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle r^2 +5 r + 6\\, =\\, (r+2)(r+3),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.75)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      the two functions [mathjaxinline]e^{-2t}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]e^{-3t}[/mathjaxinline] are solutions. Therefore, the general solution to the DE is  [mathjax]c_1 e^{-2t} + c_2 e^{-3t},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline] are arbitrary constants.     **Example 7.2** What is the specific solution to the DE above that also satisfies the initial conditions  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(0)=0;[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}(0)=1?[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.76)   ---|---|---|---|---       **Solution:** We use the **two** initial conditions to determine the **two** parameters in the general solution [mathjaxinline]y(t)=c_1 e^{-2t} + c_2 e^{-3t}[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1+c_2[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.77)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -2c_1-3c_2[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.78)      Solving these two equations simultaneously, we have [mathjaxinline]c_1=1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2=-1[/mathjaxinline]. So the solution that satisfies the initial conditions is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle y(t)=e^{-2t} - e^{-3t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.79)   ---|---|---|---      Here is a sketch of the graph of the solution:  ![The function y of t starts at the origin in the y versus t plane. It first increases with increasing t, then decreases and approaches the horizontal axis y equals 0 as t goes to infinity.](/static/images/u1c2s3_1overdampedcurve.svg)   Graph of [mathjaxinline]y(t)=e^{-2t} - e^{-3t}\\,[/mathjaxinline]      Here are the graphs of solutions to the DE above that satisfy other initial conditions:  ![The different solutions start at different heights in the y versus t plane. Some start with positive slope, negative slope, or zero slope, but all of them tend towards the horizontal axis y equals 0 as t goes to infinity.](/static/images/u1c2s3_3overdampedcurve.svg)   Graphs of solutions to [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y} +5 \\dot{y} + 6y = 0[/mathjaxinline] and different initial conditions.   The initial positions [mathjaxinline]y(0)[/mathjaxinline] are different for the different curves.   Blue curves satisfy [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}(0)>0;\\,[/mathjaxinline] green curves satisfy [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}(0)<0;\\,[/mathjaxinline] orange curve satisfies [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}=0[/mathjaxinline].    Characteristic polynomial", "filename": "06_higherorderlinearodes-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Characteristic polynomial"}

{"pageid": 129, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@08_higherorder/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@08_higherorder-tab7", "text": "It turns out that although a vector space can have different bases, each basis has **the same number of vectors** in it.  **Definition 7.1** The **dimension** of a vector space is the number of vectors in **any** basis.  **Example 7.2** The vector space [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbb {R}^3\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional real vector space, since there are 3 vectors in the basis [mathjaxinline]\\, (1,0,0),\\, (0,1,0),\\, (0,0,1).[/mathjaxinline]     **Example 7.3** The space of solutions to the homogeneous equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y} + \\dot{y} - 6y = 0[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional, since the basis [mathjaxinline]e^{2t},e^{-3t}[/mathjaxinline] has [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] elements. (Every other basis for the same vector space also has [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] elements.  **Example 7.4** The space of solutions to [mathjaxinline]\\ \\dot{y}=3y\\,[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional.  In the examples involving differential equations above, the dimension equals the order of the homogeneous linear ODE. It turns out that this holds in general:  **Dimension theorem.** **The dimension of the space of solutions to an [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order homogeneous ODE with constant coefficients is [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline].**  In other words, the number of parameters needed in the general solution to an [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order homogeneous ODE with constant coefficients is [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline].    (The theorem is also true for [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order homogeneous linear ODEs with variable coefficients provided that they are continuous and the leading coefficient is never zero.)    This theorem is a consequence of the existence and uniqueness theorem as we will see shortly.    Dimension", "filename": "08_higherorder-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Dimension"}

{"pageid": 130, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab6", "text": "**Variation of parameters** is a method for solving inhomogeneous linear ODEs. Recall a first-order inhomogeneous linear ODE in standard linear form:  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p(t) {\\color{blue}{y}} = {\\color{orange}{q(t)}} .[/mathjax]| (2.28)   ---|---      Let's see how variation of parameters works in the following example.  **Example 6.1** Solve [mathjaxinline]\\, t \\dot{y} + 2y = t^5[/mathjaxinline] on the interval [mathjaxinline](0,\\infty )[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:**   **Step 1.** The associated homogeneous equation is [mathjaxinline]t \\dot{y} + 2y = 0[/mathjaxinline], or equivalently, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y} + \\frac{2}{t} y = 0[/mathjaxinline]. Solve by separation of variables:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac{2}{t} y[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac{2}{t} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln |y|[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -2 \\ln t + C \\qquad \\text{(since } t>0)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c e^{-2 \\ln t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c t^{-2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      (Here, we have recovered the [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline] solution by allowing [mathjaxinline]c=0[/mathjaxinline].)   Choose one nonzero solution, say [mathjaxinline]y_h = t^{-2}[/mathjaxinline].  **Step 2.** Substitute [mathjaxinline]y = u(t) t^{-2}[/mathjaxinline] into the inhomogeneous equation: the left side is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle t \\dot{y} + 2y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t(\\dot{u} t^{-2} + u\\, (-2t^{-3})) + 2 u t^{-2}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.29)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t^{-1} \\dot{u}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.30)       **Note:** Observe the cancellation of two terms after the substitution. If you do not observe such a cancellation, you know you have made an computational error. The reason behind this cancellation will be explained shortly.  Using the result of our substitution, the inhomogeneous equation becomes  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t^{-1} \\dot{u}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t^5[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      **Step 3.** Solve for [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{u}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t^6[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{t^7}{7} + c.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Step 4.** The general solution to the inhomogeneous equation is  [mathjax]y = u t^{-2} = \\left(\\frac{t^7}{7} + c \\right) t^{-2} = \\frac{t^5}{7} + c t^{-2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (If you want, check by direct substitution that this really is a solution.)  **Variation of parameters general procedure**    1. Find a nonzero solution, say [mathjaxinline]y_h[/mathjaxinline], of the associated homogeneous ODE   [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{y_h}}} + p(t){\\color{blue}{y_h}} = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---     2. Substitute [mathjaxinline]\\, y = uy_h[/mathjaxinline] into the **inhomogeneous** equation, [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p(t) {\\color{blue}{y}} = {\\color{orange}{q(t)}}[/mathjaxinline] to find an equation for the unknown function [mathjaxinline]u=u(t)[/mathjaxinline].   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}(uy_h) +puy_h[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.31)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\iff \\dot u y_h + u\\dot y_h + puy_h[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.32)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\iff \\dot u y_h + u \\underbrace{(\\dot y_h + py_h)}_{=0}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.33)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\iff \\dot u y_h[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.34)      Note that the term in parentheses is zero because [mathjaxinline]y_h[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the homogeneous differential equation.    3. Solve [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot u = \\frac{q}{y_h}[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]u(t)[/mathjaxinline] by integration.     4. Once the general [mathjaxinline]u(t)[/mathjaxinline] is found, don't forget to multiply it by the homogeneous solution [mathjaxinline]y_h(t)[/mathjaxinline] to find [mathjaxinline]y=u(t)y_h(t)[/mathjaxinline], the general solution to the inhomogeneous equation.   The idea is that the functions of the form [mathjaxinline]cy_h[/mathjaxinline] are solutions to the **homogeneous** equation; maybe we can get solutions to the **inhomogeneous** equation by allowing the parameter [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] to vary, i.e., if we replace it by a nonconstant function [mathjaxinline]u(t)[/mathjaxinline].  Inhomogeneous equations: variation of parameters", "filename": "02_solvingafirstorderode-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Inhomogeneous equations: variation of parameters"}

{"pageid": 131, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab1", "text": "**Objectives**    * Represent a linear combination of a sine and cosine with the same frequency as a **sinusoidal function** .     * Describe and graph sinusoidal functions in terms of **amplitude** and **phase angles** .     * Write the equation for a sinusoidal function from a graph.     * **Graph oscillatory solutions** to spring-mass systems with no external force.     * Optional: Understand how two sinusoids of close frequencies create **beats** .   Objectives", "filename": "06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 132, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@08_higherorder/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@08_higherorder-tab5", "text": "**Definition 5.1** Vectors [mathjaxinline]\\, v_1,\\ldots ,\\, v_n\\,[/mathjaxinline] are **linearly** **dependent** (think redundant) if at least one of them is a linear combination of the others. Otherwise, call them **linearly** **independent** .  **Example 5.2** In a vector space consisting of functions, each function is a vector. The functions [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{2t},\\, e^{-3t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are linearly **independent** .     **Note:** For a set of 2 vectors, the definition of linear dependence and linear independence reduces to what we have learned before: [mathjaxinline]\\, v_1,\\, v_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are linearly dependent if one is a scalar multiple of the other. Otherwise, they are linearly independent.     **Example 5.3** The functions [mathjaxinline]f_1=e^{2t},\\, f_2=e^{-3t}, \\, f_3=e^{2t}+e^{-3t}[/mathjaxinline] are linearly **dependent** . The third function is a linear combination of the first two:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f_3\\, =\\, f_1+f_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.95)   ---|---|---|---      In fact, each function is a linear combination of the other two:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f_1\\, =\\, e^{2t}\\, =\\, \\left(e^{2t}+e^{-3t}\\right) -e^{-3t}\\, =\\, f_3-f_2,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.96)   ---|---|---|---      and similarly [mathjaxinline]\\, f_2\\, =\\, f_3-f_1.[/mathjaxinline]     **Equivalent definition:** Vectors [mathjaxinline]\\, v_1,\\ldots ,v_n\\,[/mathjaxinline] are **linearly** **dependent** if there exist numbers [mathjaxinline]c_1,\\ldots ,c_n[/mathjaxinline] **not all zero** such that [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1 v_1 + \\cdots + c_n v_n = 0[/mathjaxinline].  In example 5.3, we wrote  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f_3=f_1+f_2,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f_1=f_3-f_2,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f_2=f_3-f_1.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.97)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      A more symmetric way to describe this is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f_1+f_2-f_3[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.98)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **Example 5.4** The three functions [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{2t},\\, e^{-3t}, \\, 5e^{2t}+7e^{-3t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are linearly **dependent** , because  [mathjax](-5) e^{2t} + (-7) e^{-3t} + (1) (5e^{2t}+7e^{-3t}) = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The meaning of linear dependence is that at least one of the functions on the list is redundant (and can be expressed as a linear combination of the others.)    Linear independence", "filename": "08_higherorder-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Linear independence"}

{"pageid": 133, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab12", "text": "The system response for an unforced spring-mass-dashpot system with small damping term [mathjaxinline]\\, (b^2<4km)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is called a **damped sinusoid** and is of the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle x(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(A e^{(-b/2m)t}\\right) \\cos \\left(\\omega t -\\phi \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.29)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      In the last problem, we have just seen that the exponential factor does not affect the frequency of the oscillations: [mathjaxinline]\\, x(t) \\,[/mathjaxinline] crosses the equilibrium whenever the pure sinusoid [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos \\left(\\omega t -\\phi \\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] does.  Therefore, the period [mathjaxinline]\\, P\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the time lag [mathjaxinline]\\, t_0\\,[/mathjaxinline] still make sense and have the same formulas as for the pure sinusoid [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos \\left(\\omega t -\\phi \\right)\\, :[/mathjaxinline]  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, t_0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\phi /\\omega \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.30)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, P[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2\\pi /\\omega .[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.31)      Because the graph of [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is not truly periodic\u2013its amplitude is decreasing, we call [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] the **pseudo-period** .  For damped sinusoids, the time lag [mathjaxinline]\\, t_0\\,[/mathjaxinline] is easier to see from the shifts of zeros. The value of [mathjaxinline]t_0[/mathjaxinline] is the time difference between a zero of [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] and a corresponding zero of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos (\\omega t)\\,[/mathjaxinline].    (You can check using calculus that the local extrema of [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] are no longer at the same [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]-values as those of the pure sinusoid [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos \\left(\\omega t -\\phi \\right).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] However, they are still equally spaced. Consecutive local maxima of a damped sinusoid are still a full period [mathjaxinline]\\, P\\,[/mathjaxinline] apart.)    A series of exercises in recitation will take you through the steps of graphing a damped sinusoid.  Revisiting spring-mass-dashpot system", "filename": "06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Revisiting spring-mass-dashpot system"}

{"pageid": 134, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab9", "text": "The ERF works equally well for complex exponential inputs.  **Example 9.1** Use ERF to find a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x + x = e^{2it}.[/mathjaxinline]  **Solution:** In operator notation, this differential equation can be written as  [mathjax](D^2+1)x = e^{2it}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      By the ERF, a particular solution is given by  [mathjax]x_p = \\frac{e^{rt}}{r^2+1} = \\frac{e^{2it}}{(2i)^2+1} = \\frac{-1}{3}e^{2it}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  ERF and complex roots", "filename": "09_exponentialresponse-tab9-text1.html", "title": "ERF and complex roots"}

Then, to verify your drawing, choose the ODE from the dropdown menu in the mathlet below.  **Question 2.1** For a general differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x, y),\\,[/mathjaxinline] if a straight line is an integral curve, how is it related to the isoclines of the equation?  ###  See explanation  If there is a straight line solution [mathjaxinline]\\, y=mx+b\\,[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\, y'(x)=m,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the straight line solution curve is (part of) the [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline]-isocline. {"pageid": 136, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@01_odeintro/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@01_odeintro-tab4", "text": "Here we will see how the differential equation for our secret function appears when modeling a natural phenomenon \u2013 the population growth of a colony of cells.  In this example we'll model the number of yeast cells in a batch of dough. As we work through this example, pay careful attention to the assumptions we make, and how the **initial condition** plays a role in the resulting differential equation.  **The system**  For our system, we assume we have a colony of yeast cells in a batch of bread dough. The first step is to identify the variables, the units, and give them names.  [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] |  number of cells   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] |  time measured in seconds      We also need to set some initial condition, [mathjaxinline]y_0[/mathjaxinline], the number of cells that we begin with at [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline]. In this system, this might be the number of yeast cells in a yeast packet.  ![Yeast packet](/static/images/yeast_pack_scaled.png)   Photo by Hellahulla, Wikimedia Commons. (CC BY-SA) 4.0  **A differential model**  If [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] denotes the number of yeast cells, what can we say about the derivative [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline]? The derivative represents the rate at which the number of cells is growing. How should it depend on the number of cells? In nature, cells given plenty of space and food tend to divide through mitosis regularly. If we assume that each cell is dividing independently of all other cells, then doubling the number of cells should double the rate at which new cells are born. In fact, multiplying the number of cells by any scalar factor should do the same to the derivative. So this directly implies that the growth rate of cells is proportional to the number of cells:  [mathjax]\\dot{y} \\propto y.[/mathjax]| (2.2)   ---|---      We can make this into a true equation by simply inserting a proportionality constant [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], such that  [mathjax]\\dot{y} = ay.[/mathjax]| (2.3)   ---|---      We say that [mathjaxinline]1/a[/mathjaxinline] is a \u201ccharacteristic\" timescale for our problem, setting the rate at which the cells divide. A solution to the above differential equation is  [mathjax]y= y_0e^{at},[/mathjax]| (2.4)   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]y_0[/mathjaxinline] is the number of yeast cells we started with at [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline]. In our case, we assume that [mathjaxinline]y_0[/mathjaxinline] is the number of yeast cells in a packet, which is about [mathjaxinline]180[/mathjaxinline] billion yeast cells.  Cell division", "filename": "01_odeintro-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Cell division"}

{"pageid": 138, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab5", "text": "Homogeneous first-order linear ODEs can always be solved by separation of variables:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y} + p(t) \\, y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dt} + p(t) \\, y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle - p(t) \\, y[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle - p(t) \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Choose any antiderivative [mathjaxinline]P(t)[/mathjaxinline] of [mathjaxinline]p(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln |y|[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -P(t) + C[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle |y|[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{-P(t) + C}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\pm e^{-P(t) + C}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c e^{-P(t)},[/mathjaxinline] |  |      where [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is any number (we brought back the solution [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline] corresponding to [mathjaxinline]c=0[/mathjaxinline]).  **Note:** If you choose a different antiderivative, it will have the form [mathjaxinline]P(t) + d[/mathjaxinline] for some constant [mathjaxinline]d[/mathjaxinline], and then the new [mathjaxinline]e^{-P(t)}[/mathjaxinline] is just a constant [mathjaxinline]e^{-d}[/mathjaxinline] times the old one, so the set of all scalar multiples of the function [mathjaxinline]e^{-P(t)}[/mathjaxinline] is the same as before.  **Conclusion:**   **General solution to first-order homogeneous linear ODE.** Let [mathjaxinline]p(t)[/mathjaxinline] be a continuous function on an open interval [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline]. This ensures that [mathjaxinline]p(t)[/mathjaxinline] has an antiderivative [mathjaxinline]P(t)[/mathjaxinline]. The general solution to [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y} + p(t) \\, y = 0[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{y = c e^{-P(t)}}} ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is any real number. The parameter [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] can be determined from an initial condition.  Homogeneous equations: separation of variables", "filename": "02_solvingafirstorderode-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Homogeneous equations: separation of variables"}

{"pageid": 140, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab11", "text": "Now we can write complex numbers [mathjaxinline]z= a+bi[/mathjaxinline] in polar form as [mathjaxinline]re^{i\\theta } = r\\cos (\\theta ) + ir\\sin (\\theta ).[/mathjaxinline]  **Test for equality** of two nonzero complex numbers in polar form:  [mathjax]r_1 e^{i\\theta _1} = r_2 e^{i \\theta _2} \\quad \\textrm{if and only if}\\quad r_1 = r_2 \\; \\textrm{ and }\\; \\theta _1 = \\theta _2 + 2\\pi k \\textrm{ for some integer } k.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (This assumes that [mathjaxinline]r_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]r_2[/mathjaxinline] are positive real numbers, and that [mathjaxinline]\\theta _1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta _2[/mathjaxinline] are real numbers.)  Some arithmetic operations on complex numbers are easy in polar form:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\textrm{multiplication: } \\qquad[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad (r_1 e^{i\\theta _1})(r_2 e^{i\\theta _2})[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle r_1 r_2 e^{i(\\theta _1 + \\theta _2)}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\quad \\textrm{(multiply absolute values, add angles)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.42)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{reciprocal:}\\qquad[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{r e^{i\\theta }}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{r} e^{-i\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] |  |  | (3.43)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{division:}\\qquad[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{r_1 e^{i\\theta _1}}{r_2 e^{i\\theta _2}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{r_1}{r_2} e^{i(\\theta _1 - \\theta _2)}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\quad \\textrm{(divide absolute values, subtract angles)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.44)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle n^{\\textrm{th}} \\textrm{ power:} \\qquad[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (r e^{i\\theta })^n[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle r^n e^{i n \\theta }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\quad \\textrm{for any integer } n[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.45)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{complex conjugation:}\\qquad[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\overline{r e^{i\\theta }}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle r e^{-i\\theta } .[/mathjaxinline] |  |  | (3.46)      Taking absolute values gives identities:  [mathjax]|z_1 z_2|=|z_1|\\, |z_2|, \\quad \\left|\\frac{1}{z}\\right| = \\frac{1}{|z|},\\quad \\left|\\frac{z_1}{z_2}\\right| = \\frac{|z_1|}{|z_2|}, \\quad |z^n| = |z|^n, \\quad |\\overline{z}| = |z|.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Example 11.1** How do you turn a smiley face into the emoticon **:)** ?  ###  Answer  Since [mathjaxinline]i = e^{i \\pi /2}[/mathjaxinline], multiplying by [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] adds [mathjaxinline]\\pi /2[/mathjaxinline] to the angle of each point; that is, it rotates counterclockwise by [mathjaxinline]90^\\circ[/mathjaxinline] (around the origin).  ![Smiley face is placed on the real axis and rotated 90 degrees counterclockwise about the origin.](/static/images/multiplication-by-i- smiley.svg)  For example, one eye was originally on the real line, at [mathjaxinline]1.5[/mathjaxinline], so multiplying it by [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] produces an eye at [mathjaxinline]1.5i[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 11.2** How do you trap a lion?  ###  Answer  Build a cage in the shape of the unit circle [mathjaxinline]|z|=1[/mathjaxinline]. Get inside the cage. Make sure that the lion is outside the cage. Apply the function [mathjaxinline]1/z[/mathjaxinline] to the whole plane. Voil\u00e0! The lion is now inside the cage, and you are outside it.  Only problem: There's a lot of other stuff inside the cage too. Also, don't stand too close to [mathjaxinline]z=0[/mathjaxinline] when you apply [mathjaxinline]1/z[/mathjaxinline].  ![The unit circle is plotted in the complex plane along with the point z equals r e to the i theta outside the unit circle. {"pageid": 144, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab14", "text": "**Example 14.1** Find the general solution to the differential equation  [mathjax]2\\ddot{x}+\\dot{x}+x=1+2e^{t}.[/mathjax]| (5.19)   ---|---      ###  Worked Solution  This is an inhomogeneous linear equation, so the general solution has the form [mathjaxinline]x_p+x_h[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline] is any particular solution and [mathjaxinline]x_h[/mathjaxinline] is the general homogeneous solution. The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]P(s)=2s^2+s+1[/mathjaxinline], with roots [mathjaxinline](-1\\pm \\sqrt{7}\\, i)/4[/mathjaxinline], so and the general homogeneous solution is given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_h\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =e^{-t/4}\\left(c_1\\cos \\left( \\frac{t\\sqrt{7}}{4}\\right)+c_2\\sin \\left( \\frac{\\sqrt{7}t}{4}\\right)\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =Ae^{-t/4}\\cos \\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{7}t}{4}-\\phi \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The inhomogeneous equation is [mathjaxinline]P(D)x=1+2e^{t}[/mathjaxinline]. The input signal is a linear combination of [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]e^{t}[/mathjaxinline], so we can find particular solutions to [mathjaxinline]P\\left(D\\right)x=1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]P\\left(D\\right)x=e^{t}[/mathjaxinline] separately, then use superposition to construct a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]P(D)x=1+2e^{t}[/mathjaxinline]. If [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] is a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]P(D)x=1[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]x_2[/mathjaxinline] is a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]P(D)x=e^{t}[/mathjaxinline], then superposition says that a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]P(D)x=1+2e^{t}[/mathjaxinline] is given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_p=x_1+2x_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      The constant function [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] is an exponential: [mathjaxinline]1=e^{0t}[/mathjaxinline]. Thus [mathjaxinline]P(D)x=1[/mathjaxinline] has a particular solution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_1=\\frac{1}{P\\left(0\\right)}=1[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      (More elementarily, we've learned to look for constant solutions when the right hand side is constant, and solving [mathjaxinline]P(D)c=1[/mathjaxinline] gives [mathjaxinline]c=1[/mathjaxinline].)  Similarly, the ERF tells us that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_2=\\frac{1}{P\\left(1\\right)}e^{t}=\\frac{1}{4}e^{t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      is a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]P(D)x=e^{t}[/mathjaxinline]. Thus  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_p[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =1+2\\left(\\frac{1}{4}e^{t}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =1+\\frac{1}{2}e^t[/mathjaxinline] |  |      is a particular solution to [mathjaxinline]P(D)x=1+2e^{t}[/mathjaxinline]. So the general solution to [mathjaxinline]2\\ddot{x}+\\dot{x}+x=1+2e^{t}[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x\\left(t\\right)=1+\\frac{1}{2}e^t+Ae^{-t/4}\\cos \\left(\\frac{t\\sqrt{7}}{4}-\\phi \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 14.2** Find a particular solution to the equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{x} + 8\\dot{x} + 15 x = e^{-5t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      ###  Worked Solution  The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]P(r) = r^2 + 8r + 15[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]P(-5) = 0[/mathjaxinline] we need to use the generalized ERF.  Computing we see that [mathjaxinline]P'(r) = 2r + 8[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]P'(-5) = -2[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore the generalized ERF gives a particular solution of  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle x_p = \\frac{te^{-5t}}{P'(-5)} = -\\frac{te^{-5t}}{2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      (Of course, there are other particular solutions.) To apply a sum of two operators, apply each operator to the function and add the results. For instance, [mathjaxinline](D^2 + D) y = D^2 y + D y = \\ddot{y} + \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline].  Any number can be viewed as the \u201cmultiply-by-the-number\" operator: for instance, the operator [mathjaxinline]5[/mathjaxinline] transforms the function [mathjaxinline]\\sin t[/mathjaxinline] into the function [mathjaxinline]5 \\sin t[/mathjaxinline]. In particular, the \u201cidentity\" operator is the multiply by the number [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] operator: [mathjaxinline]1f= f[/mathjaxinline] for all functions [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline].  Similarly, we can multiply by any function of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], and this is also a linear operator. For instance, the operator [mathjaxinline]t^2[/mathjaxinline] transforms the function [mathjaxinline]\\sin t[/mathjaxinline] into the function [mathjaxinline]t^2 \\sin t[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 3.1** The ODE  [mathjax]2 \\ddot{y} + 3 \\dot{y} + 5 y = 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      whose characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]P(r) = 2r^2+3r+5[/mathjaxinline], can be rewritten as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (2D^2 + 3D + 5) y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P(D) y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The same argument shows that every constant-coefficient homogeneous linear ODE  [mathjax]a_n y^{(n)} + \\cdots + a_0 y = 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      can be written simply as  [mathjax]P(D) y = 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] is the characteristic polynomial. {"pageid": 148, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab7", "text": "Given a nonzero complex number [mathjaxinline]z=a+bi[/mathjaxinline], we can express the point [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline] in polar coordinates [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]a = r \\cos \\theta , \\qquad b = r \\sin \\theta .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Then  [mathjax]a + bi = (r \\cos \\theta ) + (r \\sin \\theta )i = r ( \\cos \\theta + i \\sin \\theta ).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      One has [mathjaxinline]r=|z|[/mathjaxinline]; here [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] must be a **positive** real number (assuming [mathjaxinline]z \\ne 0[/mathjaxinline]).  ![The point a plus b i is plotted in the first quadrant. A vector extends from the origin to the point a plus b i. This vector has magnitude r and makes an angle theta with the positive x axis. The point is labeled r times e to the i theta.](/static/images/polar_form01.svg)  Any possible [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] (a possible value for the **angle** or **argument** of [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline]) may be called [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\arg z}}[/mathjaxinline], but this is dangerously ambiguous notation since there are many values of [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] for the same [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 7.1** Suppose that [mathjaxinline]z=-3i[/mathjaxinline]. So [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] corresponds to the point [mathjaxinline](0,-3)[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjaxinline]r=|z|=3[/mathjaxinline], but there are infinitely many possibilities for the angle [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline]. One possibility is [mathjaxinline]-\\pi /2[/mathjaxinline]; all the others are obtained by adding integer multiples of [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\arg z \\quad = \\quad \\; \\ldots , \\; -5\\pi /2, \\; -\\pi /2, \\; 3\\pi /2, \\; 7 \\pi /2, \\; \\ldots .[/mathjax]|   ---|---   ![The number negative 3 i is plotted in the complex plane at the coordinate 0 comma negative 3. A vector of magnitude 3 extends from the origin to this point. However, the point is represented in polar form with the angle theta equals 7 pi over 2, which is equivalent to making one and a three-quarters revolutions about the origin starting from the positive x axis.](/static/images/7pi-over-2.svg)  To specify a **preferred** polar form, we would have to restrict the range for [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] to some interval of width [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline]. The most common choice is to require [mathjaxinline]-\\pi < \\theta \\le \\pi[/mathjaxinline]. This special [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] is called the **principal value of the argument** , and is denoted in various ways:  [mathjax]\\theta = {\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{Arg}(a+bi)}} = \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\textrm{Mathematica}}} }{{\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{Arg[a+bi]}}} } = \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\textrm{Mathematica}}} }{{\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{ArcTan[a,b]}}} } = \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\textrm{MATLAB}}} }{{\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{atan2(b,a)}}} }\\; .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Warning:** In MATLAB, be careful to use [mathjaxinline](b,a)[/mathjaxinline] and not [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline].    Given a complex number [mathjaxinline]a+bi[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]a,b \\ne 0[/mathjaxinline], how do we find the principal value of the argument [mathjaxinline]\\theta \\in (-\\pi ,\\pi ][/mathjaxinline]? The number [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] satisfies [mathjaxinline]\\tan \\theta = b/a[/mathjaxinline], but since [mathjaxinline]\\tan[/mathjaxinline] has period [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline], there are **two** angles in [mathjaxinline](-\\pi ,\\pi ][/mathjaxinline] having tangent equal to [mathjaxinline]b/a[/mathjaxinline], corresponding to opposite directions. By definition, [mathjaxinline]\\tan ^{-1}(b/a)[/mathjaxinline] is the one in [mathjaxinline](-\\pi /2,\\pi /2)[/mathjaxinline], corresponding to a direction in the right half plane. If [mathjaxinline]a+bi[/mathjaxinline] is in the right half plane ([mathjaxinline]a>0[/mathjaxinline]), then [mathjaxinline]\\theta = \\tan ^{-1}(b/a)[/mathjaxinline] works. But if [mathjaxinline]a+bi[/mathjaxinline] is in the left half plane ([mathjaxinline]a<0[/mathjaxinline]), then it is necessary to adjust [mathjaxinline]\\tan ^{-1}(b/a)[/mathjaxinline] by adding or subtracting [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline]; either adding or subtracting will give **a** value of the argument, but for the principal value you should do the operation that results in a number in [mathjaxinline](-\\pi ,\\pi ][/mathjaxinline]. This is summarized in the table below.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{ if } \\, \\, a > 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta = \\arctan (b/a)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.20)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{ if } \\, \\, a < 0 \\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{ and } \\, \\, b \\geq 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta = \\arctan (b/a) + \\pi[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.21)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{ if } \\, \\, a < 0 \\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{ and } \\, \\, b < 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta = \\arctan (b/a) - \\pi[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.22)   ![In the first and fourth quadrants, we use arctan of b over a. In the second quadrant, we add pi to arctan of be over a. In the third quadrant, we subtract pi from arctan of b over a.](/static/images/arctanangles.svg)   **Problem:** Find the principal argument of [mathjaxinline]-1-i[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:** Here [mathjaxinline]a=-1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b=-1[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]\\tan ^{-1}(b/a) = \\tan ^{-1}(1) = \\pi /4[/mathjaxinline], but this angle gives the direction opposite to [mathjaxinline]-1-i[/mathjaxinline]. Subtracting [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline] gives the principal value [mathjaxinline]-3\\pi /4[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 149, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@04_complexexponential/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@04_complexexponential-tab10", "text": "**Example 10.1** Find in Cartesian form all values of [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt[3]{1}[/mathjaxinline]  ###  Worked Solution  The cube roots of 1 are [mathjaxinline]1,\\omega ,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\omega ^2[/mathjaxinline], where  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\omega[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{2\\pi i/3}=\\cos (2\\pi /3)+ i\\sin (2\\pi /3)=[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac12 + i\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}2[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\omega ^2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{4\\pi i/3}=\\cos (4\\pi /3)+ i\\sin (4\\pi /3)=[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac12-i\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}2.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The Greek letter [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] (\u201comega\") is traditionally used for this cube root.  Note that [mathjaxinline]\\omega ^2=\\overline{\\omega }[/mathjaxinline]. Another way to do this problem would be to draw the position of [mathjaxinline]\\omega ^2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] on the unit circle and use geometry to figure out their coordinates.  We could have predicted in advance that [mathjaxinline]e^{4\\pi i/3}[/mathjaxinline] would be the complex conjugate of [mathjaxinline]e^{2\\pi i/3}[/mathjaxinline], since [mathjaxinline]e^{4 \\pi i/3} = e^{4 \\pi i/3 - 2\\pi } = e^{-2\\pi i/3}[/mathjaxinline]. Alternatively, it had to happen since the non-real roots of a real polynomial like [mathjaxinline]z^3-1[/mathjaxinline] come in complex conjugate pairs.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 10.2** Find all values of [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt[4]{i}.[/mathjaxinline]  ###  Worked Solution  In polar form, [mathjaxinline]i = e^{i\\pi /2}[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore the fourth roots are  [mathjax]\\sqrt[4]{i} = e^{i(\\pi /8 + 2\\pi k/4)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      You might notice that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{i(\\pi /8 + 2\\pi k/4)}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{i\\pi /8}e^{i2\\pi k/4}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.60)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]e^{i2\\pi k/4}[/mathjaxinline] are the [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline]th roots of unity [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt[4]{1}=1,i,-1,-i[/mathjaxinline].  Therefore one fourth root of [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]z_0 = e^{i\\pi /8}[/mathjaxinline], and all of the fourth roots of [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] are given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\sqrt[4]{i}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z_0, iz_0, -z_0, -iz_0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Notice that multiplying [mathjaxinline]z_0=e^{i\\pi /8}[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] is the same as a 90 degree rotation of [mathjaxinline]z_0[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 10.3** Solve the equation [mathjaxinline]x^6-2x^3+2=0[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Worked Solution  Treating this as a quadratic equation in [mathjaxinline]x^3[/mathjaxinline], we solve the quadratic by using the quadratic formula; the two roots are [mathjaxinline]1+i[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]1-i[/mathjaxinline] (check this!), so the roots of the original equation satisfy either  [mathjax]x^3=1+i\\quad \\text{ or }\\quad x^3=1-i .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This reduces the problem to finding the cube roots of the two complex numbers [mathjaxinline]1\\pm i[/mathjaxinline]. We start with [mathjaxinline]1+i[/mathjaxinline] and the first step is to write it in polar form:  [mathjax]1+i=\\sqrt{2}e^{\\pi i/4}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle (1+i)^{1/3}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left( 2^{1/2}e^{i\\pi /4}\\right)^{1/3}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.61)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2^{1/6}e^{i(\\pi /4 +2\\pi k)/3 }[/mathjaxinline] | | (3.62)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2^{1/6}e^{i(1+8k)\\pi /12 }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.63)      There are 3 choices for [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] to find all 3 cube roots  [mathjax]2^{1/6}e^{i\\pi /12 }, \\quad 2^{1/6}e^{i9\\pi /12 }, \\quad 2^{1/6}e^{-i7\\pi /12 }.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that [mathjaxinline]1-i[/mathjaxinline] is the complex conjugate of [mathjaxinline]1+i[/mathjaxinline]. Since we started out with a real equation, all roots must occur as complex conjugate pairs. Therefore the cube roots of [mathjaxinline]1-i[/mathjaxinline] must be the complex conjugates of the cube roots of [mathjaxinline]1+i[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]2^{1/6}e^{-i\\pi /12 }, \\quad 2^{1/6}e^{-i9\\pi /12 }, \\quad 2^{1/6}e^{i7\\pi /12 }.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      You may notice that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2^{1/6}e^{i(\\pi /4 +2\\pi k)/3 }[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2^{1/6}e^{i\\pi /12} e^{i2\\pi k/3 }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.64)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]e^{i2\\pi k/3 } = \\omega[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] is one of the cube roots of unity, [mathjaxinline]\\omega ^3 =1[/mathjaxinline].  The cube roots can also be described as  [mathjax]z_1, \\, \\, z_1\\omega ,\\, \\, z_1\\omega ^2\\; \\; \\text{ and }\\; \\; z_2,\\, \\, z_2\\omega ,\\, \\, z_2\\omega ^2[/mathjax]|   ---|---   [mathjax]\\text{ where }\\; \\; z_1=2^{1/6}e^{\\pi i/12}, \\quad z_2= \\overline{z_1} =2^{1/6}e^{-i\\pi /12} \\quad , \\text{ and } \\quad \\omega = e^{i2\\pi /3}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Worked Examples", "filename": "04_complexexponential-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Worked Examples"}

{"pageid": 153, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@29_autonomousequations2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@29_autonomousequations2-tab3", "text": "Here are two consequences of the time invariance of an autonomous equation:    * Each isocline (in the [mathjaxinline](t,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane) consists of one or more horizontal lines.     * Solution curves (in the [mathjaxinline](t,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane) are horizontal translations of one another. That is, if [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a solution, then so is [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t-a)[/mathjaxinline] for any [mathjaxinline]\\, a.[/mathjaxinline]    For example, here is the slope field for [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}=y(1-y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] with the [mathjaxinline](-1)[/mathjaxinline]-isocline and a few solution curves:  ![ ](/static/images/autonomousproperties2_newcolors.svg)   The [mathjaxinline](-1)[/mathjaxinline]-isocline (orange) consists of 2 horizontal lines;   Solution curves (blue) are horizontal translations of one another.  ###  Why are all translations of solutions also solutions? (A non-geometric argument)  Let [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] be a solution to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y} = f(y).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] We verify that [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t-a)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is also a solution.    Let [mathjaxinline]u=t-a,\\,[/mathjaxinline] then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} y(t-a)\\, =\\, \\frac{d}{dt}y(u(t))[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{du}\\, \\frac{du}{dt} \\qquad (\\text{chain rule})[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.25)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, f\\left(y(u)\\right) (1)\\, =\\, f\\left(y(t-a)\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.26)      Therefore [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t-a)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is also a solution.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  First properties", "filename": "29_autonomousequations2-tab3-text1.html", "title": "First properties"}

{"pageid": 155, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@recitation14_for_edx/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@recitation14_for_edx-tab2", "text": "**Euler's Method:** Numerical method to compute [mathjaxinline]y(x)[/mathjaxinline] of [mathjaxinline]y'=f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] with initial condition [mathjaxinline]y(x_0)=y_0[/mathjaxinline].  This is the only numerical method you are responsible for. (Memorize it.) The idea is to follow the direction field at a fixed step size [mathjaxinline]h>0[/mathjaxinline]. Start at [mathjaxinline]P_0=(x_0,y_0)[/mathjaxinline] and the iterative formulas are given by  [mathjax]x_{n+1} = x_n + h; \\quad y_{n+1} = y_n + h\\, f(x_n,y_n)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Error Estimates:** [mathjaxinline]E = y_{\\textrm{approx}} - y_{\\textrm{exact}}[/mathjaxinline]  [mathjax]|E|\\le Ch[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] is on the order of [mathjaxinline]|f| + |\\partial f/\\partial x| + |\\partial f/\\partial y|[/mathjaxinline].  **Remark.** If [mathjaxinline]y^{\\prime \\prime }<0[/mathjaxinline] in a region (concave down), then [mathjaxinline]E>0[/mathjaxinline]. (The approximation is bigger than the actual answer.) Similarly, if [mathjaxinline]y^{\\prime \\prime }>0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]E <0[/mathjaxinline]. (The approximation is smaller than the actual answer.)  Euler's method", "filename": "recitation14_for_edx-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Euler's method"}

(Isocline means \u201csame incline\", or \u201csame slope\".)  **Question 6.2** What is the equation for the [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline]-isocline?  **Answer:** The ODE says that the slope of the solution curve through a point [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline], so the **equation of the** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{C}}[/mathjaxinline] **-isocline** is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.1)   ---|---|---|---|---|---  Isoclines", "filename": "28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Isoclines"}

{"pageid": 160, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab12", "text": "**Stability** means that the long-term system behavior is independent of initial conditions.  **Stability test in terms of roots.** A constant coefficient linear ODE of _any order_ is stable if and only if every root of the characteristic polynomial has negative real part.  We will explain this in the case of a second order system. For any second order system  [mathjax]m\\ddot x + b\\dot x + kx = 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      there are 3 cases for the roots of the characteristic polynomial.    1. The roots are complex conjugates: [mathjaxinline]a\\pm bi[/mathjaxinline].     2. The roots are repeated and real: [mathjaxinline]s, s[/mathjaxinline].     3. The roots are distinct real numbers: [mathjaxinline]r_1, r_2[/mathjaxinline].   If the roots are complex conjugates, then the general solution to the homogeneous equation takes the form [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{at}\\left(A\\cos (bt-\\phi )\\right)[/mathjaxinline]. The homogeneous solution is transient only if the real part of the root is negative ([mathjaxinline]a<0[/mathjaxinline]). If the real part is zero [mathjaxinline]a=0[/mathjaxinline], the homogeneous solution oscillates forever with constant amplitude; if the real part is positive ([mathjaxinline]a>0[/mathjaxinline]), the homogeneous solution oscillates and the amplitude grows exponentially as time goes on.  If the roots are real and repeated, then the homogeneous solution takes the form [mathjaxinline](A+Bt)e^{st}[/mathjaxinline], and these solutions are transient only if [mathjaxinline]s<0[/mathjaxinline].  If the roots are real and distinct, then the homogeneous solution takes the form [mathjaxinline]c_1 e^{r_1t} + c_2 e^{r_2t}[/mathjaxinline], and these solutions are transient only if [mathjaxinline]r_1, r_2 <0[/mathjaxinline].  These conditions are collected in the table below. All three cases are covered by the statement that the real part of the roots of the characteristic polynomial must be negative.  **Roots**|  **General solution** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{x_h}}[/mathjaxinline] | **Condition for stability**   ---|---|---   complex [mathjaxinline]a \\pm bi[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]e^{at} (c_1 \\cos (bt) + c_2 \\sin (bt))[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]a<0[/mathjaxinline]   repeated real [mathjaxinline]s,s[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]e^{st} (c_1 +c_2 t)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]s<0[/mathjaxinline]   distinct real [mathjaxinline]r_1,r_2[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]c_1 e^{r_1t} + c_2 e^{r_2t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]r_1,r_2 < 0[/mathjaxinline]  Tests for stability in a second-order system", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Tests for stability in a second-order system"}

{"pageid": 162, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@33_numericalmethods/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@33_numericalmethods-tab2", "text": "**Note on video:** In the video above, Professor Mattuck uses [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\,[/mathjaxinline] instead of [mathjaxinline]\\, t,[/mathjaxinline] as the independent variable. (At the end of the video, the course 100 refers to a programming course 1.00 in the Civil Engineering department at MIT.)    Consider again the ODE [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y} = f(t,y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the starting point [mathjaxinline](t_0,y_0).\\,[/mathjaxinline] We try to approximate the solution curve through it.  **Question 2.2** Where, approximately, will be the point on the solution curve at time [mathjaxinline]\\, t_0+3h[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Solution  The crude answer would be to take [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] steps each using the initial slope [mathjaxinline]f(t_0,y_0)[/mathjaxinline] (or equivalently, one big step of width [mathjaxinline]3h[/mathjaxinline]).    Geometrically:  ![ ](/static/images/u1c5s3_crude3step.svg)    The more refined answer is called **Euler's method** : take [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] steps, **but reassess the slope after each step, using the slope field at each successive position** :  ![ ](/static/images/u1c5s3_Euler3stepsnew.svg)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t_0 + h[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_0 + f(t_0,y_0)h[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t_1 + h[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_1 + f(t_1,y_1)h[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t_3[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t_2 + h[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_3[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_2 + f(t_2,y_2)h.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The sequence of line segments from [mathjaxinline](t_0,y_0)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline](t_1,y_1)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline](t_2,y_2)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline](t_3,y_3)[/mathjaxinline] is a piecewise linear approximation to the solution curve. The more refined answer to the question is [mathjaxinline]\\, (t_3,y_3).\\,[/mathjaxinline]  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Euler's Method:**    Given an initial value problem  [mathjax]y'\\, =\\, f(t,y)\\qquad y(t_0)=y_0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and a choice of **step size** [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] (in seconds if time is the independent variable), the Euler method gives an approximation to the solution curve between [mathjaxinline]t= t_0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]t=t_0+(n+1)h,\\,[/mathjaxinline] by a sequence of line segments connecting the points [mathjaxinline]\\, (t_0,y_0),\\, (t_1,y_1),\\, \\ldots \\, (t_n,y_n), \\, (t_{n+1},y_{n+1}),\\,[/mathjaxinline] where for each [mathjaxinline]0\\leq k\\leq n,\\,[/mathjaxinline]  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle t_{k+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t_k+h[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.73)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_{k+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_k+h f(t_k,y_k).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.74)   ![ ](/static/images/u1c5s3_Eulernsteps.svg)   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{y_{k+1}-y_k\\, = \\, h y'(t_k)\\, =\\, h f(t_k,y_k)}}[/mathjaxinline]        These calculations are usually done by computer, and there are round-off errors in calculations. But even if there are no round-off errors, Euler's method hardly ever gives the exact answer. The problem is that the actual solution is rarely a straight line.  Euler's method", "filename": "33_numericalmethods-tab2-text2.html", "title": "Euler's method"}

So we change to polar form, take the power, then change back to Cartesian form:  [mathjax](1+i)^6=(\\sqrt{2} e^{i\\pi /4})^6=(\\sqrt{2})^6e^{i6\\pi /4}=8e^{i3\\pi /2}=-8i.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      You can check the answer by applying the binomial theorem to [mathjaxinline](1+i)^6[/mathjaxinline] and collecting the real and imaginary parts.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 12.2** Express [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\frac{1 + i\\sqrt3}{\\sqrt3 + i}}[/mathjaxinline] in polar form.  ###  Worked Solution  Change numerator and denominator into polar form, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\frac{1 + i\\sqrt3}{\\sqrt3 + i} = \\frac{2e^{i \\pi /3}}{2e^{i\\pi /6}} = e^{i \\pi /6}}[/mathjaxinline], use the division rule. {"pageid": 164, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab4", "text": "There are two ways of expressing any **sinusoidal function** , in **rectangular form** and in **polar form.** They are related as follows:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\underbrace{{\\color{blue}{a}} \\cos (\\theta )+{\\color{blue}{b}} \\sin (\\theta )}_{{\\color{blue}{\\text{rectangular form}}} }\\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\underbrace{{\\color{orange}{A}} \\cos (\\theta -{\\color{orange}{\\phi }} )}_{{\\color{orange}{\\text{polar form}}} }\\qquad {\\color{blue}{a}} ,\\, {\\color{blue}{b}} ,\\, {\\color{orange}{\\phi }} \\in \\mathbb {R}, \\ \\ \\ {\\color{orange}{A}} \\geq 0 \\in \\mathbb {R},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.8)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\underbrace{{\\color{orange}{A}} \\cos {\\color{orange}{\\phi }} }_{{\\color{blue}{a}} } \\cos \\theta + \\underbrace{{\\color{orange}{A}} \\sin {\\color{orange}{\\phi }} }_{{\\color{blue}{b}} } \\sin \\theta \\qquad \\text{by the trig sum formula}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.9)      where [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\phi[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are given implicitly by the following diagram:  ![The point a comma b is plotted in the first quadrant. The line segment extending from the origin to the point has length capital A and forms an angle of phi with the positive x axis.](/static/images/u1c3s1_Ampphasetriangle.svg)    That is,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle A[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{a^2+b^2}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.10)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\phi[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle :[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Angle between the positive horizontal axis and the ray to the point }\\, (a,b).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.11)      Note that [mathjaxinline]\\, (A,\\phi )\\,[/mathjaxinline] are polar coordinates of the point with rectangular coordinates [mathjaxinline]\\, (a,b).\\,[/mathjaxinline] We will use the convention [mathjaxinline]\\, A\\geq 0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] As usual for polar coordinate, the angle [mathjaxinline]\\, \\phi \\,[/mathjaxinline] is well-defined only up to addition of integer multiples of [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline].    It is amazing that the sum of two sinusoids is another sinusoid! And while graphing the sinusoid in rectangular form is a mystery, graphing the polar form is easy. We will do this shortly.    From linear combinations to amplitude phase form", "filename": "06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab4-text1.html", "title": "From linear combinations to amplitude phase form"}

{"pageid": 165, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@11_resonance/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@11_resonance-tab3", "text": "**Example 3.1** We might try to model a swing on a playground as a simple harmonic oscillator. Recall that a harmonic oscillator has a natural frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline]. When you push your kid sister on a swing, the key is to get in sync with the natural frequency of the swing. You keep pushing on regular intervals with the same force, but your sister swings higher and higher.  Let's model the swing-and-sister setup by a sinusoidally driven harmonic oscillator, [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x}+\\omega _n^2x=A\\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline]. We find a periodic solution using the exponential response formula _provided that_ [mathjaxinline]\\omega \\neq \\omega _n[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_p[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A\\frac{\\cos (\\omega t)}{\\omega _n^2-\\omega ^2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Notice that as [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] gets closer to [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline], the amplitude of this particular solution grows larger.  In this mathlet, the natural frequency is [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n=1[/mathjaxinline], and the frequency of the input signal is adjustable. The graph on the lower left shows the input signal in blue and the system response in orange. On the right, you see a graph of the amplitude of the response as a function of the input frequency. However, the vertical axis is scaled by [mathjaxinline]1/\\sqrt{2}[/mathjaxinline] to fit the frame. The abbreviation RMS stands for **root mean square** , which for a sinusoid is [mathjaxinline]\\text{amplitude}/\\sqrt{2}[/mathjaxinline]. It has a physical interpretation; it is used for a superposition of many frequencies.  Observe what happens to the amplitude of the system response as [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] approaches [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline].  What happens when the two frequencies coincide, that is [mathjaxinline]\\omega =\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline]? This is the phenomenon known as **pure resonance** , which we explore next.  Near resonance", "filename": "11_resonance-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Near resonance"}

{"pageid": 166, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@29_autonomousequations2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@29_autonomousequations2-tab12", "text": "Recall that a population [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] in an environment with limited resources is described by the logistic equation,  [mathjax]\\dot{y}=ay-by^2\\qquad (a,b>0)\\qquad (\\text{no harvesting}).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If this population is also harvested at a constant rate, we add a term to the logistic equation to include the effect of harvesting:  [mathjax]\\dot{y}=ay-by^2-h \\qquad (a,b>0,\\, h\\geq 0)\\qquad (\\text{with harvesting})[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, h\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the harvesting rate (in number of animals per time).    This is an **infinite family** of autonomous equations, one for each value of [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline], and **each has its own phase line.** We will explore how the phase line changes with [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] in the example and problems below.     **Example 12.1** Frogs grow in a pond according to the logistic equation with natural growth constant [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] (in [mathjaxinline]\\text{month}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]), and eventually the population reaches an equilibrium of [mathjaxinline]\\, 3000\\,[/mathjaxinline] frogs. Then the frogs are harvested at a constant rate. Model the population of frogs.  **Variables and functions:**  [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] |  time (months)   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  size of population (kilofrogs) at time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] |  harvest rate (kilofrogs per month)      **Differential equation:**     **Without harvesting** :    We have modeled the frog population in a pond without harvesting in a previous problem. We learned then that the logistic equation can also be written as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{y}=k_0\\left(1-\\frac{y}{y_0}\\right)\\, y.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.55)   ---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]k_0[/mathjaxinline] is the natural growth constant if the environment is unconstrained, and [mathjaxinline]y_0[/mathjaxinline] is the nonzero equilibrium population. In our example, [mathjaxinline]\\, k_0= 3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, y_0=3[/mathjaxinline] (kilofrogs); therefore the DE is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3\\left(1-\\frac{y}{3}\\right)\\, y\\, =\\, 3y-y^2.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.56)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **With harvesting** : We add the term [mathjaxinline]\\, -h\\,[/mathjaxinline] to the DE above to account for the harvesting:  [mathjax]\\dot{y} = 3y-y^2-h[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for a harvesting rate [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline]. Since the population has reached the equilibrium of [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] (kilofrogs) when harvesting starts, we use the initial condition [mathjaxinline]y(0)=3.\\,[/mathjaxinline]  A harvesting model and phase lines", "filename": "29_autonomousequations2-tab12-text1.html", "title": "A harvesting model and phase lines"}

By this point you should be able to work out the solutions to the system and find that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_1\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =e^{-t/2}\\left(\\cos \\frac{t\\sqrt{3}}{2}+\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}\\sin \\frac{t\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right),[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{x_2(t)}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =e^{-t}\\left(1+t\\right),[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{orange}{x_3(t)}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\left(\\frac{1}{2}+\\frac{3}{2\\sqrt{5}}\\right)e^{\\frac{-3+\\sqrt{5}}{2}t}+\\left(\\frac{1}{2}-\\frac{3}{2\\sqrt{5}}\\right)e^{\\frac{-3-\\sqrt{5}}{2}t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Looking at these solutions it's easy to see that [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] is the solution to an **underdamped** system, [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{x_2}}[/mathjaxinline] is the solution to a **critically damped** system, and [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{x_3}}[/mathjaxinline] is the solution to an **overdamped** system.  Now let's compare the graphs of each of these solutions.  ![All three solutions start with initial conditions x of 0 equals 0 and x dot of 0 equals 0, and the solutions all tend to 0 as t goes to infinity. {"pageid": 171, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab5", "text": "This was only done for first order previously [here](/jump_to_id/02_solvingafirstorderode-tab10).  To understand the general solution [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] to an inhomogeneous linear ODE  [mathjax]\\text{inhomogeneous equation:} \\quad p_n(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + \\cdots + p_0(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = {\\color{orange}{q(t)}} ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      do the following:    1. List all solutions to the associated homogeneous equation   [mathjax]\\text{homogeneous equation:} \\quad p_n(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + \\cdots + p_0(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = 0;[/mathjax]|   ---|---      i.e., write down the general homogeneous solution [mathjaxinline]y_h[/mathjaxinline].    2. Find (in some way) any **one** particular solution [mathjaxinline]y_p[/mathjaxinline] to the **inhomogeneous** ODE.     3. Add [mathjaxinline]y_p[/mathjaxinline] to all the solutions of the homogeneous ODE to get all the solutions to the inhomogeneous ODE.   **Summary:**  [mathjax]\\underset {{\\color{blue}{\\text{general solution}}} }{y} = \\underset {{\\color{blue}{\\text{particular solution}}} }{y_p} + \\underset {\\text{general homogeneous solution}}{y_h}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Why does this work?  Let [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] be the linear operator [mathjaxinline]L = p_n(t)D^n + \\dotsb + p_1(t)D+p_0(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Then the differential equations become  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{inhomogeneous equation} \\qquad Ly[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.7)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{homogeneous equation} \\qquad Ly[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.8)   Let [mathjaxinline]y_p[/mathjaxinline] be a particular solution to the inhomogeneous equation [mathjaxinline]L(y_p) = q[/mathjaxinline]. Let [mathjaxinline]y_h[/mathjaxinline] be a homogeneous solution [mathjaxinline]L(y_h) = 0[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjax]L(y_p+y_h) =q+0=q.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   Suppose that [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] is also a solution to [mathjaxinline]Ly=q.[/mathjaxinline] That is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle Ly[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.9)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle Ly_p[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.10)   Then it follows by linearity that [mathjax]L(y-y_p) = L(y)-L(y_p) = q - q = 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---   Therefore [mathjaxinline]y-y_p = y_h[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the associated homogeneous equation. In other words, [mathjax]y = y_p + y_h.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **The result of this section is the key point of linearity in the inhomogeneous case.** It lets us build **all** the solutions to an inhomogeneous DE out of **one particular solution** provided that you have already solved the associated homogeneous ODE. {"pageid": 172, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@01_odeintro/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@01_odeintro-tab11", "text": "Let's get back to the savings account model:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\dot x = I(t) x + q(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Maybe for financial planning I am interested in testing different saving strategies (different functions [mathjaxinline]q[/mathjaxinline]) to see what balances [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] they result in. To help with this, rewrite the ODE as  [mathjax]\\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\text{controlled by bank}}} }{\\dot{x} - I(t) x} = \\underset {{\\color{blue}{\\text{controlled by me}}} }{q(t).}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In the \u201csystems and signals\" language of engineering, [mathjaxinline]q[/mathjaxinline] is called the **input signal** , the bank is the **system** , and [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is the **output signal** . These terms do not have a mathematical meaning dictated by the DE alone; their interpretation is guided by the system being modeled. But the general picture is this:  ![The input signal and initial conditions enter the system. An output signal is produced.](/static/images/ISR.svg)  We'll see many examples that model phenomena using this input/system response language.    * The **system** may be a mechanical system such as an automobile suspension or an electrical circuit, or an economic market. It is impacted by some external signal. We are interested in understanding how the system responds to the external stimulus.     * The **input signal** is the external stimulus. It usually does not appear in as simple a way in the DE as it does in the example above. But it does always determine the right hand side of the DE (when written in standard linear form).     * The **system response** (also called **output signal** ) is the measurable behavior of the system that we are interested in. It is always the unknown function that we write a differential equation for.     * All differential equations have many solutions. The solution of interest is often determined by the state of the system at the beginning. This initial state is given by the initial conditions.   Systems and signals", "filename": "01_odeintro-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Systems and signals"}
