{"pageid": 174, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab2", "text": "**The operator** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{D}}[/mathjaxinline]    * A function takes an input number and returns another number.     * An **operator** takes an input **function** and returns another function.   For example, the **differential operator** [mathjaxinline]\\frac{d}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] takes an input function [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] and returns [mathjaxinline]\\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline]. This operator is also called [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{D}}[/mathjaxinline]. For instance [mathjaxinline]D e^{4t} = 4 e^{4t}[/mathjaxinline]. The operator [mathjaxinline]D[/mathjaxinline] is **linear** , which means that  [mathjax]D(f+g) = Df + Dg, \\qquad D(af) = a\\, Df[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for any functions [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline], and any number [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]. Because of this, [mathjaxinline]D[/mathjaxinline] behaves well with respect to linear combinations, namely  [mathjax]D(c_1 f_1 + \\cdots + c_n f_n) = c_1 \\, D f_1 + \\cdots + c_n \\, Df_n[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for any numbers [mathjaxinline]c_1,\\ldots ,c_n[/mathjaxinline] and functions [mathjaxinline]f_1,\\ldots ,f_n[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 2.1** [mathjaxinline]Dt^3=3t^2[/mathjaxinline].  **Warning :** You can't take this equation and substitute [mathjaxinline]t=2[/mathjaxinline] to get [mathjaxinline]D8=12[/mathjaxinline]. The only way to interpret \u201c[mathjaxinline]8[/mathjaxinline]\" in \u201c[mathjaxinline]D8[/mathjaxinline]\" is as a **constant** function, which of course has derivative zero: [mathjaxinline]D8=0[/mathjaxinline]. The point is that in order to know the function [mathjaxinline]Df(t)[/mathjaxinline] at a particular value of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], say [mathjaxinline]t=a[/mathjaxinline], you need to know more than just [mathjaxinline]f(a)[/mathjaxinline]; you need to know how [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] is changing near [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] as well. This is characteristic of operators; in general you have to expect to need to know the **whole** function [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] in order to evaluate an operator on it.  **Definition 2.2** In general, a **linear operator** [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] is any operator that satisfies  [mathjax]L(f+g) = Lf + Lg, \\qquad L(af) = a\\, Lf[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for any functions [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline], and any number [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 2.3** The operator [mathjaxinline]L = D^2 + p(t)D + q(t)[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]p(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]q(t)[/mathjaxinline] are any functions of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is a linear operator.  Why is [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] linear? You know that [mathjaxinline]D[/mathjaxinline] is linear, and similarly, [mathjaxinline]D^2[/mathjaxinline] is linear. To see that [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] is linear, verify that a linear combination of linear operators is again a linear operator.  Operator notation", "filename": "09_exponentialresponse-tab2-text2.html", "title": "Operator notation"}

{"pageid": 175, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@12_rlc/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@12_rlc-tab3", "text": "Recall the DE for the system response[mathjaxinline]\\, V_R\\,[/mathjaxinline] and system input [mathjaxinline]\\, V\\,[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P(D) V_R\\, =\\, Q(D) V,\\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P(D)\\, =\\, L D^2 +R D+\\frac{1}{C}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.56)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle Q(D)\\, =\\, RD.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.57)      (Recall [mathjaxinline]\\, D\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the differential operator [mathjaxinline]\\, D=\\, \\frac{d}{dt}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] ) The complex gain for [mathjaxinline]\\, V_R\\,[/mathjaxinline] is therefore  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G_R(\\omega )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{Q(i\\omega )}{P(i\\omega )}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{iR\\omega }{\\left(\\frac{1}{C}-L\\omega ^2\\right)+iR\\omega }.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.58)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---  Complex gain for the voltage drop across resistor", "filename": "12_rlc-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Complex gain for the voltage drop across resistor"}

{"pageid": 177, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@01_odeintro/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@01_odeintro-tab1", "text": "### Introduction to the course  A **differential equation (DE)** is an equation relating an unknown function and some of its derivatives. {"pageid": 178, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@33_numericalmethods/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@33_numericalmethods-tab9", "text": "When computing [mathjaxinline]\\int _a^b f(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] numerically, the most primitive method is to use the left Riemann sum: divide the range of integration into subintervals of width [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline], and estimate the value of [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] for each [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] on the subinterval by the value at the left endpoint. More sophisticated methods are the **trapezoid rule** and **Simpson's rule** , which have smaller errors.  There are analogous improvements to Euler's method.  **Integration**|  **Differential equation**|  **Error**   ---|---|---   left Riemann sum |  Euler's method |  [mathjaxinline]O(h)[/mathjaxinline]   trapezoid rule |  second-order Runge\u2013Kutta method (RK2) | [mathjaxinline]O(h^2)[/mathjaxinline]   Simpson's rule |  fourth-order Runge\u2013Kutta method (RK4) | [mathjaxinline]O(h^4)[/mathjaxinline]      The **big** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{O}}[/mathjaxinline] **notation** [mathjaxinline]O(h^4)[/mathjaxinline] means that there is a constant [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] (depending on the differential equation but not on [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline]) such that the error is at most [mathjaxinline]C h^4[/mathjaxinline], assuming that [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] is small. The error estimates in the table are valid for reasonable differential equations.  **Better methods:**    The Runge\u2013Kutta methods evaluate at more points on the interval [mathjaxinline][t_0,t_0+h][/mathjaxinline] to get a better estimate of what happens to the slope over the course of that interval.  Below is an example of a **second-order Runge\u2013Kutta method (RK2)** . It is also called the **midpoint method** or the **modified Euler method** .    Here is how one step of this method goes:  ![ ](/static/images/u1c5s3_RK2midpoint.svg)      1. Starting from [mathjaxinline]\\, (t_0,y_0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] look ahead to see where one step of Euler's method would land, but do not go there! Call this temporary point [mathjaxinline]\\, (t_1,\\tilde{y}_1).[/mathjaxinline]     2. Find the **midpoint** between the starting point and the temporary point: [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left( \\frac{t_0+t_1}{2}, \\frac{y_0+\\tilde{y}_1}{2} \\right).[/mathjaxinline]     3. Use the slope at this midpoint to find [mathjaxinline]\\, y_1\\,[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjax]y_1\\, =\\, y_0 +h f\\left( \\frac{t_0+t_1}{2}, \\frac{y_0+\\tilde{y}_1}{2} \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---    Repeat the steps above using [mathjaxinline]\\, (t_1,y_1)\\,[/mathjaxinline] as the starting point.    Here is a summary of the equations:    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle t_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t_0+h[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.77)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tilde{y}_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_0+h f(t_0,y_0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.78)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_0+ h f\\left(\\frac{t_0+t_1}{2},\\frac{y_0+\\tilde{y}_1}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.79)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(t_0, y_0 \\right)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mapsto[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(t_1, y_1\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.80)       **Even better methods:**    The **fourth-order Runge\u2013Kutta method (RK4)** is similar, but more elaborate, averaging several slopes. It is the most commonly used method for solving DEs numerically. Some people simply call it **the** Runge\u2013Kutta method. The mathlets we have been playing with use RK4 with a small step size to compute the \u201cactual\" solution to a DE.  Runge\u2013Kutta methods", "filename": "33_numericalmethods-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Runge\u2013Kutta methods"}

{"pageid": 181, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab11", "text": "We have been interchanging between a complex basis and a real basis for the solutions to a second order homogenous linear DE with two distinct complex characteristic roots. The general principle, which applies to more complicated ODEs, is summarized below.  **Complex basis vs. real-valued basis.** Let [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] be a complex-valued function of a real- valued variable [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. If [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\overline{y},\\,[/mathjaxinline] the complex conjugate of [mathjaxinline]y,\\,[/mathjaxinline] are a basis of the solutions to a second order homogeneous linear ODE with real coefficients, then  [mathjax]\\text{replacing } y, \\overline{y} \\text{ by } \\mathrm{Re\\, }(y), \\mathrm{Im\\, }(y)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      gives a new basis. Taking all **real** linear combinations of the **real** basis [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{Re\\, }(y),\\, \\mathrm{Im\\, }(y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] then gives all the **real** solutions to the DE.  **Question 11.1** Would it be okay to replace [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\overline{y}[/mathjaxinline] instead by [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(y)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]i \\mathrm{Im\\, }(y)[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Answer  Yes, but this would be less useful, because the whole point is to obtain a basis consisting of **real-valued** functions.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Question 11.2** Would it be okay to replace [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\overline{y}[/mathjaxinline] instead by [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(y)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(\\overline{y})[/mathjaxinline].  ###  Answer  No, because if [mathjaxinline]y=f+ig[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\overline{y}=f-ig[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(y)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(\\overline{y})[/mathjaxinline] are both [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline]! They are linearly dependent, so they can't be part of a basis.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Summary on complex solutions", "filename": "06_higherorderlinearodes-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Summary on complex solutions"}

{"pageid": 182, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@07_dampedoscillators/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@07_dampedoscillators-tab10", "text": "**Question 10.2** What is the solution to the system [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x}+\\dot{x}+3x= 0[/mathjaxinline] with initial conditions [mathjaxinline]x(0) = 1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}(0) = 0[/mathjaxinline]? What does the graph of [mathjaxinline]x\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] look like?  ###  Answer  The pair  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{-t/2}\\cos \\frac{t\\sqrt{11}}{2}, e^{-t/2}\\sin \\frac{t\\sqrt{11}}{2}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      form a basis for the real solutions of the system. So the general solution to the system is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = e^{-t/2}\\left(c_1\\cos \\frac{t\\sqrt{11}}{2} + c_2\\sin \\frac{t\\sqrt{11}}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = Ae^{-t/2}\\cos \\left(\\frac{t\\sqrt{11}}{2} - \\phi \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The damped angular frequency is [mathjaxinline]\\omega _d = \\sqrt{11}/2[/mathjaxinline], and the initial conditions are satisfied when [mathjaxinline]c_1=1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2=1/\\sqrt{11}[/mathjaxinline], so we can write the general solution as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = e^{-t/2}\\left(\\cos \\frac{t\\sqrt{11}}{2} + \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{11}}\\sin \\frac{t\\sqrt{11}}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\frac{\\sqrt{12}}{\\sqrt{11}}e^{-t/2}\\cos \\left(\\frac{t\\sqrt{11}}{2} - \\phi \\right),[/mathjaxinline] |  |      where [mathjaxinline]\\phi = \\tan ^{-1}(1/\\sqrt{11})[/mathjaxinline].  The graph of the solution is:  ![The graph of the function x of t starts at t equals zero and x of t equals 1. The function then decreases and oscillates about the origin with a rapidly decaying amplitude.](/static/images/underdamped-harmonic.svg)  **Figure :** The graph of the underdamped system [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x}+\\dot{x}+3x= 0[/mathjaxinline] with initial conditions [mathjaxinline]x(0) = 1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}(0) = 0[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 183, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab5", "text": "**Problem 5.1** A mass that sits on a cart is attached to a spring attached to a wall. The mass is also attached to a dashpot, a damping device. (A dashpot could be a cylinder filled with oil that a piston moves through. Door dampers and car shock absorbers often actually work this way.) Find the differential equation for the position of the mass.  ![A spring is attached to a wall on its left and a cart on its right. A dashpot is attached to the cart on its left and the wall on its right. The cart has wheels and can roll either left or right. The spring constant is labeled k, the mass is labeled m, and the damping coefficient of the dashpot is labeled b. The center of the cart is at the rest at the location x equals 0, and we take rightwards to be the positive x direction.](/static/images/curly-spring-mass-dashpot-no-external-force.svg)  **Solution:** Define variables with units:  [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] |  time (seconds [mathjaxinline]\\text{s}[/mathjaxinline])   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] |  position of the mass (meters [mathjaxinline]\\text{m}[/mathjaxinline]), with [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] being where the spring exerts no force   [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] |  the mass ([mathjaxinline]\\text{kg}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]F_{\\text{spring}}[/mathjaxinline] |  force exerted by the spring on the mass ([mathjaxinline]\\text{N}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]F_{\\text{dashpot}}[/mathjaxinline] |  force exerted by the dashpot on the mass ([mathjaxinline]\\text{N}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] |  total force on the mass ([mathjaxinline]\\text{N}[/mathjaxinline]).      The independent variable is [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]; the position [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and the forces are functions of the independent variable [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].  Physics tells us that    * [mathjaxinline]F_{\\text{spring}}[/mathjaxinline] is a function of the position [mathjaxinline]x,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and has the opposite sign of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline];     * [mathjaxinline]F_{\\text{dashpot}}[/mathjaxinline] is a function of the velocity [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x},[/mathjaxinline] and again of opposite sign of [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline].   To simplify, approximate these by **linear** functions (probably OK if [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] are small):  [mathjax]\\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\text{Hooke's law}}} }{F_{\\text{spring}} = -k x}, \\qquad F_{\\text{dashpot}} = -b \\dot{x},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is the **spring constant** (in units [mathjaxinline]\\text{N}/\\text{m}[/mathjaxinline]) and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] is the **damping constant** (in units [mathjaxinline]\\text{N}\\, \\text{s}/\\text{m}[/mathjaxinline]); here [mathjaxinline]k,b>0[/mathjaxinline].    Substituting this and Newton's second law [mathjaxinline]\\, F=m \\ddot{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] into  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = F_{\\text{spring}} + F_{\\text{dashpot}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---      gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m \\ddot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -k x - b \\dot{x},[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---      a second order linear ODE, which we would usually write as  [mathjax]m {\\color{blue}{\\ddot{x}}} + b {\\color{blue}{\\dot{x}}} + k {\\color{blue}{x}} =0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is a second order linear homogeneous ODE with constant coefficients.  In the input/system/response language:    input signal: |  [mathjaxinline]0\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] (no external force on the mass)   ---|---   system: |  spring, mass, and dashpot   system response: |  [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline].      **Remark 5.2** We have assumed that the mass [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline], the damping constant [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], and the spring constant [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] do not vary with time. One can imagine this model still applies with [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] being functions of time, but we will not solve such DEs in this course.  (There can also be an external force acting directly on the mass, but we will leave that analysis for later.)  **Remark 5.3** Note we can divide by [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] to get standard linear form: [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\ddot{x}}} + \\frac{b}{m} {\\color{blue}{\\dot{x}}} + \\frac{k}{m} {\\color{blue}{x}} = 0.[/mathjaxinline] But this is not as common for this equation.  The differential equation that arises in this model is fundamental for all oscillatory behavior.  Modeling: a spring-mass-dashpot system", "filename": "06_higherorderlinearodes-tab5-text2.html", "title": "Modeling: a spring-mass-dashpot system"}

{"pageid": 186, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab4", "text": "**Question 4.1** Why does the complex replacement method work?  ###  Answer  If [mathjaxinline]z = x_1+ix_2[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the complex replacement ODE, i.e.,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle P(D) z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{i \\omega t} ,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.20)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P(D) (x_1+ix_2)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos \\omega t + i \\sin \\omega t.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.21)      Since [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] has real coefficients, taking the real parts of both sides gives  [mathjax]P(D) x_1 = \\cos \\omega t.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which says that [mathjaxinline]x_1[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the original ODE.  Note that for free we've actually solved another equation. Taking the imaginary parts of both gives us  [mathjax]P(D) x_2 = \\sin \\omega t.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Complex replacement is helpful also with other real input signals, with any real-valued function that can be written as the real part of a reasonably simple complex input signal. Here are some simple examples that would be helpful to have memorized:  **Real input signal**|  **Complex replacement**   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\cos \\omega t[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]A \\cos (\\omega t - \\phi )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]Ae^{i(\\omega t-\\phi )}[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]e^{at} \\cos \\omega t[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]e^{(a+i\\omega )t}[/mathjaxinline]      Using complex arithmetic, there is a more complicated formula which can be derived as well (it was derived in [Lecture 6: Sinusoids](/jump_to_id/06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab6))  **Real input signal**|  **Complex replacement**   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]a \\cos \\omega t + b \\sin \\omega t[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline](a-bi)e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline]      Each function in the first column is the real part of the corresponding function in the second column. The nice thing about these examples is that the complex replacement is a constant times a complex exponential, so ERF (or generalized ERF) applies.  Why does complex replacement work?", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Why does complex replacement work?"}

{"pageid": 187, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab3", "text": "**Complex replacement** is a method for finding **a particular solution** to an inhomogeneous linear ODE  [mathjax]P(D) x = {\\color{orange}{\\cos \\omega t}} ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] is a real polynomial, and [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] is a real number. (Note that in the video [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] was the unknown function.)    1. Write the right hand side of the equation [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{\\cos \\omega t}}[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(e^{i\\omega t} \\right)[/mathjaxinline]:   [mathjax]P(D)x = {\\color{orange}{\\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( e^{i\\omega t}\\right)}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---     2. Replace the right hand side of the differential equation with the complex exponential [mathjaxinline]e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline]. We need a new variable for the solution, which will be a complex function. Give the name [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{z}}[/mathjaxinline] for the unknown complex function. The **complexified** differential equation is this:   [mathjax]P(D) {\\color{blue}{z}} = \\underset {{\\color{blue}{\\text{complex replacement}}} }{{\\color{blue}{e^{i\\omega t}}} .}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (Note that in the video [mathjaxinline]\\tilde{y}[/mathjaxinline] was used instead of [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline].)    3. Use ERF (or generalized ERF if [mathjaxinline]P(i\\omega ) =0[/mathjaxinline]) to find a particular solution [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{z_p}}[/mathjaxinline] to the complexified ODE.   [mathjax]z_p = \\frac{e^{i\\omega t}}{P(i\\omega )}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---     4. Compute [mathjaxinline]x_p = \\mathrm{Re\\, }({\\color{blue}{z_p}} )[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline] is a particular solution to the **original** ODE.   The Complex Replacement Method", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab3-text1.html", "title": "The Complex Replacement Method"}

{"pageid": 192, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab14", "text": "Why are stable systems so great? If we are interested in understanding the long term behavior with respect to an exponential input, it is enough to find one particular solution. Keep in mind that while the long term behavior is enough to answer a question, there are some situations where the initial conditions and behavior as a system reaches steady state are important. {"pageid": 193, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@29_autonomousequations2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@29_autonomousequations2-tab8", "text": "A critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, x=a\\,[/mathjaxinline] is called    * **stable** if solutions starting near it move towards it,   ![A horizontal phase line with the point a indicated. An arrow to the left of a points rightward. An arrow to the right of a points leftward.](/static/images/u2s2_stablecp.svg)      * **unstable** if solutions starting near it move away from it,   ![A horizontal phase line with the point a indicated. An arrow to the left of a points leftward. An arrow to the right of a points rightward.](/static/images/u2s2_unstablecp.svg)      * **semistable** if the behavior depends on **which side** of the critical point the solution starts.    ![A horizontal phase line with the point a indicated. An arrow to the left of a points rightward. An arrow to the right of a points rightward.](/static/images/u2s2_semistabler.svg)|  or| ![A horizontal phase line with the point a indicated. An arrow to the left of a points leftward. An arrow to the right of a points leftward.](/static/images/u2s2_semistablel.svg)   ---|---|---     **Example 8.1**  ![A slope field with vertical axis y and horizontal axis t is shown. To the left of the slope field, the phase line is shown and is rotated so that it is vertical with positive infinity is at the top and negative infinity at the bottom. The points 0 and 3 are indicated on the phase line. The arrow above 3 points downward, the arrow between 0 and 3 points upward, and the arrow below 0 points downward. The values 0 and 3 correspond to the zero isoclines y equals 0 and y equals 3 in the slope field, respectively. Solutions above the line y equals 3 have negative slopes and tend to y equals 3 as t goes to infinity. Solutions between the lines y equals 0 and y equals 3 have positive slopes. These solutions tend to 3 as t goes to infinity but tend to 0 as t goes to negative infinity. Solutions below the line y equals 0 have negative slopes and tend to negative infinity as t goes to infinity.](/static/images/logisticsolutions_colored.svg)   Phase line (left) and solutions curves (right) of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y} = 3y-y^2\\,[/mathjaxinline]      In the previous example of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y} = 3y-y^2,\\,[/mathjaxinline], the critical points are [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline]. The phase line shows that [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] is unstable, and [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] is stable. Solutions move away from the unstable critical point [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] and approach the stable critical point [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] increases, as shown in the figure above.  **Remark 8.2** A solution corresponding to an **unstable** critical point is an example of a **separatrix** because it separates solutions having very different fates. In the example above, [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline] is a separatrix. A solution starting just **below** [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] tends to [mathjaxinline]-\\infty[/mathjaxinline], while a solution starting just **above** [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] tends to [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline]: very different fates!  **Summary: steps for understanding solutions to** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{y} = f(y)}}[/mathjaxinline] **qualitatively.**    1. Find the critical points by solving [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)=0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] These divide the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis into open intervals.     2. Determine the intervals of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] in which [mathjaxinline]f(y)>0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]f(y)<0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] by either graphing [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline] or evaluating [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline] at one point in each interval.     3. Draw the phase line, which consists of a line marked with [mathjaxinline]-\\infty[/mathjaxinline], the critical points, [mathjaxinline]+\\infty[/mathjaxinline], and arrows between these.     4. Solutions starting at a critical point are constant.     5. Other solutions tend to the limit that the arrow points to as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] increases. As [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] decreases, solutions tend to the limit that the arrow originates from.   Stability", "filename": "29_autonomousequations2-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Stability"}

{"pageid": 194, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@exitsurvey/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@exitsurvey-tab1", "text": "  Exit survey", "filename": "exitsurvey-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Exit survey"}

{"pageid": 195, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab7", "text": "Isoclines organize the slope field. The [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-isocline, also called the **nullcline** , is especially helpful. The critical points of all solutions to the DE lie on the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-isocline.  **Example 7.1** For [mathjaxinline]y'=y^2-x[/mathjaxinline], what is the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-isocline?  **Solution:** Here [mathjaxinline]f(x,y) \\colon =y^2-x[/mathjaxinline], so the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-isocline is the curve [mathjaxinline]y^2-x=0[/mathjaxinline], which is a parabola concave to the right. At every point of this parabola, the slope of the solution curve is [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline].  ![ ](/static/images/u2s1_0isocline.svg)  **Example 7.2** For [mathjaxinline]y'=y^2-x[/mathjaxinline], where are the points at which the slope of the solution curve is positive?  **Solution:** This will be the region in which [mathjaxinline]f(x,y)>0[/mathjaxinline]. The [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-isocline [mathjaxinline]f(x,y)=0[/mathjaxinline] divides the plane into regions, and [mathjaxinline]f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] has constant sign on each region. To test the sign, check one point in each region.   Recall [mathjaxinline]f(x,y) = y^2-x.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Since [mathjaxinline]\\, f(-1,0)=0^2-(-1)>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] by continuity it follows that [mathjaxinline]f(x,y)>0\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the entire region to the left of the parabola. Similarly, since [mathjaxinline]\\, f(1,0)=0^2-(1)<0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] it follows that [mathjaxinline]f(x,y)<0\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the region to the right of the parabola. Therefore, the answer is that the slope of the solution curve is negative in the region to the right of the parabola, and the slope of the solution is positive in the region to the left.  ![ ](/static/images/u2s1_0isoclineshaded.svg)  Zero Isoclines", "filename": "28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Zero Isoclines"}

{"pageid": 196, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab15", "text": "**Example 15.2** Consider the harmonic oscillator with a sinusoidal forcing term:  [mathjax]\\ddot x+\\omega _n^2x=A\\cos (\\omega t),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (where [mathjaxinline]A\\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline] is the input). Find a the complex gain, the gain, and the phase lag, and a particular solution. Food for thought: is this system stable?  ###  Worked Solution  This ODE has complex gain  [mathjax]G(\\omega ) = \\frac{1}{P(i\\omega )}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P(i\\omega )=(i\\omega )^2+\\omega _n^2=\\omega _n^2-\\omega ^2.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Thus a particular solution is given by  [mathjax]x_p=\\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(\\frac{1}{\\omega _n^2-\\omega ^2}Ae^{i\\omega t}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      as long as the input frequency is different from the natural frequency of the harmonic oscillator. Since the denominator is **real** , the real part is easy to find:  [mathjax]x_p=A\\frac{\\cos (\\omega t)}{\\omega _n^2-\\omega ^2}\\, .[/mathjax]| (5.34)   ---|---      Note that the gain is  [mathjax]g =| G(\\omega )| = \\frac{1}{|\\omega _n^2-\\omega ^2|}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Since the complex gain is real, the phase lag is either [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\pi[/mathjaxinline] depending on whether [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n > \\omega[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n < \\omega[/mathjaxinline].  This solution puts in precise form some of the things we can check from experimentation with vibrating systems. When the frequency of the signal is smaller than the natural frequency of the system, [mathjaxinline]\\omega <\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline], the denominator is positive. The effect is that the system response is a **positive** multiple of the signal: the vibration of the mass is \u201cin sync\" with the impressed force. As [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] increases towards [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline], the denominator of the particular solutions nears zero, so the amplitude of the solution grows arbitrarily large.  When [mathjaxinline]\\omega =\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline] the system is **in resonance** with the signal; the Exponential Response Formula fails because the gain would be infinite there, and there is **no** periodic (or even bounded) solution. This phenomena is called resonance, and will be discussed in more detail in the next section [11 Resonance and Frequency Response.](/jump_to_id/11_resonance-tab1)  When [mathjaxinline]\\omega >\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline], the denominator is negative. The system response is a **negative** multiple of the signal: the vibration of the mass is perfectly \u201cout of sync\" with the impressed force.  Since the coefficients are constant here, a time-shift of the signal results in the same time-shift of the solution:  [mathjax]\\ddot x+\\omega _n^2x=A\\cos (\\omega t-\\phi )[/mathjax]|   ---|---      has the periodic solution  [mathjax]x_p=A\\frac{\\cos (\\omega t-\\phi )}{\\omega _n^2-\\omega ^2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In particular, the same equation forced with a sine input curve  [mathjax]\\ddot y+\\omega _n^2y=A\\sin (\\omega t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      has response  [mathjax]y_p=A\\frac{\\sin (\\omega t)}{\\omega _n^2-\\omega ^2}\\,[/mathjax]| (5.35)   ---|---      by time invariance.  The equations [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_p=A\\frac{\\cos (\\omega t)}{\\omega _n^2-\\omega ^2}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_p=A\\frac{\\sin (\\omega t)}{\\omega _n^2-\\omega ^2}[/mathjaxinline] will be very useful to us when we solve ODEs via Fourier series in _Fourier Series and Partial Differential Equations_.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Forced harmonic oscillator", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab15-text2.html", "title": "Forced harmonic oscillator"}

It is a **nonlinear** , **autonomous** equation.  The logistic equation", "filename": "29_autonomousequations2-tab6-text1.html", "title": "The logistic equation"}

{"pageid": 200, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@01_odeintro/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@01_odeintro-tab6", "text": "  1. A **homogeneous linear ODE** is a differential equation such as   [mathjax]e^t \\, {\\color{blue}{\\ddot{y}}} + 5 \\, {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + t^9 \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      in which each summand is a function of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] times one of [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{y}}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\ddot{y}}}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline] .  **Most general** [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] **order homogeneous linear ODE:**  [mathjax]p_n(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + p_{n-1}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n-1)}}} \\dotsc + p_1(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p_0(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some functions [mathjaxinline]p_n(t)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]p_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] called the **coefficients** .    2. An **inhomogeneous linear ODE** is the same except that it has also **one term that is a function of** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{t}}[/mathjaxinline] **only** . For example,   [mathjax]e^t \\, {\\color{blue}{\\ddot{y}}} + 5 \\, {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + t^9 \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = {\\color{orange}{7 \\sin t}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is a second-order inhomogeneous linear ODE.  **Most general** [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] **order inhomogeneous linear ODE:**  [mathjax]p_n(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + p_{n-1}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n-1)}}} \\dotsb + p_1(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p_0(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = {\\color{orange}{q(t)}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some functions [mathjaxinline]p_n(t)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]p_0(t)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{q(t)}}[/mathjaxinline].    3. A **linear ODE** is an ODE that can be rearranged into either of the two types above.     4. Either of the two forms above can be reduced further by dividing the entire DE by [mathjaxinline]p_n(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] so that the coefficient of the highest derivative [mathjaxinline]y^{(n)}\\,[/mathjaxinline] becomes [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]. A differential equation written in either of the two forms above but with leading coefficient [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] is said to be in **standard linear form** .   [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + p_{n-1}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n-1)}}} \\dotsb + p_1(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p_0(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---   [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + p_{n-1}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y^{(n-1)}}} \\dotsb + p_1(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + p_0(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{y}} = {\\color{orange}{q(t)}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---    **Remark 6.1** We insist that solutions [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] are defined on an entire open interval [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline], as opposed to disjoint intervals. We will always assume the functions [mathjaxinline]p_n(t)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]p_{n-1}(t)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]p_0(t)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]q(t)[/mathjaxinline] are well behaved, for example continuous, on [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline]. (We'll look at more complicated functions in our class _Transfer Functions and the Laplace Transform_.)  ###  What is an open interval?  An **open interval** is a connected set of real numbers without endpoints. The notation [mathjaxinline](a, b)[/mathjaxinline] denotes the open interval of all points [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]a < x < b[/mathjaxinline]. It is conventional to allow one or both end points to be infinite: [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline](-\\infty ,b)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline](a,\\infty )[/mathjaxinline]. The open interval [mathjaxinline](-\\infty ,\\infty )[/mathjaxinline] denotes the entire real line, which is often denoted by [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Remark 6.2** If you already know that an ODE is linear, there is an easy test to decide if it is homogeneous or not: Plug in the constant function [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline].    * If [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline] is a solution, the ODE is homogeneous.     * If [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline] is not a solution, the ODE is inhomogeneous.   **Remark 6.3** The cell division example gives us a homogeneous equation. If you start with no yeast cells, the population stays at [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline].  For an ODE to be **nonlinear** , the functions [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{y}}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\dotsc[/mathjaxinline] must enter the equation in a more complicated way: raised to powers, multiplied by each other, or with nonlinear functions applied to them.  More terminology", "filename": "01_odeintro-tab6-text1.html", "title": "More terminology"}

{"pageid": 201, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@11_resonance/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@11_resonance-tab5", "text": "In a realistic physical situation, there is at least a tiny amount of damping, and this prevents the runaway growth of the amplitude of the system response that we saw in the previous section.  **Question 5.1** What happens if [mathjaxinline]\\omega =3[/mathjaxinline] exactly, but there is a tiny amount of damping, so that the ODE is  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} + \\underset {{\\color{blue}{\\text{damping term}}} }{b \\dot{x}} + 9 x = \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\text{input signal}}} }{\\cos \\omega t}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some small positive constant [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Answer  The new characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]P(r)=r^2+br+9[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]3i[/mathjaxinline] is no longer a root, the ERF applies. The complex gain is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G= \\frac{1}{P(3i)} = \\frac{1}{3bi}[/mathjaxinline], and the gain is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle |G| = \\frac{1}{3b}[/mathjaxinline]. This is large, but the oscillations are bounded; there is a steady-state solution.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Resonance with damping", "filename": "11_resonance-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Resonance with damping"}

{"pageid": 202, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab2", "text": "Recall the spring mass system from [Lecture 1](/jump_to_id/01_odeintro-tab12):  ![A spring is attached to a wall on the left and a cart on the right. The cart has wheels and can roll either left or right.](/static/images/springmass.svg)  Using Newton's second law, we found a second order linear homogeneous DE that describes the displacement [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] of the mass:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m{\\color{blue}{\\ddot x}} + {\\color{orange}{k}} {\\color{blue}{x}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.65)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Let us now look at the solutions to this equation. For simplicity, let [mathjaxinline]\\, m=k=1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] so the equation becomes  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{x} +x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.66)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      We will use this example to discuss some properties of the solutions before diving into the technique of solving this kind of equation.     **Question 2.1** From your experience with calculus, what functions satisfy [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x}=-x[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Answer:  If [mathjaxinline]x = \\cos (t)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x} = -\\sin (t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{x} = -\\cos (t)[/mathjaxinline]. A similar calculation shows that [mathjaxinline]\\sin (t)[/mathjaxinline] is a solution too. {"pageid": 203, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab2", "text": "**Separation of variables** is a technique that reduces the problem of solving certain first-order ODEs to evaluating two integrals.  Separation of variables works when we can write the equation in the form  [mathjax]\\frac{dy}{dt} \\, = \\, g(t)f(y) .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Here's an example.  **Example 2.1** Solve [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y} - 2ty = 0[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:**    1. Isolate the derivative and express in the form [mathjaxinline]\\dot y = h(t,y)[/mathjaxinline]:   [mathjax]\\dot y = 2ty .[/mathjax]|   ---|---     2. Write as   [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dt} =g(t)f(y) = 2ty, \\qquad \\qquad \\left( \\, g(t) = 2t, \\quad f(y) = y\\, \\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---     3. Separation: Put the terms involving [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] on the left and terms involving [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] on the right.   [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{f(y)}= g(t)dt \\iff \\frac{dy}{y} = 2t\\, dt[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Warning:** We divided by [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline], so at some point we will have to check [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline] as a potential solution.    4. Integrate.   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\frac{dy}{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int 2t\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.14)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln |y|+C_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t^2 + C_2[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.15)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln |y|[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t^2 + (C_2-C_1)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.16)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln |y|[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t^2 + C[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.17)       **Note:** The method reduces to evaluating two integrals separately, one in [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] and one in [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. Observe that we combined the two constants [mathjaxinline]C_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]C_2[/mathjaxinline] of integration into one constant [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline]. We will combine the two constants to form [mathjaxinline]C = C_2-C_1[/mathjaxinline] immediately from now on.    5. Solve for [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline].   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle |y|[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{t^2+C}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\pm e^C e^{t^2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      As [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] runs over all real numbers, the coefficient [mathjaxinline]\\pm e^C[/mathjaxinline] runs over all nonzero real numbers. Thus the solutions we have found so far are  [mathjax]y = c e^{t^2}, \\quad c\\neq 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---     6. Because we divided by [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline], there is possibly an exceptional solution [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline]. Checking directly, it turns out that it is indeed a solution. It can be considered as the function [mathjaxinline]c e^{t^2}[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]c=0[/mathjaxinline].   **Conclusion:** The general solution to [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y} - 2ty = 0[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]y = c e^{t^2},\\quad \\text{where } c \\text{ is any real number.}[/mathjax]|   ---|---     7. (Optional) Double check your solution. Plugging in [mathjaxinline]y=ce^{t^2}[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y} - 2ty = 0[/mathjaxinline] gives [mathjaxinline]c e^{t^2} (2t) - 2t c e^{t^2} = 0[/mathjaxinline], which is true, as it should be.   **Separation of variables, the systematic procedure:**    1. Check that the DE is a **first-order ODE** . (If not, give up and try another method.) Suppose that the function to be solved for is [mathjaxinline]y=y(t)[/mathjaxinline].     2. Rewrite [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline].     3. Express [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] as a function of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] only.   [mathjax]\\frac{dy}{dt} \\, = \\, h(t,y) .[/mathjax]|   ---|---     4. If you are lucky, you can write [mathjaxinline]h(t,y)[/mathjaxinline] as a product of two functions, one of which is purely a function of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]; and the other purely a function of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]:   [mathjax]h(t,y) = g(t)f(y)[/mathjax]|   ---|---     5. Separate the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]'s and [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]'s. Specifically, try to multiply and/or divide (and in particular move the [mathjaxinline]dt[/mathjaxinline] to the right side) so that the equation ends up as an equality of differentials of the form   [mathjax]\\, \\frac{ dy}{f(y)} = g(t) \\, dt.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Note:** If there are factors involving both variables, such as [mathjaxinline]y+t[/mathjaxinline], then it is impossible to separate variables; in this case, give up and try a different method.  **Warning:** Dividing by [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)[/mathjaxinline] invalidates the calculation if [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] so at the end, check what happens if [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)=0[/mathjaxinline]; this may add to the list of solutions.    6. Integrate both sides to get an equation of the form   [mathjax]F(y) = G(t) + C.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      These are implicit equations for the solutions, in terms of a parameter [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline].    7. If possible (and if desired), solve for [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].     8. Check for extra solutions coming from dividing by zero (see the warning in Step 5). The solutions in the previous step and this step comprise the general solution.     9. (Optional, but recommended) Check your work by verifying that the general solution actually satisfies the original DE.   ###  A justification of separation of variables  In the argument above, the step where we multiply by [mathjaxinline]dt[/mathjaxinline] seems informal. To justify this step, we check that it works in reverse. If  [mathjax]\\frac{d}{dy} H(y) = \\frac{1}{f(y)} \\qquad \\frac{d}{dt} G(t) = g(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the function [mathjaxinline]y=y(t)[/mathjaxinline] is implicitly defined by  [mathjax]H(y) = G(t) +C.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Implicitly differentiate this to see that we get the differential equation we started with.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} H(y)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\left( G(t) +C\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.18)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dH}{dy}\\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dG}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.19)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{f(y)} \\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle g(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.20)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(y)g(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.21)      The technique of multiplying by differentials allows us to work backwards to the formula for the solution.  What about the exceptional solution? If [mathjaxinline]f(y_0)=0[/mathjaxinline] for a constant [mathjaxinline]y_0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]y(t) = y_0[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the differential equation since [mathjaxinline]\\dot y = f(y_0)g(t) = 0[/mathjaxinline] holds true (as both sides evaluate to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]).  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Separation of variables for first order ODEs", "filename": "02_solvingafirstorderode-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Separation of variables for first order ODEs"}

{"pageid": 206, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab13", "text": "**Complex numbers** are expressions of the form [mathjaxinline]a+bi[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are real numbers, and [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] is a new symbol. As an example, the point 2 minus i is plotted at the coordinate 2 comma negative 1.](/static/images/complex_plane03.svg)   **Figure :** A point in the complex plane.      ### Operations on complex numbers   **real part**|  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(a+bi) \\, \\colon =\\, a[/mathjaxinline] |   ---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(2-i) = 2[/mathjaxinline]| ![The point 2 minus i is plotted in the complex plane at the coordiante 2 comma negative 1. The real part is indicated by a vertical line segment starting at the coordinate 2 comma 0 and extending downward to the point 2 comma negative 1.](/static/images/complex_plane_realpart.svg)    **imaginary part**|  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Im\\, }(a+bi) \\, \\colon =\\, b[/mathjaxinline] |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Im\\, }(2-i) = -1[/mathjaxinline]| ![The point 2 minus i is plotted in the complex plane at the coordiante 2 comma negative 1. The real part is indicated by a horizontal line segment starting at the coordinate 0 comma negative 1 and extending to the right to the point 2 comma negative 1.](/static/images/complex_plane_complexpart.svg)    **complex conjugate**|  [mathjaxinline]\\overline{a+bi} \\, \\colon =\\, a-bi[/mathjaxinline] |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\overline{2-i} \\, = \\, 2+i[/mathjaxinline]| ![The point 2 minus i is plotted in the complex plane at the coordiante 2 comma negative 1. Its conjugate 2 plus i is plotted at the coordinate 2 comma 1.](/static/images/complex_plane_conjugation.svg)       **Note:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Im\\, }(a+bi) = b[/mathjaxinline] is a real number. It is not [mathjaxinline]bi[/mathjaxinline].    **Note:** To find the complex conjugate, negate the imaginary component. This is equivalent to reflecting the complex number across the real axis.    The **absolute value** (or **magnitude** or **modulus** ) [mathjaxinline]|z|[/mathjaxinline] of a complex number [mathjaxinline]z=a+bi[/mathjaxinline] is its distance to the origin:  [mathjax]|a+bi| \\colon =\\sqrt{a^2+b^2} \\qquad \\textrm{(this is a real number).}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ### Some useful identities  The following are true for all complex numbers [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Re\\, }z = \\frac{z+\\overline{z}}{2}, \\qquad \\mathrm{Im\\, }z = \\frac{z-\\overline{z}}{2i}, \\qquad \\overline{\\overline{z}} = z, \\qquad z \\overline{z} = |z|^2.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Also, for any **real** number [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] and complex number [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(cz) = c \\, \\mathrm{Re\\, }z,\\qquad \\mathrm{Im\\, }(cz) = c \\, \\mathrm{Im\\, }z.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ### Polar form of a complex number  Given a nonzero complex number [mathjaxinline]z=a+bi[/mathjaxinline], we can express the point [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline] in polar coordinates [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]a = r \\cos \\theta , \\qquad b = r \\sin \\theta .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Then  [mathjax]a + bi = (r \\cos \\theta ) + (r \\sin \\theta )i = r ( \\cos \\theta + i \\sin \\theta ).[/mathjax]|   ---|---   ![The point a plus b i is plotted in the first quadrant. A vector extends from the origin to the point a plus b i. This vector has magnitude r and makes an angle theta with the positive x axis. The point is labeled r times e to the i theta.](/static/images/polar_form01.svg)  Any possible [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] (a possible value for the **angle** or **argument** of [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline]) may be called [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\arg z}}[/mathjaxinline], but this is dangerously ambiguous notation since there are many values of [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] for the same [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline].  [mathjax]{\\color{orange}{\\textrm{Euler's formula:}}} \\qquad e^{it}=\\cos (t)+i\\sin (t)[/mathjax]| (3.47)   ---|---  Summary", "filename": "03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 207, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab1", "text": "**Objectives**    * Represent **complex numbers** geometrically as points on the **complex plane** .     * Represent complex numbers algebraically in **cartesian form** and **polar form** as a complex exponential using **Euler's formula** .     * Perform basic operations on complex numbers: **conjugation** , taking the **real and imaginary parts** , finding the **absolute value** , and determining possible values of the **argument** .     * Perform **arithmetic on complex numbers** : addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, roots and powers in both cartesian and polar forms.     * Differentiate (and integrate) **complex-valued functions of a real variable** by breaking up such functions into their real and imaginary parts, and differentiating (and integrating) component-wise.   Objectives", "filename": "03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 208, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab12", "text": "The characteristics of solution curves that we have been discussing are true for both linear and nonlinear equations. But there is often a big difference between the domain of definition of solutions to linear and nonlinear DEs.    For first order **linear DEs** of the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle y'=f(x,y) \\qquad \\text{where}\\, f(x,y)=q(x)-p(x)y,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.14)   ---|---|---|---      recall that any solution defined at [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] is defined on the **entire interval** which contains [mathjaxinline]\\, a\\,[/mathjaxinline] and on which [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]q(x)[/mathjaxinline] are continuous. (Note that [mathjaxinline]\\, p\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, q\\,[/mathjaxinline] being continuous is equivalent to the hypothesis of the general existence/uniqueness theorem presented in this lecture, namely, that [mathjaxinline]\\, f\\,[/mathjaxinline] and[mathjaxinline]\\, \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are continuous.)    For **nonlinear DEs** , solutions do not have to be defined on the entire interval on which [mathjaxinline]\\, f\\,[/mathjaxinline] and[mathjaxinline]\\, \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}[/mathjaxinline] are continuous. Consider the following example.  **Example 12.1** Draw the solution curve to [mathjaxinline]y'=y^2\\,[/mathjaxinline] that satisfies the condition [mathjaxinline]\\, y(0)=1\\,[/mathjaxinline]. What is the domain of definition of this solution curve?  **Solution:** This DE is nonlinear, so our methods of solving linear DEs do not apply. We solve it by separation of variables:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = y^2[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y^{-2} \\, dy[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = dx \\qquad (y\\neq 0)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int y^{-2} \\, dy[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int dx[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{y^{-1}}{-1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = x + C \\qquad (\\textrm{for some constant } C)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{-1}{x + C} .[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The condition [mathjaxinline]\\, y(0)=1\\,[/mathjaxinline] leads to  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1 \\, =\\, \\frac{-1}{0+C}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C = -1,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      which gives the solution  [mathjax]y = \\frac{-1}{x-1} = \\frac{1}{1-x}\\qquad \\text{where}\\, -\\infty <x<1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore, here is the solution curve:  ![ ](/static/images/u2s1_halfhyperbola.svg)    The solution approaches [mathjaxinline]\\infty[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]x\\rightarrow 1^-[/mathjaxinline]. We say that the solution **blows up** at [mathjaxinline]x=1.\\,[/mathjaxinline] The domain of definition of the solution is [mathjaxinline]-\\infty <x<1[/mathjaxinline]. It is also called the **interval of validity** of the solution. The **interval of validity** of a solution is the largest interval on which it can be defined.    The graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, y= \\frac{1}{1-x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] consists of both branches of the hyperbola. But **be careful** , the full hyperbola is not a solution; only the branch through the point [mathjaxinline]\\, (x,y)=(0,1)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is.    For nonlinear DEs, the interval of validity of a solution cannot be read off from the equation. It can be much smaller than the domain on which the equation is defined.  Interval of validity", "filename": "28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Interval of validity"}

{"pageid": 209, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@12_rlc/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@12_rlc-tab4", "text": "Let us now use the gain to explain the qualitative behavior we just saw in the lab.  **Recall from complex numbers:** The modulus of a complex number [mathjaxinline]z=a+ib[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]|z|= \\sqrt{a^2+b^2}[/mathjaxinline] and therefore the modulus squared is [mathjaxinline]|z|^2 = a^2+b^2[/mathjaxinline].  video notes", "filename": "12_rlc-tab4-text1.html", "title": "video notes"}

{"pageid": 210, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@01_odeintro/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@01_odeintro-tab12", "text": "One of the most important sources for differential equations comes from Newton's second law  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ma.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      That is, force equals mass times acceleration. This is a differential equation! For now we restrict our attention to 1-dimensional systems. The acceleration [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] is the second time derivative of position [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], which is [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\ddot{x}}}[/mathjaxinline]. Thus we can rewrite the equation as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m{\\color{blue}{\\ddot{x}}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      What is creating that force? The force depends on the system we are modeling. We will start with a very simple toy model that will serve as the basis for almost every other model we will encounter in this course.  **Example 12.1** Model a spring attached to a wall, with a mass on the other end sitting on a cart that moves without friction. We pull the cart back and release it. How does the mass on the cart behave?  **Solution:** To begin the modeling process, let's **draw a diagram** .  ![A spring is attached to a wall on the left and a cart on the right. The cart has wheels and can roll either left or right.](/static/images/hanging- mass.svg)      Next, let's **label the elements of interest** in the diagram. We have the mass [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline], and the strength of the spring [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline], which appears in Hooke's law.  The variable of interest is the position of the mass. What do we mean by the position of the mass? The most natural way to record the position of the mass is to consider the displacement of the mass [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{x}}[/mathjaxinline] away from the position when the spring is relaxed [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{x}} =0[/mathjaxinline]. We also have to decide on the sign, so we choose [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline] when the spring is stretched, which is sensible given our picture.  ![A spring is attached to a wall on the left and a cart on the right. The cart has wheels and can roll either left or right. When x equals 0, the spring is neither stretched nor compressed. When x is greater than zero, the cart is pulled towards the right and the spring is stretched. When x is less than zero, the cart is pushed towards the left and the spring is compressed.](/static/images/hanging-mass-displacement.svg)      Let's try to put this into the **input/ system response** paradigm we've just introduced. The system response is the displacement of the mass. This is what we are interested in.  What is the input signal? You could imagine that there are other forces acting on the mass, like there is a sail on the mass, and wind is blowing on the sail creating an input signal. But we are going to start by considering the case where the input signal is [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]. Note that pulling the cart back and releasing it specifies the initial state of the system, that is, it gives the initial conditions.  Now we are ready to **write down the differential equation** . The equation is governed by Newton's second law  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F = m{\\color{blue}{\\ddot x}} .[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      We need to identify the forces acting on the mass. There is the force due to the spring. For the moment, we assume that air resistance is negligible, and there is no friction on the cart.  What is the spring force? When the displacement is positive, the spring is stretched, the force is negative. When the displacement is negative, the spring is compressed, the force is positive. Thus this force is modeled linearly by Hooke's law  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -{\\color{orange}{k}} {\\color{blue}{x}} ,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      which is a function of the displacement [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{x}}[/mathjaxinline] away from the neutral position [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{x}} =0[/mathjaxinline]. Note that this linear model is only valid for relatively small displacements. If we stretch the spring too far, the spring force won't obey this linear law anymore.  The position at time [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]\\, x(0)=x_0[/mathjaxinline] for some positive displacement [mathjaxinline]\\, x_0>0[/mathjaxinline]. From the problem statement, we assume that we release the cart with zero initial velocity, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot x(0) =0[/mathjaxinline].  Putting this all together, we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -{\\color{orange}{k}} {\\color{blue}{x}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m{\\color{blue}{\\ddot x}}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.8)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      with initial conditions  [mathjax]x(0) = x_0, \\qquad \\qquad \\dot x(0) =0.[/mathjax]| (2.9)   ---|---      The last step is to **write this in standard linear form** . (In this case, put all the terms involving the response on the left hand side, but omit the step of dividing through by [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] to make the leading coefficient [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], because this equation is more typically written as below.) We obtain the following differential equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m{\\color{blue}{\\ddot x}} + {\\color{orange}{k}} {\\color{blue}{x}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.10)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(0) = x_0[/mathjaxinline] |  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot x(0) = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.11)       **Example 12.2** Now let's consider the same mass/spring system as above where we've add a sail to the mass.  ![A spring is attached to a wall on the left and a cart on the right. The cart has wheels and can roll either left or right. A sail is attached to the top of the mass.](/static/images/hanging-mass-labels.svg)      The mass now experiences an additional external force from the wind. How does this change the model?  **Solution:** The model is exactly the same. The only difference is that the input signal is no longer zero, rather it is now the external force due to the wind on the sail. This external force [mathjaxinline]F_{\\text{wind}}(t)[/mathjaxinline] depends on time in some complicated way that we will not try to write down. The differential equation for this system is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m{\\color{blue}{\\ddot x}} + {\\color{orange}{k}} {\\color{blue}{x}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F_{\\text{wind}}(t),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.12)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      with initial conditions  [mathjax]x(0) = x_0, \\qquad \\qquad \\dot x(0) =0.[/mathjax]| (2.13)   ---|---  Newtonian mechanics", "filename": "01_odeintro-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Newtonian mechanics"}

{"pageid": 211, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@08_higherorder/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@08_higherorder-tab9", "text": "ODEs with real coefficients have real valued functions as their solutions. However, our solution method often requires us to deal with complex solutions as well. Let us recall how this works in the familiar example of the undamped spring mass system.    Recall the second order ODE that models a spring mass system with no damping:  [mathjax]\\ddot{y} + y = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]r^2+1[/mathjaxinline], which factors as [mathjaxinline](r-i)(r+i)[/mathjaxinline]. Its roots are [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-i[/mathjaxinline]. Thus, [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{it}, e^{-it}\\,[/mathjaxinline] form a basis for the space of solutions, and the general solution is  [mathjax]c_1 e^{it} + c_2 e^{-it}, \\qquad \\textrm{where } c_1,c_2 \\in \\mathbb {C}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Due to Euler's formula [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{it} = \\cos t + i \\sin t\\,[/mathjaxinline] (or the pair of reverse formulas [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos t = \\frac{e^{it}+e^{-it}}{2}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\sin t = \\frac{e^{it}-e^{-it}}{2i}),\\,[/mathjaxinline] the general solution above is the same as  [mathjax]d_1 \\cos t + d_2 \\sin t, \\qquad \\textrm{where } \\, d_1,d_2 \\in \\mathbb {C}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In our new terminology,  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Span}(e^{it}, e^{-it})=\\mathrm{Span}(\\cos t,\\sin t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (assuming that complex numbers are allowed as coefficients in the linear combinations).    Moreover, the two pairs of functions on the left and on the right above are both **bases** of the set of all solutions since both pairs of functions are linearly independent.    Review: complex roots", "filename": "08_higherorder-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Review: complex roots"}

{"pageid": 212, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab4", "text": "Complex conjugation, changing [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]-i[/mathjaxinline], transforms the equation [mathjaxinline]i^2=-1[/mathjaxinline] into a true equation [mathjaxinline](-i)^2=-1[/mathjaxinline], so it will also preserve any equation that is deduced from [mathjaxinline]i^2=-1[/mathjaxinline]. The definitions of addition and multiplication used only [mathjaxinline]i^2=-1[/mathjaxinline], so addition and multiplication respect complex conjugation. For example, if complex numbers satisfy [mathjaxinline]y=z+w[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\bar{y}=\\bar{z}+\\bar{w}[/mathjaxinline]. In other words,  [mathjax]\\overline{z+w} = \\bar{z} + \\bar{w}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Similarly,  [mathjax]\\overline{zw} = \\bar{z} \\, \\bar{w}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      What does this multiplication rule say if [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] happens to be a real number [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline]? Answer: [mathjaxinline]\\overline{aw} = a \\bar{w}[/mathjaxinline].  Complex conjugation", "filename": "03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Complex conjugation"}
