{"pageid": 214, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@08_higherorder/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@08_higherorder-tab10", "text": "How do we get a real basis for the solutions to a **higher order** homogeneous ODE with constant **real coefficients** and whose characteristic roots are not all real? The answer is that we replace pairs of complex solutions with their real and imaginary parts.   **Example 10.1** Find a basis of solutions to  [mathjax]y^{(3)} + 3 \\ddot{y} + 9 \\dot{y} - 13 y = 0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      consisting of **real-valued** functions.  **Solution:**   The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]\\, P(r) \\colon =r^3+3r^2+9r-13.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Checking the divisors of [mathjaxinline]-13[/mathjaxinline] (as instructed by the rational root test), we find that [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] is a root, so [mathjaxinline]r-1[/mathjaxinline] is a factor. Long division (or solving for unknown coefficients) produces the other factor:  [mathjax]P(r) = (r-1)(r^2+4r+13).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The quadratic formula, or completing the square (rewriting the second factor as [mathjaxinline](r+2)^2 + 9[/mathjaxinline]), shows that the roots of [mathjaxinline]\\, P(r)[/mathjaxinline] are [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]-2+3i[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]-2-3i[/mathjaxinline]. Thus [mathjaxinline]e^t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{(-2+3i)t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{(-2-3i)t}[/mathjaxinline] form a basis of solutions. But the last two are not real-valued!  So instead replace [mathjaxinline]y=e^{(-2+3i)t}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\overline{y}=e^{(-2-3i)t}[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(y)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Im\\, }(y)[/mathjaxinline], found by expanding  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{(-2+3i)t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = e^{-2t} e^{i(3t)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = e^{-2t} \\left( \\cos (3t) + i \\sin (3t) \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = e^{-2t} \\cos (3t) + i \\, e^{-2t} \\sin (3t).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Thus  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{e^t,\\quad e^{-2t} \\cos (3t), \\quad e^{-2t} \\sin (3t)}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is another basis, this time consisting of real-valued functions.  **Example 10.2** Suppose the roots \u2014with multiplicity\u2014 of the characteristic polynomial of a certain homogeneous constant coefficient linear equation are  [mathjax]3, \\, 4, \\, 4, \\, 4, \\, 5\\pm 2i, \\, 5\\pm 2i.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Give the general real solution to the equation. What is the order of the equation?  **Solution:**   A basis for the real valued solutions is given by  [mathjax]\\\\{ e^{3t}, \\, e^{4t}, \\, te^{4t}, \\, t^2e^{4t}, \\, e^{5t}\\cos (2t), \\, e^{5t}\\sin (2t), \\, te^{5t}\\cos (2t), \\, te^{5t}\\sin (2t)\\\\} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      (For each repeated root we added a power of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] to the basic solution.) Using superposition, the general solution is a linear combination of these basis solutions  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t) =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, c_1e^{3t}+ c_2e^{4t}+c_3te^{4t} +c_4t^2e^{4t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle + c_5e^{5t}\\cos (2t)+c_6 e^{5t}\\sin (2t) + c_7te^{5t}\\cos (2t) + c_8 te^{5t}\\sin (2t).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      There are 8 roots, so the order of the differential equation is 8.  We can obtain real solutions to linear ODEs with nonconstant real coefficients as well:  **Complex basis vs. real-valued basis.** Let [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] be a complex-valued function of a real- valued variable [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. If [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\overline{y}[/mathjaxinline] are part of a basis of solutions to a homogeneous linear system of ODEs with **real coefficients** , then  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\textrm{replacing }\\quad y,\\, \\overline{y} \\quad \\textrm{ by } \\quad \\mathrm{Re\\, }(y), \\, \\mathrm{Im\\, }(y)}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      gives a new basis of the homogeneous solutions.    ###  Why is this true?  To know that the new list, which includes [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{Re\\, }(y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{Im\\, }(y),\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a basis, we need to check two things:    1. **The span of the new list is the set of all solutions.**   This is true, because any solution is a linear combination of the old basis, and can be converted to a linear combination of the new list by substituting  [mathjax]y = \\mathrm{Re\\, }(y) + i \\, \\mathrm{Im\\, }(y), \\qquad \\overline{y} = \\mathrm{Re\\, }(y) - i \\, \\mathrm{Im\\, }(y).[/mathjax]|   ---|---     2. **The new list is linearly **independent.** **   If not, say  [mathjax]c_1 \\mathrm{Re\\, }(y) + c_2 \\mathrm{Im\\, }(y) + \\cdots = 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then substituting  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(y) = \\frac{y+\\overline{y}}{2}, \\qquad \\mathrm{Im\\, }(y) = \\frac{y-\\overline{y}}{2i}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      would show that the old basis was linearly dependent, which is impossible for a basis.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Higher order ODEs with complex roots", "filename": "08_higherorder-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Higher order ODEs with complex roots"}

{"pageid": 215, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@29_autonomousequations2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@29_autonomousequations2-tab4", "text": "**Definition 4.1** The values of [mathjaxinline]\\, y\\,[/mathjaxinline] at which [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)=0\\,[/mathjaxinline] are called the **critical points** or **equilibria** of the autonomous equation [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}=f(y)[/mathjaxinline].  If [mathjaxinline]y_0[/mathjaxinline] is a critical point of an autonomous equation, then [mathjaxinline]\\, y=y_0\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a constant (or horizontal, or equilibrium) solution, because the derivative of a constant function is [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]. The [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-isocline of an autonomous equation consists of all the constant solutions.  ![An example of a slope field with zero isoclines at y equals y sub 1 and y equals y sub 0 where y sub 1 is greater than y sub 0. Solutions above y equals y sub 1 and below y equals y sub 0 have negative slopes \\(down region\\) where f of y is less than 0. Solutions between y equals y sub 1 and y equals y sub 0 have positive slopes \\(up region\\) where f of y is greater than 0.](/static/images/autonomous0isocline_newcolors.svg)   The constant solutions [mathjaxinline]\\, y=y_0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y=y_1\\,[/mathjaxinline]   (where [mathjaxinline]y_0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y_1[/mathjaxinline] are critical points) divide   the [mathjaxinline](t,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane plane into \"up\" and \"down\" regions.      Recall that for any first order DE, the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-isocline divides the [mathjaxinline](t,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane into \u201cup\" regions, where [mathjaxinline]\\, f>0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and solutions are increasing, and \u201cdown\" regions, where [mathjaxinline]\\, f<0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and solutions are decreasing. For autonomous equations, the qualitative behaviour of all solutions is encoded by the critical points and the signs of [mathjaxinline]f(y)[/mathjaxinline] in the intervals between the critical points.    To find the qualitative behaviour of solutions to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}=f(y),\\,[/mathjaxinline] we follow two steps:    1. Find the critical points. That is, solve [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)=0[/mathjaxinline].     2. Determine the intervals of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] in which [mathjaxinline]f(y)>0[/mathjaxinline] and in which [mathjaxinline]f(y)<0[/mathjaxinline]. These are intervals in which solutions are increasing and decreasing respectively.   We will use these steps in the next two examples.    Critical points and qualitative behavior of solutions", "filename": "29_autonomousequations2-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Critical points and qualitative behavior of solutions"}

{"pageid": 216, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@08_higherorder/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@08_higherorder-tab8", "text": "Equipped with the linear algebra notions, we now generalize the solution method we used for second order homogeneous constant coefficient ODEs, such as [mathjaxinline]\\, \\ddot{y} - \\dot{y} + 6 y = 0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] to solve homogeneous constant coefficient ODEs of any order.    Given  [mathjax]a_n {\\color{blue}{y^{(n)}}} + \\cdots + a_1 {\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + a_0 {\\color{blue}{y}} = 0,[/mathjax]| (4.99)   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]a_n,\\ldots ,a_0[/mathjaxinline] are **real** constants, do the following:    1. Write down the **characteristic equation**  [mathjax]a_n r^n + \\cdots + a_1 r + a_0 = 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      in which the coefficient of [mathjaxinline]r^j[/mathjaxinline] is the coefficient of [mathjaxinline]y^{(j)}[/mathjaxinline] from the ODE. The left hand side is called the **characteristic polynomial** [mathjaxinline]\\, P(r).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] For example, [mathjaxinline]\\, y^{(4)} - 2y^{(2)}+y = 0\\,[/mathjaxinline] has characteristic polynomial [mathjaxinline]r^4-2r^2+1.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]    2. Factor [mathjaxinline]\\, P(r)\\,[/mathjaxinline] as   [mathjax]P(r)\\, =\\, a_n (r-r_1)(r-r_2)\\cdots (r-r_n)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the [mathjaxinline]\\, n\\,[/mathjaxinline] roots [mathjaxinline]\\, r_1,\\ldots ,r_n\\,[/mathjaxinline] are (possibly complex) numbers. There are guaranteed to be [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] (possibly complex) roots counted with multiplicity by the fundamental theorem of algebra. The roots may be all distinct or some roots may be repeated.      3. If [mathjaxinline]\\, r_1,\\ldots ,r_n\\,[/mathjaxinline] are **distinct** , then the functions [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{r_1 t},\\ldots ,e^{r_n t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] form a basis for the vector space of solutions to the constant coefficient ODE. In other words, the general solution is   [mathjax]c_1 e^{r_1 t} + \\cdots + c_n e^{r_n t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that complex roots always appear in pairs of conjugates, and if some of the roots are complex, the coefficients [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1,\\, \\ldots ,\\, c_n\\,[/mathjaxinline] will have to be complex as well.    4. If [mathjaxinline]\\, r_1,\\ldots ,r_n[/mathjaxinline] are **not distinct** , then [mathjaxinline]e^{r_1 t},\\ldots ,e^{r_n t}[/mathjaxinline] cannot be a basis since some of these functions are redundant (definitely not linearly independent)! If a particular root [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] is repeated [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] times, then   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{replace}\\quad[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\overbrace{e^{rt},\\quad e^{rt},\\quad e^{rt},\\quad \\ldots ,\\quad e^{rt}}^{{\\color{orange}{m \\textrm{ copies}}} }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.100)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textrm{by}\\quad[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{rt},\\quad te^{rt},\\quad t^2 e^{rt},\\quad \\ldots ,\\quad t^{m-1} e^{rt}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.101)      We'll explain why this works in the next lecture.         **Important:** In all cases,  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{ \\text{Number of roots of } \\, P(r)\\, \\text{ counted with multiplicity}\\, =\\text{Order of ODE}\\, =\\, \\text{Number of functions in basis},}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      as asserted in the dimension theorem.  **Example 8.1** Find the general solution to  [mathjax]y^{(6)} + 6 y^{(5)} + 9 y^{(4)} = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Solution:**   The characteristic polynomial is  [mathjax]r^6 + 6 r^5 + 9 r^4 = r^4(r+3)^2,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      whose roots listed with multiplicity are  [mathjax]0,0,0,0,-3,-3.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Since the roots are not distinct, the basis is **not**  [mathjax]e^{0t}, \\quad e^{0t}, \\quad e^{0t}, \\quad e^{0t}, \\quad e^{-3t}, \\quad e^{-3t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We need to replace the first block of four functions, and also the last block of two functions. So the correct basis is  [mathjax]\\underbrace{e^{0t}, \\quad t e^{0t}, \\quad t^2 e^{0t}, \\quad t^3 e^{0t}}, \\quad \\underbrace{e^{-3t}, \\quad t e^{-3t}},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which simplifies to  [mathjax]1, \\quad t, \\quad t^2, \\quad t^3, \\quad e^{-3t}, \\quad t e^{-3t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Thus the general solution is  [mathjax]c_1 + c_2 t + c_3 t^2 + c_4 t^3 + c_5 e^{-3t} + c_6 t e^{-3t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      As expected, the set of all solutions to this [mathjaxinline]6^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order linear ODE is [mathjaxinline]6[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional.      **Example 8.2** Find the simplest constant-coefficient homogeneous linear ODE having [mathjaxinline](5t+7)e^{-t} - 9 e^{2t}[/mathjaxinline] as one of its solutions.  **Solution:** The given function is a linear combination of  [mathjax]e^{-t}, \\quad t e^{-t}, \\quad e^{2t}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so the roots of the characteristic polynomial (with multiplicity) should include [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]. So the simplest characteristic polynomial is  [mathjax](r+1)(r+1)(r-2) = r^3 - 3 r - 2[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the corresponding ODE is  [mathjax]y^{(3)} - 3 \\dot{y} - 2y = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Solving a homogeneous linear ODE with constant coefficients", "filename": "08_higherorder-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Solving a homogeneous linear ODE with constant coefficients"}

{"pageid": 217, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@ourcourse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@ourcourse-tab5", "text": "There are 5 categories of graded problems in 18.031x: Lecture exercises, Recitation problems, Part A Homework, Part B Homework, and the Final Exam. Note that audit learners have access to all graded assessments except for the final exam. You must decide by mid July if you wish to upgrade to take the exam.    * **Lecture exercises** These are the problems that are interspersed through the lecture content. These problems count for 10% of your grade.   These problems will be used to motivate theory, practice concepts, and review material from previous lectures. You are graded on these problems. This is where you will do the majority of your learning. We encourage you to make mistakes and learn from them!    * **Recitation problems** There is a recitation worksheet associated to each lecture. Most problems have an answer box that allows you to check your answers with up to 10 attempts. The entries of these answer boxes counts towards 10% of your grade.  At MIT, recitations are group work sessions led by a teaching assistant. We are hoping to create a similar collaborative learning environment on the forum. Recitations involve the type of problem solving we will be asking of you in the homework. You are free to discuss the solutions to these problems on the forum before the due date! In fact, we will not reveal solutions to these problems, so to ensure that you have understood these problems, please take the opportunity to discuss and learn from each other.    * **Part A Homework** Each unit has 1 Part A Homework assignment, which gives you an opportunity to practice what you learned. These problems count for 10% of your total grade.   Wait until the end of the unit to attempt these problems. These problems help you identify the concepts that you have forgotten, and aid in long-term retention. These problems are mostly mechanical\u2013asking you to practice methods, and techniques learned in each unit. Each problem typically tests knowledge from only one section in a unit. (We won't necessarily tell you which one though!)    * **Part B Homework** Each unit has 1 Part B Homework assignment. The part B homework counts for 25% of your total grade.   The problems on this homework combine ideas from all of the sequences in the unit. These problems are mostly in the form of word problems which ask you to apply the methods learned to new scenarios.    * **Final Exam** The final exam is the culmination of your learning, and will account for 45% of your grade. These problems cover all of the material in this course. The exam is open book and timed. You have 48 hour to complete the exam, which will take about 3 hours to complete. Each problem has an infinite number of attempts, but you will not see the correctness of your submissions, only that your answer has been submitted. (The progress page display graph will be disabled during the exam.)   Grading", "filename": "ourcourse-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Grading"}

{"pageid": 218, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@33_numericalmethods/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@33_numericalmethods-tab4", "text": "To improve the approximation by the Euler method, we can use a smaller step size [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline], so that the slopes of the line segments are reassessed more frequently.    The cost of this, however, is that to increase [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] by a fixed amount, more steps will be needed.    Under reasonable hypotheses on [mathjaxinline]f\\,[/mathjaxinline] \u2013 the right hand side of the DE [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}=f(t,y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] \u2013 one can prove that in the limit as [mathjaxinline]h \\to 0[/mathjaxinline], this process converges and produces an exact solution curve. This is one way to prove that the solution to the initial value problem exists. In fact, this is the way Euler proved it.  ### Error of approximation:  Let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\bar{y}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] be the approximate solution given by Euler's method with step size [mathjaxinline]\\, h.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]    Let the **error of approximation** [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline] over the interval [mathjaxinline]\\, [a,b]\\,[/mathjaxinline] be  [mathjax]e\\, = \\max _{a\\leq t\\leq b} \\left|y(t)-\\bar{y}(t)\\right|.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      That is, [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline] is the maximum absolute difference between the actual solution [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\bar{y}(t).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The error [mathjaxinline]\\, e\\,[/mathjaxinline] is bounded above by a **linear** function of [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline]  [mathjax]e\\leq C h[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] is a constant depending on [mathjaxinline]\\, f.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Because [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] occurs as a first power above, not [mathjaxinline]h^{1/2}\\,[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]h^2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] Euler's method is called a **first order method** .    Step size", "filename": "33_numericalmethods-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Step size"}

{"pageid": 219, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab4", "text": "**Example 4.1** My minestrone soup is in an insulating thermos. Model its temperature as a function of time.  **Simplifying assumptions:**    * The insulating ability of the thermos does not change with time.     * The rate of cooling depends only on the **difference** between the soup temperature and the external temperature.     1. **Draw a picture:**  ![A schematic of a thermos containing soup with the variable x on the outside of the thermos, the variable y on the inside of the soup, and the variable k on the thermos itself. See text below for description of variables.](/static/images/thermos2.svg)    2.  **Identify variables and parameters (with units):**  [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] |  time ([mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{minutes}[/mathjaxinline])   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] |  external temperature ([mathjaxinline]{}^\\circ \\mathrm{C}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] |  soup temperature ([mathjaxinline]{}^\\circ \\mathrm{C}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] |  conduction of thermos (to be determined by equation)      Here [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is the independent variable, and [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] are functions of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. The conduction [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is a parameter of the system determined by the conductivity of the thermos.    3. **Identify input, response, and any initial conditions:**      * The **system** is the thermos full of soup.       * The **input** is [mathjaxinline]\\, x[/mathjaxinline], the temperature outside of the thermos.       * The **response** is [mathjaxinline]\\, y[/mathjaxinline], the temperature of the soup inside of the thermos.       * We are not given initial conditions in this problem.     4. **Write differential equation:**  [mathjax]\\dot{y} = k(x-y)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is **Newton's law of cooling** : the rate of cooling of an object is proportional to the difference between its temperature and the external temperature. It's very important to get the sign right. When the temperature outside the thermos is smaller than the temperature of the soup, the soup is cooling. We set up the equation this way so that the conductivity constant [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is positive.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle <[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.23)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x-y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle <[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.24)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle k[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle >[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.25)      The units of [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] must be [mathjaxinline]\\text{minutes}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline] for the units of [mathjaxinline]\\dot y[/mathjaxinline], which is Celsius per minute, to agree with the right hand side, which has units of [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] times units of Celsius.  Smaller [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] means better insulation, because smaller [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] leads to smaller rate of change of temperature. The case [mathjaxinline]k=0[/mathjaxinline] is perfect insulation; the temperature inside the thermos doesn't change at all.    5. **Put into standard linear form:** This ODE can be rearranged into standard form:   [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}} + k {\\color{blue}{y}} = k{\\color{orange}{x}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      It's a first-order inhomogeneous linear ODE!  **Note:** Notice that the factor of [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is essential in the differential equation for the units to work out. In standard linear form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle p(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle k[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.26)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle q(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle kx(t).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.27)      Note that the right hand side [mathjaxinline]q(t)= kx(t)[/mathjaxinline] is not the input. The input signal is [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{x(t)}}[/mathjaxinline]. The system response is [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{y(t)}} .[/mathjaxinline]  Newton's Law of cooling", "filename": "02_solvingafirstorderode-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Newton's Law of cooling"}

{"pageid": 220, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@04_complexexponential/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@04_complexexponential-tab6", "text": "**Example 6.1** How many roots does the polynomial [mathjaxinline]z^3 - 3 z^2 + 4[/mathjaxinline] have? It factors as [mathjaxinline](z-2)(z-2)(z+1)[/mathjaxinline], so it has only two distinct roots ([mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline]). But if we count [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] twice, then the number of roots **counted with multiplicity** is [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline], equal to the degree of the polynomial.  Some polynomials with real coefficients, like [mathjaxinline]z^2+9[/mathjaxinline], cannot be factored completely into degree [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] real polynomials, but do factor into degree [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] polynomials with complex coefficients: [mathjaxinline](z+3i)(z-3i)[/mathjaxinline].    * **Real polynomial** : polynomial with real coefficients.       * **Complex polynomial** : polynomial with complex coefficients.   In fact, **every** complex polynomial factors completely into degree [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] complex polynomials\u2014this is proved in advanced courses in complex analysis. This implies the following:  **Fundamental Theorem of algebra.** Every degree [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] complex polynomial [mathjaxinline]f(z)[/mathjaxinline] has exactly [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] complex roots, if counted with multiplicity.  Since real polynomials are special cases of complex polynomials, the fundamental theorem of algebra applies to them too. For real polynomials, any complex roots will occur with their complex conjugate pairs.  **Example 6.2** The degree [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] polynomial [mathjaxinline]z^3+z^2-z+15[/mathjaxinline] factors as [mathjaxinline](z+3)(z-1-2i)(z-1+2i)[/mathjaxinline], so it has three distinct roots: [mathjaxinline]-3[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]1+2i[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]1-2i[/mathjaxinline]. Of these roots, [mathjaxinline]-3[/mathjaxinline] is real, and [mathjaxinline]1+2i[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]1-2i[/mathjaxinline] form a complex conjugate pair.  **Example 6.3** Want a fourth root of [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline]? The fundamental theorem of algebra guarantees that [mathjaxinline]z^4-i=0[/mathjaxinline] has a complex solution (in fact, four of them). We'll learn how to find them next.  The fundamental theorem of algebra will be useful for constructing solutions to higher order linear ODEs with constant coefficients, and for discussing eigenvalues.  Complex roots of polynomials", "filename": "04_complexexponential-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Complex roots of polynomials"}

{"pageid": 222, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab10", "text": "We have already discussed the existence and uniqueness theorem for linear ODEs. Here is a version of the theorem that also works for first order nonlinear ODEs.    **Theorem 10.1** Existence and uniqueness theorem for a first order (linear or nonlinear) ODE Consider a first order ODE  [mathjax]y' = f(x,y).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      For any point [mathjaxinline]\\, (x_0, y_0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\, f(x,y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are continuous near [mathjaxinline]\\, (x_0,y_0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] then there is a unique solution to the first order DE through the point [mathjaxinline]\\, (x_0,y_0).[/mathjaxinline]    As a consequence of uniqueness, we have the following two geometric features:    1. Solutions curves cannot cross.     2. Solutions curves cannot become tangent to one another; that is, they cannot touch.   Use the Mathlet below to investigate the behavior of solution curves.    **Solution Target mathlet**  This is a game to find a solution curve through a specific point called the target. If you click on the target itself, the mathlet will draw the solution curve through it. When you click on another point, the mathlet will draw the solution curve through that point. You can try to aim for the solution through the target by clicking on other points than the target.    You may notice in some examples, the consequences of uniqueness seem to fail. Why is that the case?  Existence and uniqueness revisited", "filename": "28_nonlineardesgraphicalmethods2-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Existence and uniqueness revisited"}

{"pageid": 224, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@partB05/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@partB05-tab1", "text": "### What are g-forces?  Pilots, astronauts, and parachute jumpers are all concerned with the g-forces they experience. The g-force is a measurement of the acceleration that causes weight. The unit of measurement is [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]g, the ordinary force of gravity on Earth. When the parachute jumper is in free fall with closed parachute, experiencing only the effect of gravity with no normal force opposing the force due to gravity, the jumper feels weightless. Thus the jumper experiences [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]g's. The g-force experienced by a parachute jumper is the number of g's of acceleration relative to free fall.  g-forces", "filename": "partB05-tab1-text1.html", "title": "g-forces"}

{"pageid": 225, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab8", "text": "( **Small error in video above:** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} e^{i \\theta } = ie^{i\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] should be [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} e^{i t} = ie^{it}.[/mathjaxinline])  For students in science and engineering, you will often use exponential notation to abbreviate the polar form [mathjaxinline]\\cos (\\theta )+i\\sin (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] of a complex number of modulus [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]. The function [mathjaxinline]e^t[/mathjaxinline] is **defined** to be the solution of the initial value problem [mathjaxinline]\\dot x=x[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]x(0)=1[/mathjaxinline]. More generally, the chain rule implies the  [mathjax]\\textrm{For any constant }\\, a, \\, \\, e^{at} \\, \\textrm{ is the solution of } \\, \\, \\dot x=ax, \\quad x(0)=1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In addition to solving this initial value problem, for Euler's formula to be a good definition, we want [mathjaxinline]e^{it}[/mathjaxinline] to satisfy exponential properties we know from Calculus. That is to justify Euler's formula, we expect to have    1. **Exponential law:** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{it_1}e^{it_2} = e^{i(t_1+t_2)}[/mathjaxinline]     2. **Initial value problem:** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} e^{it} = ie^{it}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{i0} = 1[/mathjaxinline].     3. **Taylor's formula:** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{it} = \\sum _{n=0}^{\\infty } \\frac{(it)^n}{n!}.[/mathjaxinline]   The next videos justify the first two properties of the exponential [mathjaxinline]e^{it}[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 227, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@29_autonomousequations2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@29_autonomousequations2-tab13", "text": "Let us continue with our previous example of frogs being harvested from a pond. Their population is modeled by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3y-y^2-h\\qquad (h\\geq 0).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.61)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      You have just seen that the phase lines corresponding to different values of [mathjaxinline]h,\\,[/mathjaxinline] can be very different, and they tell us how the frog population evolves for different harvesting rate. Our goal now is to summarize all this information in a single diagram.    If we draw phase lines vertically at several [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline]-values in the [mathjaxinline](h,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane, we get a diagram on the left below. If we draw phase lines at all [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline]-values, we get a diagram on the right below.    ![The vertical axis is labeled y, and the horizontal axis is labeled h. As usual, the arrows tell us the stability of the critical points. In the diagram, we have also explicitly indicated the stability of the critical points by colors: **stable** , **unstable** , and **semistable**.  **Question 13.2** What is the shape of the curve on the bifurcation diagram for [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y} = 3y-y^2-h[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Answer:  The curve on this bifurcation diagram is a parabola. It is defined by [mathjaxinline]3y-y^2-h=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] or equivalently  [mathjax]\\, h=3y-y^2,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      a sideways parabola.    **Remark:** The shape of the curve on the bifurcation diagram depends on the differential equation, and so there are many possibilities. [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Question 13.3** How do we find the direction of the arrows (and stability of critical points) on the bifurcation diagram above without drawing many phase lines?  ###  Answer:  To get the arrow on the bifurcation diagram directly, check the sign of [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}=f(y)[/mathjaxinline] of one point in each region defined by the graph on the diagram.    In our example of [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}=3y-y^2-h,\\,[/mathjaxinline] check one point inside the parabola, such as [mathjaxinline](h,y)=(0,1)[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}=3y-y^2-h=2>0.\\,[/mathjaxinline] This gives an up arrow for the entire region inside the parabola. Similarly check one point outside the parabola, such as [mathjaxinline](h,y)=(1,0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}=3y-y^2-h= -1<0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This gives a down arrow for the entire region outside the parabola.  Therefore, the upper branch of the parabola consists of **stable** critical points, and the lower branch consists of **unstable** critical points when [mathjaxinline]9-4h>0\\,[/mathjaxinline]. When [mathjaxinline]9-4h=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the critical point is **semistable**. ( **Sustainable** means that the harvesting does not cause the population to crash to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], but that instead [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\lim _{t \\to +\\infty } y(t)[/mathjaxinline] is positive, so that the harvesting can continue indefinitely.)  **Solution:** The maximum sustainable harvesting rate is [mathjaxinline]h=9/4[/mathjaxinline], i.e., [mathjaxinline]2250 \\textrm{ frogs}/ \\textrm{month}[/mathjaxinline].     **Why?**      * For [mathjaxinline]h < 9/4[/mathjaxinline], the phase line is   ![The horizontal phase line is shown with positive infinity on the right and negative infinity on the left. So we have the initial condition is [mathjaxinline]\\, y(0)=3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] which is above the top (blue) branch of the parabola. Let the top branch of the parabola be called [mathjaxinline]\\, y_{\\text{top}}(h).\\,[/mathjaxinline] Then for each value of [mathjaxinline]h<9/4,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, y(t) \\to y_{\\text{top}}(h)\\,[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\,[/mathjaxinline] increases.    * For [mathjaxinline]h=9/4[/mathjaxinline], the phase line is   ![A horizontal phase line is shown with positive infinity on the right and negative infinity on the left. One critical point is indicated on the line at the value 3 over 2. The arrow to the left of 3 over 2 is pointing leftward. The arrow to the right of 3 over 2 is pointing rightward.](/static/images/u2s2_harvestproblemphaselinesswithnumbers.svg)  Since [mathjaxinline]\\, y(0)=3>3/2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]y(t) \\to 3/2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\,[/mathjaxinline] increases.    * For [mathjaxinline]h>9/4[/mathjaxinline], the phase line is   ![A horizontal phase line is shown with positive infinity on the right and negative infinity on the left. No critical points are indicated. A single arrow on the line is pointing leftward.](/static/images/u2s2_harvestproblemphaselinenocrit.svg)  In this case, no matter what the starting population is, [mathjaxinline]y(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] will reach [mathjaxinline]\\, 0\\,[/mathjaxinline] in finite time and a population crash is inevitable (overharvesting).  **Remark 13.5** Harvesting at exactly the maximum rate is a little dangerous, however, because if after a while [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] becomes very close to [mathjaxinline]3/2[/mathjaxinline], and a little kid comes along and takes a few more frogs out of the pond so that the population is just below [mathjaxinline]3/2[/mathjaxinline], the whole frog population will crash! This real number is the square of the distance to the origin:  [mathjax]z \\, \\overline{z} =a^2+b^2 = |z|^2.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      For a complex number [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline], inequalities like [mathjaxinline]z<3[/mathjaxinline] do not make sense, but inequalities like [mathjaxinline]|z|<3[/mathjaxinline] do, because [mathjaxinline]|z|[/mathjaxinline] is a real number. On the previous page, we defined the function [mathjaxinline]e^{\\alpha t}[/mathjaxinline] to be the solution to this equation guaranteed by the existence and uniqueness theorem, and then used the equation to establish various properties of the exponential function. In this note, we'll just assume that the solution given by the exponential function exists and prove the uniqueness part of the theorem. The most common proof of existence is not too hard but relies on some advanced Calculus \u2013 in particular convergence theorems.  We begin by restating with the most basic version of the existence and uniqueness theorem for first order equations with constant (complex) coefficients.  **Theorem 3.1** Let [mathjaxinline]\\alpha \\in \\mathbb {C}[/mathjaxinline]. Then for a given [mathjaxinline]x_0 \\in \\mathbb {C}[/mathjaxinline], the initial value problem  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\alpha x(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.50)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.51)      has a unique solution given by  [mathjax]x(t) = e^{\\alpha t} x_0[/mathjax]| (3.52)   ---|---       **Proof of uniqueness** Suppose that [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] is any other solution to [mathjaxinline]y'(t) = \\alpha y(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Define  [mathjax]z(t) = e^{-\\alpha t} y(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Then,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z'(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle - \\alpha e^{-\\alpha t} y(t) + e^{-\\alpha t} y'(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.53)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle - \\alpha e^{-\\alpha t} y(t) + e^{-\\alpha t} \\alpha y(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.54)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.55)      where above in the second line we used the equation [mathjaxinline]y'(t) = \\alpha y(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]z'(t) = 0[/mathjaxinline] we know [mathjaxinline]z(t)[/mathjaxinline] is equal to a constant. Using the initial conditions [mathjaxinline]y(0) = x_0[/mathjaxinline], we see that [mathjaxinline]z(0) = x_0[/mathjaxinline], and thus [mathjaxinline]z(t) = x_0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t \\in \\mathbb {R}[/mathjaxinline]. Hence,  [mathjax]x_0 = e^{-\\alpha t} y(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      or in other words, [mathjaxinline]y(t) = e^{\\alpha t}x_0[/mathjaxinline], which proves uniqueness. [mathjaxinline]\\square[/mathjaxinline]  The proof above easily generalizes to  **Theorem 3.2** [Uniqueness for an inhomogeneous equation] Let [mathjaxinline]\\alpha \\in \\mathbb {C}[/mathjaxinline] and let [mathjaxinline]q(t)[/mathjaxinline] be a continuous function on an open time interval [mathjaxinline]J \\subset \\mathbb {R}[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]0 \\in J[/mathjaxinline]. The existence part of the theorem can be proved using, say, the variation of parameters formula. We will prove uniqueness here.  **Proof of uniqueness** Suppose there are two solutions [mathjaxinline]x_1(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x_2(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjaxinline]w(t):= x_1(t) - x_2(t)[/mathjaxinline] solves the homogeneous equation,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle w'(t) - \\alpha w(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.58)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle w(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.59)      Then, we just apply the previous argument to conclude that [mathjaxinline]w(t) = 0[/mathjaxinline] is the unique solution to the above, and thus [mathjaxinline]x_1(t) = x_2(t)[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t \\in J[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 231, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@01_odeintro/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@01_odeintro-tab3", "text": "**Example 3.1** Can you guess my secret function [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline]?  **Clue:** It satisfies the differential equation  [mathjax]\\dot{y} = 3y,[/mathjax]| (2.1)   ---|---      which could model population growth in some biological system, like the growth of yeast cells. Note that [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{y}}}[/mathjaxinline] is common notation for the derivative with respect to time; [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y'[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] all mean the same thing here.  Maybe you guessed [mathjaxinline]y = e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline]. This is **a solution** to the differential equation above, because substituting it into the DE gives [mathjaxinline]3e^{3t}=3e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline]. But it's not the function I was thinking of! Some other solutions are [mathjaxinline]y=7e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y=-5e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline], etc. From calculus we know that the family of functions  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y=ce^{3t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      is the **general solution** .  Saying this means that    * for each number [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline], the function [mathjaxinline]y=ce^{3t}[/mathjaxinline] is a solution, and     * there are no other solutions besides these.   So there is a [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]-parameter family of solutions to this DE. The constant [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is a **parameter** .  **You still haven't guessed my secret function.**   **Clue 2:** My function satisfies the **initial condition** [mathjaxinline]y(0)=5[/mathjaxinline].  ###  See secret function  There is a number [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]y(t)=ce^{3t}[/mathjaxinline] holds for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]; we need to find [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline]. Plugging in [mathjaxinline]t=0[/mathjaxinline] shows that [mathjax]5 = c e^0, \\, \\, \\text{ so }\\, \\, c=5.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   Thus, among the infinitely many solutions to the DE, **the solution** satisfying the initial condition [mathjaxinline]y(0)=5[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjax]y(t)=5e^{3t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Definition 3.2** An **initial value problem** is a differential equation together with initial conditions.  **Important :** Checking a solution to a DE is usually easier than finding the solution in the first place, so it is often worth doing. Just plug in the function to both sides, and also check that it satisfies the initial condition.  In the solution to the DE, only one initial condition was needed, since only one parameter [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] needed to be recovered.  A secret function", "filename": "01_odeintro-tab3-text1.html", "title": "A secret function"}

{"pageid": 233, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@08_higherorder/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@08_higherorder-tab6", "text": "When discussing second order ODEs, we called a set of 2 linearly independent homogeneous solutions a _basis_ for all homogeneous solutions. Below is the general definition of a basis.  **Definition 6.1** A **basis** of a vector space [mathjaxinline]S[/mathjaxinline] is a list of vectors [mathjaxinline]v_1,v_2,\\ldots ,\\, v_n\\,[/mathjaxinline] such that    1. [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Span}(v_1,\\, v_2,\\, \\ldots ,\\, v_n) = S[/mathjaxinline], and     2. The vectors [mathjaxinline]\\, v_1,\\, v_2,\\, \\ldots ,\\, v_n[/mathjaxinline] are linearly **independent.**  **Example 6.2** The vectors [mathjaxinline]\\, (1,0,0),\\, (0,1,0),\\, (0,0,1)\\,[/mathjaxinline] form a basis for [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3\\,[/mathjaxinline] (a real vector space). This is because any vector [mathjaxinline]\\, (x,y,z)\\,[/mathjaxinline] can be written as (real) linear combinations of these 3 basis vectors, and these 3 basis vectors are linearly independent: [mathjaxinline]c_1(1,0,0)+c_2(0,1,0)+c_3(0,0,1) =(0,0,0)\\,[/mathjaxinline] **only** if [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1, \\, c_2,\\, c_3[/mathjaxinline] **all** equal zero.  The vector spaces that are relevant to differential equations are vector spaces of functions. A basis of a vector space of functions is given as a list of functions [mathjaxinline]\\, f_1,\\, f_2,\\ldots ,\\, f_n.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Think of the functions in the basis as \u201cbasic building blocks\". Condition 1 says that every function in [mathjaxinline]S[/mathjaxinline] can be built from [mathjaxinline]f_1,f_2,\\ldots[/mathjaxinline]. Condition 2 says that there is no redundancy in the list (no building block could have been built from the others).     **Example 6.3** The functions [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{2t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{-3t}[/mathjaxinline] form a basis for the space of solutions to the homogeneous equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y} + \\dot{y} - 6y = 0[/mathjaxinline].  **Key point:** The vector space of solutions to a homogeneous ODE consists of infinitely many functions. To describe it compactly, we give a **basis** of the vector space. In this case, the basis has only 2 functions.    The plural of basis is **bases,** pronounced BAY-sees.     **Fact:** A vector space has many different bases.     **Example 6.4** The vectors [mathjaxinline]\\, (1,0), \\, (0,1)[/mathjaxinline] is a basis for [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2\\,[/mathjaxinline] (a real vector space), but so is any other pair of linearly independent vectors, such as [mathjaxinline]\\, (1,0),\\, (1,1)[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 6.5** The space of solutions to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\ddot{y} + y = 0\\,[/mathjaxinline] is spanned both by the basis [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{it},\\, e^{-it},\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the basis [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos (t),\\, \\sin (t)[/mathjaxinline]. (Here, we allow complex linear combinations of the basis functions.)  Basis", "filename": "08_higherorder-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Basis"}

{"pageid": 234, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@ourcourse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@ourcourse-tab2", "text": "Scientists and engineers understand the world through differential equations. How do you design    * a boat that doesn't tip over as it bobs in the water,     * the suspension system of a car for a smooth ride,     * circuits that tune to the correct frequencies in a cell phone?   How do you model    * the growth of antibiotic resistant bacteria,     * gene expression,     * online purchasing trends?   The answer: differential equations. {"pageid": 235, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@01_odeintro/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@01_odeintro-tab5", "text": "There are two kinds:    * An **ordinary differential equation (ODE)** involves derivatives of a function of **only one** variable.     * A **partial differential equation (PDE)** involves **partial derivatives** of a **multivariable** function.   Here we will study ordinary differential equations. In _Fourier Series and PDEs_ , we will study partial differential equations. When we consider ODEs, we will often regard the independent variable to be time.  Notation for higher derivatives of a function [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline]:  first derivative: |  [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]y^{\\prime }[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---   second derivative: |  [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y}[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]y^{\\prime \\prime }[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^2 y}{dt^2}[/mathjaxinline]   third derivative: |  [mathjaxinline]y^{(3)}[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^3 y}{dt^3}[/mathjaxinline]   |  [mathjaxinline]\\vdots[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] derivative: | [mathjaxinline]y^{(n)}[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d^n y}{dt^n}[/mathjaxinline]      **Warning:** The dot notation [mathjaxinline]\\dot y[/mathjaxinline] should only be used to refer to a **time** derivative. If for example [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] is a function of a spacial variable [mathjaxinline]y= y(x)[/mathjaxinline], we will only use the notation [mathjaxinline]y'[/mathjaxinline] to denote the derivative with respect to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline].  If [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] has units [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{m}[/mathjaxinline] (meters) and [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] has units [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{s}[/mathjaxinline] (seconds), then [mathjaxinline]\\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] has the same units as [mathjaxinline]\\frac{y}{t}[/mathjaxinline] would, namely [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{m}/\\mathrm{s}[/mathjaxinline] (meters per second). Similarly, [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y}[/mathjaxinline] would have units [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{m}/\\mathrm{s}^2[/mathjaxinline].  **Definition 5.1** The **order** of a DE is the highest [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] such that the [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] derivative of the function appears.  **Example 5.2** Is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle 9375 \\cos (t^5) \\, \\ddot{y}^4 + 982 (y + t^3)^7 \\, \\dot{y} - 387 y^{(3)} y^{(4)} + 2t y^{(5)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {}=- 30987\\sqrt{y}+ 4087 \\sin (t/y) + 7092 \\ln (1- t^7) + 3786 e^{y^8 - t^3} + 18.031 \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  |      an ODE or a PDE?        ###  Answer  The equation is an **ODE** because it only involves derivatives with respect to one variable, the variable [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{t}}[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Classification of differential equations", "filename": "01_odeintro-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Classification of differential equations"}

{"pageid": 236, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab7", "text": "In polar form, it is easy to see that the graph of the sinusoidal function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)=A \\cos (\\omega t-\\phi )\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a rescaled and shifted version of the cosine graph, as shown below:  ![ ](/static/images/sinusoids.svg)   Graph of [mathjaxinline]f(t)=A \\cos (\\omega t-\\phi )[/mathjaxinline]        This graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] can be described geometrically in terms of    * [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{A}} ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] its **amplitude** , how high the graph rises above the [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]-axis at its maximum;       * [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{P}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] (in **seconds** or **seconds per cycle** ), its **period** , the time for one complete oscillation, or equivalently the width between successive maxima;    * [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{t_0}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] (in **seconds** ), its **time lag** (relative to the cosine curve), a [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]-value at which a maximum is attained. The time lag is well defined up to the addition of integer multiples of a period.   **Question 7.1** How are the parameters describing the graph, [mathjaxinline]\\, P\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, t_0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] related to the parameters, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\phi ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the function [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)[/mathjaxinline] ?  **Answer:**      * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle P = \\frac{2 \\pi }{\\omega },\\,[/mathjaxinline] since adding [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\frac{2\\pi }{\\omega }\\,[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\,[/mathjaxinline] increases the angle [mathjaxinline]\\omega t - \\phi[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]2\\pi[/mathjaxinline].     * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle t_0= \\frac{\\phi }{\\omega },\\,[/mathjaxinline] since [mathjaxinline]\\, t_0\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]-value for which the angle [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega t - \\phi =0,\\,[/mathjaxinline].   There is also **frequency** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\nu \\colon =\\frac{1}{P}\\,[/mathjaxinline] (in **Hertz** = **cycles per second** ), the number of complete oscillations per second. To convert from frequency [mathjaxinline]\\nu[/mathjaxinline] to angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline], multiply by [mathjaxinline]\\frac{2\\pi \\textrm{ radians}}{1 \\textrm{ cycle}}[/mathjaxinline]; thus [mathjaxinline]\\omega = 2\\pi \\nu = 2\\pi /P[/mathjaxinline], which is consistent with the formula [mathjaxinline]P = 2\\pi /\\omega[/mathjaxinline] above.  **Steps to graph [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)=A \\cos (\\omega t - \\phi )[/mathjaxinline]:**    Start with the curve [mathjaxinline]y(\\theta )=\\cos \\theta .\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Then \u201cwork from the outside in.\"    1. Amplify (stretch vertically) by a factor of [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{A}} ,[/mathjaxinline] the **amplitude** . You now have the graph of [mathjaxinline]y(\\theta )=A\\cos (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline].     2. Shift the graph by [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\phi }}[/mathjaxinline] (in **radians** ) to the right. You now have the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, y(\\theta )=A\\cos (\\theta -\\phi ).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]     The angle [mathjaxinline]\\, \\phi \\,[/mathjaxinline] is called the **phase lag** or **phase shift** (relative to the cosine curve). The first maximum of the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, A\\cos (\\theta -\\phi )\\,[/mathjaxinline] is at [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta =\\phi ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] shifted from [mathjaxinline]\\theta =0\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, A\\cos (\\theta ).\\,[/mathjaxinline]      3. Compress the result horizontally by **dividing** by the scale factor [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\omega }} \\,[/mathjaxinline] (in **radians/second** ), the **angular frequency** . The result is the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)=A\\cos (\\omega t-\\phi ).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]    With this horizontal rescaling, the horizonal axis changes from the [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline]-axis (in radians) to the [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]-axis (in seconds). The first maximum of the rescaled graph is at [mathjaxinline]t_0=\\phi /\\omega[/mathjaxinline] instead of at [mathjaxinline]\\theta =\\phi ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and one complete oscillation takes [mathjaxinline]2\\pi /\\omega \\,[/mathjaxinline] instead of [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi[/mathjaxinline].  **Remark:** The phase lag [mathjaxinline]\\phi \\,[/mathjaxinline] tells us by what **fraction of a cycle** the graph of [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] is shifted from a cosine graph of the same frequency. For example, the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)=A\\cos (\\omega t-\\pi /2)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is shifted by [mathjaxinline]\\, 1/4\\,[/mathjaxinline] of a cycle to the right from the graph of [mathjaxinline]A\\cos (\\omega t).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] On the other hand, the time lag [mathjaxinline]\\, t_0\\,[/mathjaxinline] tells us by **how much time** the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\, f(t)=A\\cos (\\omega t-\\pi /2)\\, =\\, A\\cos \\left(\\omega (t-t_0)\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is shifted to the right from the graph of [mathjaxinline]A\\cos (\\omega t).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Also note that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\frac{\\phi }{2\\pi }= \\frac{t_0}{P}.[/mathjaxinline]    Link to glossary of terms can be found [here](https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/18-03sc-differential-equations- fall-2011/6aa608816eca943e2bd9cff517d88362_MIT18_03SCF11_s7_1text.pdf).  Graphing sinusoidal functions", "filename": "06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Graphing sinusoidal functions"}

{"pageid": 237, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab7", "text": "**Warm-up problem:** If [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] is a number, what is [mathjaxinline](2D^2+3D+5) e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline]?  **Solution:** First, [mathjaxinline]D e^{rt} = r e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]D^2 e^{rt} = r^2 e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline] (keep applying the chain rule). Thus  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (2D^2+3D+5) e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 2 r^2 e^{rt} + 3 r e^{rt} + 5 e^{rt}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = (2r^2+3r+5) e^{rt}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The operator is [mathjaxinline]P(D) = 2D^2+3D+5[/mathjaxinline]. Notice that [mathjaxinline]P(r) = 2r^2+3r+5[/mathjaxinline] is the characteristic polynomial. The same calculation, but with an arbitrary polynomial, proves the following general rule.  **Theorem 7.1** For any polynomial [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] and any number [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{P(D) e^{rt} = P(r) e^{rt}.}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Shortcut for applying an operator to an exponential function.", "filename": "09_exponentialresponse-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Shortcut for applying an operator to an exponential function."}

{"pageid": 238, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_higherorderlinearodes/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_higherorderlinearodes-tab1", "text": "**Objectives**    * Model **spring-mass-dashpot** systems using 2nd order homogeneous linear ODEs.     * Apply the **superposition principle** to find solutions to the **unforced** spring-mass-dashpot using 2nd order **homogeneous** linear ODEs.     * Use the **characteristic polynomial** to find the **exponential solutions** for 2nd order homogeneous linear ODEs with **constant coefficients** .     * Find the **general solution** and the **general real solution** to 2nd order linear homogeneous constant coefficient DEs with **distinct characteristic roots** .   Second order homogeneous linear ODEs", "filename": "06_higherorderlinearodes-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Second order homogeneous linear ODEs"}

{"pageid": 239, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@08_higherorder/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@08_higherorder-tab4", "text": "The span of a set of functions is always a _vector space_.     **What is a vector space?**     **Example 4.1** The 2-dimensional [mathjaxinline]\\, (x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane is a vector space. The vectors are the ordered pairs [mathjaxinline]\\, (x, y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] that add component-wise: [mathjaxinline]\\, (x_1, y_1)+(x_2, y_2) = ( x_1+x_2, y_1 + y_2).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] There is a zero element [mathjaxinline](0,0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and you can scale vectors by real numbers: [mathjaxinline]\\, a(x,y)= (ax,ay).[/mathjaxinline]  **Definition 4.2** Suppose that [mathjaxinline]\\, S\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a set of elements called **vectors** equipped with two laws: a law for adding vectors in [mathjaxinline]\\, S,\\,[/mathjaxinline] called **vector addition** , and a law for multiplying vectors in [mathjaxinline]\\, S\\,[/mathjaxinline] by real numbers, called **scalar multiplication.** Then [mathjaxinline]\\, S\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a **real vector space** if **all** of the following are true:    1. There is a **zero vector** in [mathjaxinline]\\, S\\,[/mathjaxinline]: a vector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{0}\\,[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\, S\\,[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v+\\mathbf{0}=\\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] for every vector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\, S .[/mathjaxinline]     2. ( _Closed under scalar multiplication._ ) Multiplying any one vector in [mathjaxinline]\\, S\\,[/mathjaxinline] by a real number gives another vector in [mathjaxinline]\\, S:\\,[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] is in [mathjaxinline]\\, S\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, a \\,[/mathjaxinline] is a real number, then [mathjaxinline]\\, a\\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] is in [mathjaxinline]\\, S \\,[/mathjaxinline] too.     3. ( _Closed under vector addition._ ) Adding any two vectors in [mathjaxinline]\\, S\\,[/mathjaxinline] gives another vector in [mathjaxinline]\\, S:\\,[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{w}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are in [mathjaxinline]\\, S,\\,[/mathjaxinline] then the vector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v+\\mathbf{w}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is in [mathjaxinline]S.[/mathjaxinline]   **Remark :** This definition can also be used to define a **complex vector space** ; it's the same thing as a real vector space, but scalar multiplication is defined for complex numbers instead of just real numbers.  **Example 4.3** The set of all real-valued functions forms a real vector space. The constant [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-function is the zero vector. Vector addition is addition of functions point-wise [mathjaxinline]\\, (f+g)(x) = f(x) + g(x).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Scalar multiplication is multiplying a function by a real number at each point, e.g. [mathjaxinline]-2f (x)=(-2) (f(x))[/mathjaxinline].  **Non-example:**   The set of all nonnegative functions is not a real vector space because [mathjaxinline]\\, x^2 \\,[/mathjaxinline] is in this set, but [mathjaxinline]\\left(-1\\right)\\cdot x^2=-x^2[/mathjaxinline] is not.     **Non-example:**   The set containing only the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]- and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axes is not a vector space because if we add two nonzero elements we don't always stay in the space, e.g. [mathjaxinline]\\, (1,0)+(0,1)\\, =\\, (1,1)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is not on either axes.    Last, but not least, recall:  **Theorem 4.4** **The set of all homogeneous solutions to a linear ODE is a vector space.**  Vector space", "filename": "08_higherorder-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Vector space"}

{"pageid": 240, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@07_dampedoscillators/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@07_dampedoscillators-tab4", "text": "**Case 1:** [mathjaxinline]b^2 < 4mk\\,[/mathjaxinline] **underdamped**    There are two complex roots, and we will give names to the real and imaginary parts. Since the real part is always negative, we call it [mathjaxinline]-p,\\,[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, p=\\frac{b}{2m}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The imaginary part is either positive or negative of the **damped frequency** [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega _d,\\,[/mathjaxinline] given by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{\\omega _d}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{\\colon =}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{\\frac{\\sqrt{4mk-b^2}}{2m} }}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.68)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{ \\sqrt{\\omega _n^2-p^2} }} \\ ,\\qquad \\text{where } \\, {\\color{blue}{\\omega _n=\\sqrt{\\frac{k}{m}} }} \\, \\, \\text{is the natural frequency}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.69)      Note that both [mathjaxinline]\\, p\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega _d\\,[/mathjaxinline] are positive.         **Summary of results:**    Roots: |  [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\displaystyle - p\\pm i\\omega _d[/mathjaxinline]   ---|---   Basis of solution space: |  [mathjaxinline]e^{(-p + i\\omega _d)t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\; e^{(-p - i\\omega _d)t}[/mathjaxinline]   Real-valued basis: |  [mathjaxinline]e^{-p t} \\cos (\\omega _d t)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\; e^{-p t} \\sin (\\omega _d t)[/mathjaxinline].   General real solution: |  [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{e^{-p t} (a \\cos (\\omega _d t) + b \\sin (\\omega _d t))}}[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]a,b[/mathjaxinline] are real constants.   |  [mathjaxinline]= {\\color{blue}{A e^{-pt}\\cos (\\omega _d t - \\phi ) }}[/mathjaxinline] for some [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\phi[/mathjaxinline].      This is a sinusoid multiplied by a decaying exponential. Each nonzero solution tends to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], but changes sign infinitely many times along the way. The system is called **underdamped** , because there was not enough damping to eliminate the oscillation completely.    The damping not only causes the solution to decay exponentially, but also **changes the frequency of the sinusoid**. The new angular frequency, [mathjaxinline]\\omega _d[/mathjaxinline], is called **damped (angular) frequency** (or sometimes _pseudo (angular) frequency_ as in the video).    The damped frequency [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega _d\\,[/mathjaxinline] is less than the natural (undamped) frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline], as evident from the formula [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega _d=\\sqrt{\\omega _n^2-p^2}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] When [mathjaxinline]\\, b=0,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega _d\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the same as [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega _n[/mathjaxinline].    The damped solutions are not actually periodic: they don't repeat exactly, because of the decay. Therefore,[mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi /\\omega _d[/mathjaxinline] is called the **pseudo-period** .    Case 1: underdamped", "filename": "07_dampedoscillators-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Case 1: underdamped"}

{"pageid": 242, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab9", "text": "Here we explain why it is really enough to understand the system response to the input signal [mathjaxinline]\\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline].  We have been studying LTI, or Linear Time-Invariant systems. \u201cTime-invariant\" means that the system parameters are not changing, or are changing very slowly relative to the time scale we are interested in. The implication for our input/output analysis is this: If [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is a system response to the input signal [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline], then if we delay the input signal by [mathjaxinline]t_0[/mathjaxinline] seconds, the output signal is the same as before but delayed by [mathjaxinline]t_0[/mathjaxinline] seconds as well: [mathjaxinline]x(t-t_0)[/mathjaxinline] is a system response to the input [mathjaxinline]f(t-t_0)[/mathjaxinline]. The system parameters are the coefficients in the differential equation; so \u201ctime-invariant\" is the same as \u201cconstant coefficient.\"  Because our systems are also **linear** , if [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is a system response to [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]Ax(t)[/mathjaxinline] is a system response to [mathjaxinline]Af(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Thus when studying a linear time-invariant system with sinusoidal input [mathjaxinline]A\\cos (\\omega t-\\phi )[/mathjaxinline], it is enough to consider the input [mathjaxinline]\\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline] since linearity and time-invariance give the response to all other sinusoidal inputs for free.  **Example 9.1** If  [mathjax]P(D) x = \\cos \\omega t[/mathjax]|   ---|---      has [mathjaxinline]x_p = A \\cos (\\omega t - \\phi )[/mathjaxinline] as a particular solution, then shifting time by [mathjaxinline]a=\\alpha /\\omega[/mathjaxinline] shows that  [mathjax]P(D) x = \\cos (\\omega t - \\alpha )[/mathjax]|   ---|---      has [mathjaxinline]x_p = A \\cos (\\omega t - \\alpha - \\phi )[/mathjaxinline] as a particular solution.  The gain and phase lag represent a relationship between the input and the output (both sinusoidal). The gain is the ratio of the output amplitude to the input amplitude, and the phase lag is the number of radians the output signal falls behind the input signal. Because our system is time-invariant, those relationships between input and response are **unchanged** by replacing the input signal [mathjaxinline]\\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\cos (\\omega t- \\alpha )[/mathjaxinline]: the gain is [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and the phase lag is [mathjaxinline]\\phi[/mathjaxinline].  The meaning of LTI", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab9-text1.html", "title": "The meaning of LTI"}

{"pageid": 244, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@07_dampedoscillators/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@07_dampedoscillators-tab2", "text": "Let us review what we have learned about the spring-mass-dashpot system with no external force. We will first review the cases where oscillations are present.    If there is **no damping** , the DE that models the position of the mass is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m \\ddot{x} + k x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0\\qquad (m,k>0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.64)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{standard linear form:}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{x} +\\frac{k}{m} x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.65)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{or}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{x} +\\omega _n^2 x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 \\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\omega _n\\colon =\\sqrt{\\frac{k}{m}}[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.66)       **Summary of results:**    Characteristic polynomial: |  [mathjaxinline]\\, P(r) = mr^2+k\\,[/mathjaxinline] (defined up to a constant multiple)   ---|---   Roots: |  [mathjaxinline]\\pm i \\omega _n,\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\omega _n = \\sqrt{\\frac{k}{m}} }}[/mathjaxinline].   Basis of solution space: |  [mathjaxinline]e^{i \\omega _n t}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]e^{-i\\omega _n t}[/mathjaxinline].   Real-valued basis: |  [mathjaxinline]\\cos \\omega _n t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\omega _n t[/mathjaxinline].   General real solution: |  [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\, {\\color{blue}{ a \\cos \\omega _n t + b \\sin \\omega _n t}}[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]a,b[/mathjaxinline] are real constants   |  [mathjaxinline]={\\color{blue}{A \\cos (\\omega _n t - \\phi )}}[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]A>0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\phi[/mathjaxinline] are real constants.      In other words, the real-valued solutions are all the sinusoidal functions of angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline].    This system, or any other system governed by the same DE, is also called a **simple harmonic oscillator** . The angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega _n[/mathjaxinline] is also called the **natural frequency** (or **resonant frequency** ) of the oscillator.
