{"pageid": 248, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@09_exponentialresponse/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@09_exponentialresponse-tab8", "text": "**Question:** For any polynomial [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] and number [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline], what is a particular solution to  [mathjax]P(D)y = e^{rt}?[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Answer (superposition):** We have  [mathjax]P(D) {\\color{blue}{e^{rt}}} = {\\color{orange}{P(r) e^{rt}}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is off by a factor of [mathjaxinline]P(r)[/mathjaxinline]. So multiply through by [mathjaxinline]1/P(r)[/mathjaxinline] and we can use linearity to get  [mathjax]P(D)\\left(\\frac{1}{P(r)}e^{rt} \\right) = e^{rt}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Conclusion:** This is called the **Exponential Response Formula (ERF)** .  In words, for any polynomial [mathjaxinline]P[/mathjaxinline] and any number [mathjaxinline]r[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]P(r) \\ne 0[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\frac{1}{P(r)} e^{rt}}} \\quad \\text{ is a particular solution to }\\quad P(D) y = {\\color{blue}{e^{rt}}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Remember, this is just one particular solution. To get the general solution, we need to add the solution to the associated homogeneous equation.  **Example 8.1** Find the general solution to [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{y} + 7\\dot{y} + 12 y = {\\color{blue}{-5e^{2t}}}[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:**  Characteristic polynomial: |  [mathjaxinline]P(r) = r^2+7r+12 = (r+3)(r+4)[/mathjaxinline].   ---|---   Roots: |  [mathjaxinline]-3[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]-4[/mathjaxinline].   General solution to **homogeneous** equation: | [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{y_h}} = c_1 e^{-3t} + c_2 e^{-4t}[/mathjaxinline].      ERF says:  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\frac{1}{P(2)} e^{2t}}} \\quad \\text{is a particular solution to }\\quad P(D) y = {\\color{blue}{e^{2t}}} ;[/mathjax]|   ---|---      i.e.,  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\frac{1}{30} e^{2t}}} \\quad \\text{ is a particular solution to }\\quad \\ddot{y} + 7 \\dot{y} + 12 y = {\\color{blue}{e^{2t}}} ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so  [mathjax]\\underset {{\\color{blue}{ \\text{call this } y_p}} }{-\\frac{1}{6} e^{2t}} \\quad \\textrm{ is a particular solution to }\\quad \\ddot{y} + 7 \\dot{y} + 12 y = {\\color{blue}{-5e^{2t}}} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      General solution to inhomogeneous equation:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = {\\color{blue}{y_p}} + {\\color{orange}{y_h}}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -\\frac{1}{6} e^{2t} + c_1 e^{-3t} + c_2 e^{-4t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Exponential response", "filename": "09_exponentialresponse-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Exponential response"}

{"pageid": 249, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@29_autonomousequations2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@29_autonomousequations2-tab9", "text": "**Note on video:** In the first graph on top at 2:15, David draws a line of positive slope, but the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-intercept should be on the left side, not the right side, of the vertical axis (as he discovered later that the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-intercept is [mathjaxinline]-1/a[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]a>0[/mathjaxinline]). However, this does not affect the character of the phase line.    Using the analysis from the video, we can predict the effect of immigration on the population of a country.     **Example 9.1** The population of a wealthy and sparsely populated country is currently at [mathjaxinline]7[/mathjaxinline] million and is declining from low birth rate. The natural growth rate is [mathjaxinline]a=-0.01[/mathjaxinline] (in [mathjaxinline]\\text{year}^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]). What will be the effect on the population If the country admits [mathjaxinline]10,000[/mathjaxinline] immigrants per year?    **Solution:**   Let [mathjaxinline]\\, x(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] (in ten thousands) be the population at time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] (in years). Since the country is sparsely populated and wealthy, we can assume resources are unlimited. In other words, the quadratic term in the logistic equation is negligible. Therefore, without immigration, the population can be modeled by  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ax\\, =\\, -\\frac{1}{100}x.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.49)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      With immigration, the rate of change of population [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] must include an additional term:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac{1}{100}x+1,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.50)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, 1\\,[/mathjaxinline] (in ten thousand immigrants per year) is the immigration rate. This DE is the same as in the video with [mathjaxinline]a=-1/100.[/mathjaxinline] Therefore, as in the video, the phase line is  ![A horizontal phase line is shown with positive infinity on the right and negative infinity on the left. The value negative 1 over a is indicated. The arrow to the left of negative 1 over a points rightward. The arrow to the right of negative 1 over a points leftward.](/static/images/u2s2_populationphaseline.svg)    This means that no matter what the initial population is, the population will approach the equilibrium of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle -\\frac{1}{a}=100[/mathjaxinline] (in ten thousands), that is, 1 million people. The current population of the country is 7 million; so the population will be decreasing while tending to 1 million.    Note", "filename": "29_autonomousequations2-tab9-text2.html", "title": "Note"}

{"pageid": 250, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab11", "text": "**Remarks on video:** For higher order systems, we haven't presented the general integral formula for solving differential equations with arbitrary input. So here we only discuss transients, steady state, and stability in the case of complex exponential input for higher order systems.  A certain spring/mass/dashpot system is modeled by the LTI ODE  [mathjax]\\ddot x + 7\\dot x+12 x = 12f(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\ f(t)=\\cos (2t)[/mathjaxinline] is the input signal.  **Question:** Suppose that the solution to this equation with initial conditions [mathjaxinline](x(0), \\dot x(0)) = (2,3)[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline]. What can you say about the solution [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] to the same ODE with initial condition [mathjaxinline](y(0), \\dot y(0)) = (3,-8)[/mathjaxinline]?    * It isn't related to [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] in any way.     * It oscillates.     * Its graph becomes asymptotic to that of [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t \\rightarrow \\infty[/mathjaxinline].     * Its graph diverges from that of [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t\\rightarrow \\infty[/mathjaxinline].   **Solution:**  The characteristic roots are [mathjaxinline]-3[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-4[/mathjaxinline]. Thus the general homogeneous solution has the form  [mathjax]x_h = c_1 e^{-3t} + c_2 e^{-4t},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline] are constants determined by initial conditions. All of these homogeneous solutions decay (rapidly!) to zero as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] grows to [mathjaxinline]\\infty[/mathjaxinline]. So any solution with different initial conditions will eventually become asymptotic to that of [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Why is this?  The general solution to the original inhomogeneous ODE is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = x_p + x_h[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\underbrace{\\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( \\frac{12}{8+14i} e^{2it} \\right)}_{{\\color{blue}{\\text{steady state solution}}} } + \\underbrace{c_1 e^{-3t} + c_2 e^{-4t}}_{{\\color{orange}{\\text{transient}}} }.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      In general, a damped oscillator forced with a sinusoidal input produces a sinusoidal output signal. That output is a particular solution called a **steady-state solution** , because this is what the solution looks like as [mathjaxinline]t \\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline]. Every other solution is the steady-state solution plus a **transient** , where the transient is a function that decays to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t \\to +\\infty[/mathjaxinline].  Changing the initial conditions changes only the constants [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline] in the homogeneous solution above, so the steady-state solution is the same. A system like this, in which changes in the initial conditions have vanishing effect on the long-term behavior of the solution, is called **stable** .  Steady state, transient solutions, and stability", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab11-text2.html", "title": "Steady state, transient solutions, and stability"}

{"pageid": 251, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@10_complexreplacement/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@10_complexreplacement-tab7", "text": "Our goal is to explain how the amplitude and phase lag of the system response depend on system parameters and the input frequency. To do so, we will use our method of complex replacement and introduce the complex gain.  Let's state the general picture here for reference. We have an LTI system modeled by the differential equation  [mathjax]P(D) x = Q(D) y[/mathjax]|   ---|---      with input signal [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] and system response [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]. The ERF together with complex replacement shows that if [mathjaxinline]y=\\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline], then a particular solution is given by  [mathjax]x_p = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(G(\\omega )e^{i\\omega t}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where  [mathjax]G(\\omega ) = \\frac{Q(i\\omega )}{P(i\\omega )} \\quad \\text{if } P(i\\omega ) \\neq 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ###  Complexification and ERF worked out  The complexified equation is  [mathjax]P(D) z = Q(D) e^{i\\omega t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If [mathjaxinline]P(i\\omega ) \\neq 0[/mathjaxinline], the ERF gives us a particular solution of the form  [mathjax]z_p = \\frac{Q(i\\omega )}{P(i\\omega )}e^{i\\omega t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We can express this as  [mathjax]z_p =G(\\omega ) e^{i\\omega t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Writing the complex gain in polar form, [mathjaxinline]G(\\omega ) = \\left|G(\\omega )\\right| e^{-i\\phi }[/mathjaxinline], we find  [mathjax]z_p =\\left|G(\\omega )\\right| e^{i(\\omega t-\\phi )}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      So the solution to the original ODE is  [mathjax]x_p =\\left|G(\\omega )\\right| \\cos {(\\omega t-\\phi )}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  This form leads directly to the polar form of the sinusoidal function [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline]. Let's see how this works with the equation we used to model the tide in Boston Harbor  [mathjax]\\dot x + kx = k\\cos (\\omega t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Recall that we model the ocean tide by [mathjaxinline]\\cos (\\omega t),[/mathjaxinline] and this is regarded as the input signal. The system response [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is the height of the water in harbor.  We use the method of complex replacement to solve the ODE for the Boston harbor problem    * The complex replacement ODE is   [mathjax]\\dot z + kz = ke^{i\\omega t}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      with input signal [mathjaxinline]e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline].    * One particular response determined by ERF is   [mathjax]z_p = \\frac{Q(i\\omega )}{P(i\\omega )}e^{i\\omega t}=\\frac{k}{i\\omega + k}e^{i\\omega t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---     * The ERF shows that the system response to a complex exponential input signal is a **constant multiple** of that input signal. That constant is the **complex gain** :   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G(\\omega )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\text{complexified system response}}{\\text{complexified system input}}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      In the present case,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G(\\omega )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{k}{i\\omega + k}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      and  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z_p =G(\\omega )e^{i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{k}{i\\omega + k}e^{i\\omega t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This complex number [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline], expressed as a ratio of two functions of time is **constant** . It depends upon the system parameters, of course, but we regard them as fixed. We are interested in how it varies with the input angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline], and write [mathjaxinline]G(\\omega )[/mathjaxinline] to stress that functional dependence.    * To get a particular solution to the original real ODE, take the real part of [mathjaxinline]z_p[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]x_p = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( G(\\omega ) e^{i\\omega t}\\right) = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( \\frac{k}{i\\omega + k}e^{i\\omega t} \\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---     * Now comes the best part of this method. Writing the particular solution in terms of [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline] leads directly to the polar form for [mathjaxinline]x_p[/mathjaxinline]. To find it, write out the polar expression for the complex number [mathjaxinline]G(\\omega )[/mathjaxinline]:   [mathjax]G(\\omega ) = \\left| G(\\omega ) \\right|e^{-i\\phi }.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In our case,  [mathjax]\\left| G(\\omega ) \\right| = \\frac{k}{\\sqrt{\\omega ^2+k^2}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and so  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z_p[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{k}{\\sqrt{\\omega ^2+k^2}}e^{i(\\omega t-\\phi )} \\qquad \\text{and} \\qquad x_p[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{k}{\\sqrt{\\omega ^2+k^2}}\\cos (\\omega t-\\phi ).[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      We have discovered that the gain is given by  [mathjax]\\text{gain} = g(\\omega ) = \\frac{k}{\\sqrt{\\omega ^2+k^2}}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---    **General rule:**   In general, the  [mathjax]\\text{gain} = g(\\omega ) = \\left|G(\\omega ) \\right|[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the  [mathjax]\\text{phase lag} = \\phi = -\\arg G(\\omega ).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In the mathlet, the complex gain is depicted in the Nyquist Plot. The (real) gain and phase lag are depicted in the Bode Plot. Click on the buttons to see these plots in the mathlet.  Observe that the amplitude of the response is different than the amplitude of the input. That ratio of the system response amplitude to the input amplitude is the gain [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline], which is the magnitude of the complex gain [mathjaxinline]g = |G|[/mathjaxinline]. The **phase lag** is [mathjaxinline]\\phi = -\\arg {G}[/mathjaxinline].  For this system,  [mathjax]\\text{gain} = |G| = \\frac{k}{\\left| k+i\\omega \\right|} = \\frac{k}{\\sqrt{k^2 + \\omega ^2}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text{phase lag} = -\\arg G[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\left(\\arg \\frac{k}{k+i\\omega }\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.26)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle - \\arg k + \\arg (k+i\\omega ) = \\arg (k+i\\omega ).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.27)      Note the last equality follows because [mathjaxinline]\\arg k =0[/mathjaxinline] since [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is real and positive. Observe that in general, we have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{complex gain} = G[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{Q(i\\omega )}{P(i\\omega )}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.28)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{phase lag} = -\\arg G[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\arg P(i\\omega ) - \\arg Q(i\\omega ).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.29)  Complex gain, gain, and phase lag for an ODE", "filename": "10_complexreplacement-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Complex gain, gain, and phase lag for an ODE"}

{"pageid": 252, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@11_resonance/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@11_resonance-tab6", "text": "Given any ODE  [mathjax]P(D)x = Q(D)\\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      the complex gain is a complex function given by  [mathjax]G(\\omega ) = \\frac{Q(i\\omega )}{P(i\\omega )} = ge^{-i\\phi } \\quad \\text{(in polar form)}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The gain of the response [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]g= |G(\\omega )|[/mathjaxinline], which can also be thought of as a function of the input sinusoidal frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline]. The phase lag of the response [mathjaxinline]-\\phi =\\arg (G(\\omega ))[/mathjaxinline] can similarly be thought of as a function of [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline].  In engineering, the graph of gain as a function of [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] is called a **Bode plot** (Bode is pronounced Boh-dee), and is usually on a log-log scale. Alternatively, a **Nyquist plot** shows the trajectory of the complex gain [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline] varies. The Bode plots contain, at a glance, all of the information about the resonant response [mathjaxinline]\\omega _r[/mathjaxinline]. By looking at the Bode plot of the amplitude as a function of frequency, we can observe any vertical asymptotes (pure resonant values) or local maxima (resonant values). Sometimes the gain is monotonically decreasing, this is the case of no resonance.  **Note on video:** In the video that follows, the input is the entire right hand side [mathjaxinline]F_0 \\cos (\\omega t)[/mathjaxinline]. The response is [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]. In this video, the _gain_ is called the _amplitude response_.  There is a misspeak in the video where the amplitude response is said to be the complex gain. Instead it is the gain, not the complex gain.  Frequency response", "filename": "11_resonance-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Frequency response"}

Both roots are negative, since [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt{b^2-4mk} < b[/mathjaxinline]. Call them [mathjaxinline]-s_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-s_2[/mathjaxinline].  General real solution: |  [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{a e^{-s_1 t} + b e^{-s_2 t}}}[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]a,b[/mathjaxinline] are real constants.   ---|---      As in all the other damped cases, all solutions tend to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t \\to +\\infty[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 255, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@12_rlc/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@12_rlc-tab2", "text": "A very simple passive AM radio receiver may be modeled by the following circuit.  ![A circuit diagram with a power source of voltage V of t on the left, a resistor labeled R on the top, an inductance coil labeled L on the right, and a capacitor labeled C on the bottom. The current I travels clockwise.](/static/images/RLC.svg)    The power source at left is the antenna, being driven by radio waves. The resistor at top is a speaker. The other components are a capacitor (at bottom) and an inductance coil (at right).  We will model this circuit using the same five-step process as before.    1. **Draw a diagram of the system.** We've already done Step 1!     2. **Identify and give symbols for the parameters and variables of the system.** The diagram shows symbols for four standard electronic components:   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{R}}[/mathjaxinline] |  resistance of the resistor ([mathjaxinline]\\text{ohms}[/mathjaxinline])   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{L}}[/mathjaxinline] |  inductance of the inductor ([mathjaxinline]\\text{henries}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{C}}[/mathjaxinline] |  capacitance of the capacitor ([mathjaxinline]\\text{farads}[/mathjaxinline])   [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{V}}[/mathjaxinline] |  voltage source ([mathjaxinline]\\text{volts}[/mathjaxinline])      The quantities [mathjaxinline]\\, R,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]L,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, C\\,[/mathjaxinline] are constants while the voltage source [mathjaxinline]V[/mathjaxinline] is a function of time.    Next, to understand the diagram above, we need to define an orientation of the circuit; say that current flows clockwise. Since it's a series circuit, the current through any of the wires is the same; write [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{I(t)}}[/mathjaxinline] for it. Then we can say that the power source, at left, produces a voltage **increase** of [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{V(t)}}[/mathjaxinline] volts at time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. This voltage increase may vary with time, and may be negative as well as positive. In fact we'll be especially interested in the case in which it is sinusoidal!    The meaning of each of the other components is specified by how the voltage **decrease** across it is related to the current flowing through it. For us, these relationships **define** the components. The impact of each component is determined by the constant appearing in these relationships.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text{Voltage drop across the }{\\color{blue}{\\text{inductor:}}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{V_L(t)}} =L\\dot I(t).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.49)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Voltage drop across the }{\\color{blue}{\\text{resistor:}}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle {\\color{blue}{V_R(t)}} =RI(t).[/mathjaxinline] | | (5.50)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{Voltage drop across the }{\\color{blue}{\\text{capacitor:}}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C {\\color{blue}{\\dot{V}_C(t)}} = I(t).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (5.51)      These are related by **Kirchhoff's voltage law** : The voltage gain across the power source must equal the sum of the voltage drops across the other components:  [mathjax]V=V_L+V_R+V_C\\, .[/mathjax]|   ---|---     3. **Declare the input signal and the system response.** We will declare the voltage increase [mathjaxinline]V(t)[/mathjaxinline] produced by the power source as the input signal. For system response, we are interested in the loudness of the speaker, which is proportional to the voltage drop across the resistor. So we declare [mathjaxinline]V_R[/mathjaxinline] to be the system response.   This means that we want to set up a differential equation relating [mathjaxinline]V(t)[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]V_R(t)[/mathjaxinline].    4. **Write down a differential equation relating the input signal and the system response, using Newton's \u201c[mathjaxinline]F=ma[/mathjaxinline]\" in the mechanical case or Kirchhoff's laws in the electrical case.** Because [mathjaxinline]\\dot V_C[/mathjaxinline] appears in the definition of a capacitor, it is natural to differentiate Kirchhoff's voltage law, and rewrite in terms of [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline];   [mathjax]\\dot V=\\dot V_L+\\dot V_R+\\dot V_C=L\\ddot I+R\\dot I+(1/C)I\\, .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      To make this into an equation relating the input signal [mathjaxinline]V[/mathjaxinline] to the system response [mathjaxinline]V_R[/mathjaxinline], we just have to remember that [mathjaxinline]V_R=RI[/mathjaxinline]. So multiply through by [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline] and make this substitution, along with its consequences [mathjaxinline]\\dot V_R=R\\dot I[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\ddot V_R=R\\ddot I[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]R\\dot V=L\\ddot V_R+R\\dot V_R+(1/C)V_R\\, .[/mathjax]|   ---|---     5. **Rewrite the equation in standard form.** Input and output are already separated; to put this in standard form we just swap sides:   [mathjax]L\\ddot V_R+R\\dot V_R+(1/C)V_R=R\\dot V\\, .[/mathjax]|   ---|---    We're done. But before we discuss consequences, recall the equation describing the spring/mass/dashpot system driven through the dashpot:  [mathjax]m\\ddot x+b\\dot x+kx=b\\dot y\\, .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      These two equations are formally identical in the way they relate input and system response. This reflects a rough parallel between mechanical and electrical systems, in which  Mechanical| Electrical   ---|---   displacement|  [mathjaxinline]x,y[/mathjaxinline]|  voltage drop, gain| [mathjaxinline]V_R,V[/mathjaxinline]   mass|  [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline]|  inductance| [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline]   damping constant|  [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline]|  resistance| [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline]   spring constant |  [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline]|  1/capacitance| [mathjaxinline]1/C[/mathjaxinline]      Similarly, a harmonic oscillator (undamped) is analogous to a series LC circuit (no resistor).  RLC Circuits", "filename": "12_rlc-tab2-text2.html", "title": "RLC Circuits"}

{"pageid": 256, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab6", "text": "There are three ways to write a sinusoid function of angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\omega[/mathjaxinline]:    * **amplitude-phase form** : [mathjaxinline]A \\cos (\\omega t - \\phi )[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\phi[/mathjaxinline] are real numbers with [mathjaxinline]A \\ge 0[/mathjaxinline]     * **complex form** : [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(c e^{i\\omega t} \\right)[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is a complex number     * **linear combination** : [mathjaxinline]a \\cos \\omega t + b \\sin \\omega t[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are real numbers   Different forms are useful in different contexts, so we'll need to know how to convert between them. The following proposition explains how.  **Proposition 6.1** If constants [mathjaxinline]A,\\omega ,\\phi ,a,b,c[/mathjaxinline] are set so that the equations  [mathjax]\\qquad \\overline{c}=\\, A e^{i\\phi }\\, =\\, a+ bi,\\, \\qquad \\qquad c\\in \\mathbb {C}, \\quad A\\geq 0,\\, a,\\, b,\\, \\phi \\in \\mathbb {R},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      hold, then  [mathjax]\\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(c e^{i\\omega t}\\right)\\, =\\, A\\cos (\\omega t -\\phi )\\, =\\, a\\cos \\omega t+ b\\sin \\omega t,\\qquad \\omega >0\\in \\mathbb {R}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   **Use these key equations to convert between the three forms!**     **Warning:** Don't forget that it is [mathjaxinline]\\overline{c}[/mathjaxinline] and not [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] itself that appears in the key equations. An equivalent form of the key equations (obtained by taking complex conjugates) is  [mathjax]c = Ae^{-i\\phi } = a-bi.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If you ever forget the key equations above, you can do the conversion manually by going through the steps in the proofs below.  **Proofs:**      1. |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(c e^{i\\omega t} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(A e^{-i \\phi } \\, e^{i\\omega t} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |    ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( A e^{i(\\omega t - \\phi )} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = A \\cos (\\omega t - \\phi ).[/mathjaxinline] |  |     2. |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(c e^{i\\omega t} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left( (a-bi) (\\cos \\omega t + i \\sin \\omega t) \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |    ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(a \\cos \\omega t + b \\sin \\omega t + i(\\cdots ) \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = a \\cos \\omega t + b \\sin \\omega t.[/mathjaxinline] |  |     3. Using [mathjaxinline]\\cos (x-y)=\\cos x \\cos y + \\sin x \\sin y,\\,[/mathjaxinline] we have   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A \\cos (\\omega t - \\phi )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = A \\cos \\omega t \\cos \\phi + A \\sin \\omega t \\sin \\phi[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = a \\cos \\omega t + b \\sin \\omega t.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The last step follows from [mathjaxinline]\\, a = A \\cos \\phi \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, b = A \\sin \\phi ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] since [mathjaxinline]A,\\phi[/mathjaxinline] are polar coordinates of [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline].    4. |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a \\cos \\omega t + b \\sin \\omega t[/mathjaxinline] |  |    ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = (a,b) \\cdot (\\cos \\omega t,\\sin \\omega t)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = |(a,b)| \\; |(\\cos \\omega t,\\sin \\omega t)| \\; \\cos \\left(\\text{angle between the vectors } (a,b) \\, \\text{and}\\, (\\cos \\omega t,\\sin \\omega t)\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad \\qquad (\\text{by the geometric interpretation of the dot product)}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = A \\cos (\\omega t - \\phi ).[/mathjaxinline] |  |    Three forms", "filename": "06_sinusoidalfunctions-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Three forms"}

{"pageid": 257, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab3", "text": "**real part**|  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(a+bi) \\, \\colon =\\, a[/mathjaxinline] |   ---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Re\\, }(2-i) = 2[/mathjaxinline]| ![The point 2 minus i is plotted in the complex plane at the coordiante 2 comma negative 1. The real part is indicated by a vertical line segment starting at the coordinate 2 comma 0 and extending downward to the point 2 comma negative 1.](/static/images/complex_plane_realpart.svg)    **imaginary part**|  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Im\\, }(a+bi) \\, \\colon =\\, b[/mathjaxinline] |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Im\\, }(2-i) = -1[/mathjaxinline]| ![The point 2 minus i is plotted in the complex plane at the coordiante 2 comma negative 1. The real part is indicated by a horizontal line segment starting at the coordinate 0 comma negative 1 and extending to the right to the point 2 comma negative 1.](/static/images/complex_plane_complexpart.svg)    **complex conjugate**|  [mathjaxinline]\\overline{a+bi} \\, \\colon =\\, a-bi[/mathjaxinline] |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\overline{2-i} \\, = \\, 2+i[/mathjaxinline]| ![The point 2 minus i is plotted in the complex plane at the coordiante 2 comma negative 1. Its conjugate 2 plus i is plotted at the coordinate 2 comma 1.](/static/images/complex_plane_conjugation.svg)       **Note:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{Im\\, }(a+bi) = b[/mathjaxinline] is a real number. It is not [mathjaxinline]bi[/mathjaxinline].    **Note:** To find the complex conjugate, negate the imaginary component. This reflects the complex number across the real axis.    Complex numbers can be **added** , **subtracted** , **multiplied** , and **divided** (except for division by [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]). Addition, subtraction, and multiplication are defined as for polynomials, except that after multiplication one should simplify by using [mathjaxinline]i^2 = -1[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 3.1**   **addition**|  [mathjaxinline](a+bi)+(c+di) \\, = \\, (a+c)+(b+d)i[/mathjaxinline] |   ---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline](2-2i)+(3+i)\\, =\\, 5-i[/mathjaxinline]| ![Addition in the complex plane. The complex number 2 minus 2 i is added to the number 3 plus i resulting in 5 minus i.](/static/images/complex_addition.svg)    **multiplication by a real number**|  [mathjaxinline]c(a+bi) \\, =\\, (ca)+(cb) i[/mathjaxinline] |   |  [mathjaxinline]3(-2-i) \\, = \\, -6 -3i[/mathjaxinline]| ![Scalar multiplication in the complex plane. Multiplying the number negative 2 minus i by 3 leads to negative 6 minus 3 i.](/static/images/complex_scalarmult.svg)    **multiplication of two complex numbers**|  [mathjaxinline](a+bi)(c+di) \\, = \\, (ac-bd)+(cb+ad)i[/mathjaxinline] |   |  [mathjaxinline](2+3i)(1-5i) = 2-7i - 15i^2 = 17 - 7i[/mathjaxinline] |      The only new operation is that we can now multiply two complex numbers using the rule:  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{ i^2 = -1 }} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      To **divide** [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]w[/mathjaxinline], we \u201crealify\" the denominator by multiplying top and bottom by the complex conjugate of the denominator [mathjaxinline]\\overline{w}/\\overline{w}[/mathjaxinline]. (\u201cRealification\" is the same as rationalizing the denominator since [mathjaxinline]i = \\sqrt{-1}[/mathjaxinline] is a square root.)  **Example 3.2** We have  [mathjax]\\frac{2+3i}{1-5i} = \\frac{2+3i}{1-5i} \\cdot \\frac{1+5i}{1+5i} = \\frac{2+13i+15i^2}{1-25i^2} = \\frac{-13+13i}{26} = -\\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{1}{2} i.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ### Properties of arithmetic on complex numbers  The arithmetic operations on complex numbers satisfy the same properties as for real numbers ([mathjaxinline]zw = wz[/mathjaxinline] etc). The mathematical jargon for this is that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {C}[/mathjaxinline], like [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}[/mathjaxinline], is a **field** .  ###  What properties?    * Closure under addition and multiplication: if [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]w[/mathjaxinline] are complex numbers, so are [mathjaxinline]z+w[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]zw[/mathjaxinline].     * Commutativity of addition and multiplication: [mathjaxinline]z+w=w+z[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]zw=wz[/mathjaxinline].     * Associativity of addition and multiplication: [mathjaxinline]v+(z+w) = (v+z)+w[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]v(zw) = (vz)w[/mathjaxinline].     * Distribution of multiplication over addition: [mathjaxinline]v(z+w) = vz +vw[/mathjaxinline].     * Additive inverses: [mathjaxinline]z+(-z) = 0[/mathjaxinline].     * Multiplicative inverses: [mathjaxinline]z(1/z) = 1[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]z\\neq 0[/mathjaxinline].   [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 3.3** In particular, for any complex number [mathjaxinline]z[/mathjaxinline] and integer [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline], the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline]th **power** [mathjaxinline]z^n[/mathjaxinline] can be defined in the usual way. (We need [mathjaxinline]z \\ne 0[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]n<0[/mathjaxinline].)  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z^3[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\colon =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle zzz,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.1)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z^0[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\colon =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.2)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z^{-3}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\colon =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1/z^3.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.3)      Addition and subtraction of complex numbers has the same geometric interpretation as for vectors in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline]. The same holds for scalar multiplication of a complex number by a real number.  Operations on complex numbers", "filename": "03_existenceanduniquenessintrotocomplex-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Operations on complex numbers"}

{"pageid": 258, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@29_autonomousequations2/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@29_autonomousequations2-tab2", "text": "An **autonomous** ODE is a differential equation that does not explicitly depend on the independent variable. If time is the independent variable, this means that the ODE is time-invariant. We will use time as the independent variable in this lecture.    The standard form for a first order autonomous equation is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dt} = f(y) \\qquad (\\text{instead of }\\, f(t,y))[/mathjaxinline] |  | (6.23)   ---|---|---|---      where the right hand side does not depend on [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. As usual, we write [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}=\\frac{dy}{dt}[/mathjaxinline].  For example, the (nonlinear) equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{y}=y-3y^2[/mathjaxinline] | | (6.24)   ---|---|---|---      is autonomous. We will find out later that this DE models population growth in an environment with limited resources. It is called a _logistic equation_.   **Why is this called autonomous?** In ordinary English, a machine or robot is called autonomous if it operates without human input. A differential equation is called autonomous if its coefficients are not changed over time, such as might happen if a human adjusted a dial on a machine and let it run.  Definitions", "filename": "29_autonomousequations2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Definitions"}

{"pageid": 259, "url": "https://courses.mitxonline.mit.edu/learn/course/course-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@sequential+block@02_solvingafirstorderode/block-v1:MITxT+18.03.1x+2T2023+type@vertical+block@02_solvingafirstorderode-tab13", "text": "We are using Newton Cooling to solve a problem in a crime scene investigation (CSI).  If we write Newton's Law of cooling as  [mathjax]\\frac{dT}{dt} = k\\left(T_e-T\\right),[/mathjax]| (2.66)   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]T\\left(t\\right)[/mathjaxinline] is temperature as a function of time and [mathjaxinline]T_{e}[/mathjaxinline] is the ambient temperature, the solution takes the form  [mathjax]T(t)=T_e+\\left(T_0-T_e\\right)e^{-kt},[/mathjax]| (2.67)   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]T_{0}=T\\left(0\\right)[/mathjaxinline] is the initial temperature.  The equation above does a surprisingly good job of modeling real world temperature changes over time. For example it's used by law enforcement in criminal cases to determine the time of death in a murder case.  We assume that up until a person is murdered the body temperature is constant at [mathjaxinline]37{}^{\\circ }\\text{C}[/mathjaxinline]. After the murder, the body cools, via Newton cooling, to the ambient temperature. When investigators arrive at the scene to find a corpse, one of the first things done is to measure of the core temperature of the body and the ambient temperature. This gives two immediate pieces of information:    1. [mathjaxinline]T(t_1)[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]t_1[/mathjaxinline] is the (unknown) time since the murder, and     2. [mathjaxinline]T_e[/mathjaxinline], the ambient temperature.   We also assume that the starting temperature [mathjaxinline]T_0[/mathjaxinline] is the average human core temperature of [mathjaxinline]37{}^{\\circ }\\text{C}[/mathjaxinline].  **Question 13.1** Is this enough information to determine the time since the murder [mathjaxinline]t_1[/mathjaxinline]?  ###  Answer  No. When we evaluate the solution at time [mathjaxinline]t_1[/mathjaxinline], we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle T(t_1) = T_e+(T_0-T_e)e^{-kt_1}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Every quantity is known except for [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]t_1[/mathjaxinline]. In general, the constant [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] is the conductivity, determined by many factors to do with the heat flow properties of the body and its surroundings. However, we can assume, if the body is not disturbed, that for a given case the value of [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] will not change over time.  If so, we can determine [mathjaxinline]k[/mathjaxinline] by taking a second measurement at a later time [mathjaxinline]t_2[/mathjaxinline].  We can then write a system of equations using our data,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle T(t_1)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = T_e+(T_0-T_e)e^{-kt_1}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle T(t_2)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = T_e+(T_0-T_e)e^{-kt_2}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      We can solve the system above because we know the time difference [mathjaxinline]t_2-t_1[/mathjaxinline].
